<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3:35 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Says Bombing Will Continue  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Despite the release of three American POWs,  
President Clinton said today the U.S.-led NATO campaign against 
Yugoslavia will not end until Slobodan Milosevic ``shows he is 
ready to end the nightmare for the people of Kosovo.'' As Jesse 
Jackson's plane touched down at a nearby Air Force base, returning 
the civil rights leader from his mission to free the three 
soldiers, Clinton thanked him for the free-lance diplomatic effort. 
But he said the United States cannot forget the plight of Kosovo 
refugees. ``When will these people see their home again, with the 
safety and rights Mr. Milosevic has often pledged but never 
delivered?'' Clinton said in a joint news conference with Japanese 
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Warns Japan on Trade  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Bill Clinton warned Japan today to  
reduce its steel imports ``on a consistent basis'' or the United 
States will act to block those imports. During a news conference, 
Clinton said he reiterated to Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi 
that the United States would act to keep Japanese steel out of U.S. 
markets if those imports continue to exceed levels prior to the 
Asian economic crisis. 

</P>
<P>
	Tests Show POWs Have Injuries  
</P>
<P>
	LANDSTUHL, Germany (AP) -- Doctors examining the three U.S.  
soldiers freed yesterday have found injuries that may raise 
questions about their treatment in Yugoslavia. Staff Sgt. Andrew 
Ramirez had two fractured ribs, and Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone 
had a broken nose. But the men enjoyed their first full day of 
freedom today as they were reunited with their families. 

</P>
<P>
	Britain Pledges More Refugee Aid  
</P>
<P>
	BRAZDA, Macedonia (AP) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair said  
today he will double aid for Kosovo Albanians and will not be 
swayed from efforts to ``defeat the policies of ethnic cleansing.'' 
Blair visited Macedonia's largest refugee camp and said Britain 
would increase its refugee aid contributions to $64 million, and 
take in more ethnic Albanians fleeing the southern Yugoslav 
province. More than 170,000 refugees are presently in Macedonia, 
according to U.N. officials. 

</P>
<P>
	Colorado Students Return to Class  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Chatfield High School welcomed students  
today from former rival Columbine High School, who returned to 
class for the first time since a deadly rampage nearly two weeks 
ago. Chatfield students had morning classes. The roughly 2,000 
Columbine students, whose school is still a police crime scene, are 
attending afternoon sessions. Three large banners adorned 
Chatfield, one reading: ``Welcome Columbine.'' The schools are 
about three miles apart. ``They've been really nice, very 
supportive,'' one Columbine student said of the Chatfield students 
and staff. ``I didn't think they would want us here.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Jury Recommends Death for Charles Ng  
</P>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Charles Ng should be put to death for  
murdering 11 people in the mid-1980s, a jury recommended today. The 
recommendation may be accepted by Orange County Superior Court 
Judge John J. Ryan or reduced to life in prison without parole. The 
jury deliberated for 15 hours over three days. Ng showed no 
reaction as the jury's verdict was read and the jurors were somber 
and calm as they were polled individually. Each responded, ``Yes,'' 
when asked if it was his verdict. 

</P>
<P>
	US Scientists Study Malaysia Virus  
</P>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- U.S. scientists are probing a mysterious  
microscopic enemy that has killed more than 100 people in Malaysia 
in seven months. Researchers are baffled about the origin and mode 
of transmission of the rare form of viral encephalitis, which 
spread from pigs to humans. It first surfaced last year near the 
northern city of Ipoh. It has since sickened more than 250 
Malaysians, mostly pig farmers. Soldiers have killed almost 1 
million pigs and some stray dogs to try to curb the virus. Medical 
authorities named the new virus Nipah, after the village where it 
was first isolated. 

</P>
<P>
	Scientists Spot Possible Moon Bases  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Researchers say three sites located near the  
Moon's south pole provide nearly constant sunlight and could be 
ideal for future bases. Having nearly constant light means the 
bases could use solar energy, reducing or eliminating the need for 
other energy sources, according to the team lead by D. Ben J. 
Bussey of the European Space Agency in Noordwijk, Netherlands. The 
temperature at the suggested sites is relatively constant because 
of the steady light and was estimated at about -64 degrees 
Fahrenheit. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 123  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 3 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 123.13 to 10,912.17. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,861-1,058. The Nasdaq was down 27.19 to 
2,515.66. 

</P>
<P>
	Cuban Team To Battle Orioles  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cuba's national baseball team will play the  
Orioles tonight, completing a historic doubleheader that began with 
Baltimore playing in Havana. It is the first game ever between a 
Cuban team and a major league team in the United States. The 
Orioles defeated the Cubans 3-2 in 11 innings on March 28. Cuban 
officials were said to be just as concerned with the possible 
defection of players as the outcome of the game. 
</P>
</TEXT>
