<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Unlikely Comcast Buyer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It looks less likely that Microsoft or America  
Online will take on AT&AMP;T Corp. in the bidding for MediaOne's 
coveted cable systems, a battle that might have been the 
highest-profile duel on Wall Street since RJR Nabisco. 
</P>
<P>
	One thing that's certain: Monday wasn't an encouraging day for  
Comcast, the cable company that's been trumped in its bid to buy 
MediaOne. 
</P>
<P>
	First, MediaOne announced that it has ditched their merger  
agreement in favor of AT&AMP;T's sweeter offer. Then, AOL reportedly 
pulled out as a possible Comcast partner. 
</P>
<P>
	There was no word, meanwhile, from Microsoft, the other company  
examining MediaOne's books, about whether the software giant is 
really intent on helping resurrect the Comcast bid. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL declined to comment Monday on a CNBC report saying it won't  
be joining the fray. The company's chairman, Steve Case, speculated 
last week that his company might be interested working with 
MediaOne. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast, which also had nothing to say Monday, still has until  
Thursday night to cobble together a better offer than AT&AMP;T's. 
</P>
<P>
	But despite fears that AT&AMP;T will dominate the potential online  
and telephone riches to be mined from cable TV wires, analysts were 
growing less optimistic that a competing offer would emerge. For 
one thing, Microsoft and AOL simply may not want to become cable 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think (Comcast's) partners want to be as deeply into  
cable as some people are assuming they do,'' said Tom Vanderslice, 
managing director for media corporate finance at CIBC Oppenheimer. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T, however, has already committed itself to the cable  
business though its purchase of TCI, the nation's second biggest 
system, and an alliance with Time Warner, the biggest. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft and AOL don't have the same incentive. If the goal of  
buying MediaOne is to use cable TV wires for Internet access and 
phone calls, what good does it do to own the nation's fourth 
largest cable company if it means alienating AT&AMP;T, which already 
has access to the two biggest? 
</P>
<P>
	``AT&AMP;T needs MediaOne more than Comcast does and more than  
Microsoft does,'' Thomas Eagan, a cable industry for PaineWebber 
Group, who also expressed doubt that Comcast, Microsoft and AOL 
have enough in common to join forces. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's impossible for all these companies to get along. Although  
they have interests in common, they also have interests that 
compete with each other,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	That's bad news for those who were relishing the thought of  
high-powered struggle among some of the most influential companies 
and executives in corporate America. 
</P>
<P>
	A bidding war pitting AT&AMP;T Chairman C. Michael Armstrong against  
AOL's Case and Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates might have been the 
most captivating on Wall Street since the battle for RJR Nabisco in 
1989 -- or, more recently, the battle that Viacom's Sumner Redstone 
won over QVC's Barry Diller for Paramount in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	If AT&AMP;T wins, the No. 1 long-distance company will also be the  
No. 1 cable company, having access to 60 percent of the U.S. homes 
wired for cable. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, MediaOne said its board of directors felt the AT&AMP;T  
offer, initially valued at $55.8 billion in stock and cash, was a 
``superior proposal'' to Comcast's bid, which was worth about $48 
billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T has structured the deal so that if its share price drops as  
much as 10 percent below $57, the amount paid MediaOne shareholders 
-- equivalent to about $85 a share -- would not decline. 
</P>
<P>
	In Monday's trading on the New York Stock Exchange, MediaOne  
fell $1.93 3/4, or 2.3 percent, to $79.68 3/4 per share, while AT&AMP;T rose 
56 1/4 cents to $51.06 1/4. On the Nasdaq Stock Market, Comcast's class A 
common stock rose $3.06 1/4, or nearly 5 percent, to $65.93 3/4 a share. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
