<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Moscoso Wins Panama Presidency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) -- Mireya Moscoso took her place in  
Panamanian history today, winning election as the nation's first 
woman president and tasting sweet revenge as she beat the son of 
the man who overthrew her husband years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscoso, the widow of an ousted president, will also get to  
preside over another historic moment in her nation's history: the 
handover of the Panama Canal. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscoso's supporters drove through Panama City's streets late  
Sunday after the election, honking and waving her party's yellow, 
red and purple flags. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a fabulous result. A woman who is dedicated to the  
people, in sync with the people, has triumphed. She has won in a 
decisive manner,'' Guillermo Endara, a former Panamanian president 
from Moscoso's Arnulfista Party, told The Associated Press after 
Sunday's vote. 
</P>
<P>
	The presidential election is only the second since U.S. forces  
invaded Panama to eject military strongman Manuel Noriega, who had 
canceled 1989 election results won by Endara. After the invasion, 
Endara assumed the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscoso will take office on Sept. 1 and take control of the  
canal Dec. 31. She beat Martin Torrijos, the son of military 
strongman Gen. Omar Torrijos, who had helped depose Moscoso's late 
husband Arnulfo Arias from the presidency and went on to sign the 
1977 Canal Treaties with the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the accords, the United States must handover control of  
the canal, withdraw the last of its military forces and cede 
control of 40,000 acres surrounding the 85-year-old shipping route. 
</P>
<P>
	The 52-year-old Moscoso, a coffee company owner, will be the  
first woman to lead the nation of 2.8 million. 
</P>
<P>
	With 72 percent of ballots counted, Moscoso had 44 percent of  
the vote to Torrijos' 38 percent. A third candidate, banker Alberto 
Vallarino, who bolted from Moscoso's party after losing the 
nomination to her, won 18 percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't Mireya who won, it was the Panamanian people,'' a  
hoarse Moscoso told supporters at her campaign headquarters Sunday 
night. 
</P>
<P>
	During the campaign, Moscoso promised to keep politics or  
corruption from undermining administration of the canal as well as 
to protect the water basin needed to operate the canal lock system. 
She said canal workers and ship companies would be involved in 
decisions about the 50-mile waterway, which handles an average of 
35 ships a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscoso's late husband was three times Panama's president before  
his final term was cut short in 1968. A year later, the 22-year-old 
Moscoso married the 67-year-old Arias. He died in exile in 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	Moscoso was born to a lower-class family in the provincial town  
of Pedasi, in the southern Azuero Peninsula. Her father, a school 
teacher and principal, died when she was a child. 
</P>
<P>
	During her campaign, Moscoso also pledged to slow the  
privatization of state enterprises initiated by outgoing President 
Ernesto Perez Balladares, who was constitutionally forbidden from 
seeking another term. 
</P>
<P>
	Perez Balladares, one of the first to vote Sunday, said the  
election was evidence that ``democracy is gaining strength'' in 
Panama, which separated from Colombia in 1903. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
