<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Playboy Logo Banned on Web Site </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- A judge ordered an Internet Web site design company  
Monday to stop using the Playboy name and logo on its sites, which 
offered hopes of future money and fame to women who sent in sexy 
videos and photographs. 
</P>
<P>
	Playboy Enterprises International Inc., based in Chicago, had  
filed a federal complaint against Global Site Designs Inc. for 
``usurping and misappropriating (Playboy's) reputation and 
goodwill'' for financial gain. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge Edward B. Davis entered a temporary  
restraining order against Global and two employees on Monday, and 
set another hearing for May 10. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys for Playboy did not return a call for comment; Bob  
Webb, an officer at Global and a defendant in the trademark 
infringement lawsuit, also did not immediately return a call. 
</P>
<P>
	Playboy claimed two sites set up by Global --  
www.playboyonline.net and www.playmatesearch.net -- were rip-offs of 
Playboy's own Web site, www.playboy.com, which prominently displays 
the trademark Playboy Online, and of Playboy's recent search for a 
Playmate for the Year 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people we select, in addition to receiving international  
recognition, will have a chance at great cash and prizes,'' the 
Global sites say under the headings ``Search 4 Sexy'' and $100,000. 
It also promised the winner would drive away in a Stingray 
Corvette. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also alleged Global already has made money off the  
site, by charging $20 for each photograph or video entry. It was 
not known how many people had entered the contest advertised on 
both Global sites. 
</P>
<P>
	Playboy said in its lawsuit that Global had been served a  
cease-and-desist letter on April 22 but ignored it. Even after the 
judge signed the temporary restraining order Monday, both Global 
sites remained online. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
