<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MediaOne To Accept AT&AMP;T Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- MediaOne Group Inc. plans to accept an offer to  
be acquired by AT&AMP;T Corp., abandoning a previous deal with Comcast 
Corp. and setting the stage for a bidding war over the cable 
television company. 
</P>
<P>
	MediaOne said today its board felt the AT&AMP;T offer valued at  
$55.8 billion in stock and cash was a ``superior proposal'' to 
Comcast's bid which was worth about $48 billion in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	But under terms of its deal with Comcast, the Philadelphia-based  
cable company has until Thursday to make a better offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast declined to comment on today's announcement.  
</P>
<P>
	The fight over MediaOne is attracting some of the biggest names  
in the cable, telephone, computer and Internet industries. 
Microsoft Corp. and America Online Inc., for example, may join 
Comcast to help the company beat AT&AMP;T's bid. 
</P>
<P>
	At stake are MediaOne's 5 million U.S. cable TV subscribers and  
8.9 million overseas subscribers, who could be converted into 
lucrative, high-speed Internet subscribers. Cable access to the 
Internet is expected to replace telephone access because 
higher-capacity cable wires can carry voices, video and data 
faster. 
</P>
<P>
	So whoever controls MediaOne could have more control over the  
potential riches of the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	On one side: AT&AMP;T chairman C. Michael Armstong has joined forces  
with the co-founder of Continental Cablevision (which later became 
MediaOne), Amos Hostetter. 
</P>
<P>
	On the opposite side: Comcast president Brian Roberts is trying  
to forge a stronger bid, together or separately, with Microsoft 
Chairman Bill Gates, America Online Chairman Steve Case, and Paul 
Allen, the Microsoft co-founder who left the software company in 
1983 and recently has been building a mini-empire of cable assets. 
</P>
<P>
	If the AT&AMP;T team wins, the No. 1 long-distance company will also  
be the No. 1 cable company, having access to 60 percent of the U.S. 
homes wired for cable. Hostetter would be the nonexecutive chairman 
in charge of cable assets, in effect retaking the helm of his 
former company. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Comcast team wins, Comcast will be a stronger No. 3 in  
the cable business, while America Online, the largest Internet 
service provider, could have guaranteed high-speed Internet links 
to millions of homes. Meanwhile, Microsoft could sell the software 
that makes it all happen. 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, MediaOne confirmed that it had signed confidentiality  
agreements with America Online and Microsoft to allow the two 
companies access to MediaOne's internal financial information as 
part of their review before entering into a possible deal. Several 
press reports said Allen also was interested in saving Comcast's 
bid. 
</P>
<P>
	But with so many industry icons involved, putting a deal  
together may be tricky, one banker said. 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast, Microsoft and AOL ``are in three different businesses  
and have at least two different reasons for wanting to own 
(MediaOne),'' said Tom Vanderslice, managing director for media 
corporate finance at CIBC Oppenheimer. ``They're not on the same 
page. It would have to be a very complex agreement if there was 
going to be a partnership with three very powerful constituents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Comcast, based in Philadelphia, originally offered to use its  
stock to buy MediaOne, but AT&AMP;T trumped that bid with a superior 
cash and stock offer. 
</P>
<P>
	AT&AMP;T's offer, however, lost $1.7 billion of its value last week  
as the company's stock price slid from $59.50 to $50.50 on investor 
concerns that staid Ma Bell was becoming Ma Cable and diluting the 
value of its shares. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the deal, the decline in share price means that  
AT&AMP;T will have to spend $36.55 in cash and $47.975 in stock for 
each MediaOne share, a marked difference from the $30.85 in cash 
and the $56.525 in stock it originally offered. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online could help strengthen Comcast's hand. But with  
only $1.8 billion in cash, AOL is in a better position to lend its 
high-flying stock price. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, which is sitting on $22 billion in cash, could give  
Comcast's side several billion dollars to tempt MediaOne executives 
and shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the Seattle-based software company declined  
comment Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	MediaOne's shares were off 75 cents to $80.75 1/2 in early morning  
trading Monday on the New York Stock Exchange. AT&AMP;T's shares were 
up $1.43 3/4 at $51.93 3/4 on the NYSE. Comcast's class A special common 
stock was up $1.28 1/8 at $66.96 7/8 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
