<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gov't Projects Record Debt Payoff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The government will pay off a record $116  
billion of the $5.5 trillion national debt in the April-June 
quarter, the Treasury Department said in revised projections 
released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	That's higher than the $105 billion to $110 billion payoff  
predicted in February. It would beat the previous record of $97.9 
billion set in April-June 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The department attributed its more optimistic prediction to  
higher-than-expected tax receipts and lower-than-expected 
government spending. 
</P>
<P>
	However, during the January-March quarter, net government  
borrowing was $5.8 billion, reversing what had been a prediction of 
$5 billion in debt reduction. Bigger-than-expected expenses and tax 
refunds were to blame, the department said. 
</P>
<P>
	From October to March, the first quarter of the government's  
fiscal year 1999, net government borrowing was $24 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Once rare, reductions in federal debt are becoming increasingly  
common as a result of the return of annual federal budget surpluses 
after 28 consecutive years of deficit, 1969 through 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clinton administration, in its fiscal 2000 budget, projected  
that the surplus will grow from $69.2 billion in 1998 to $80 
billion in 1999 and $117 billion in 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
