<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Ban on Castro-Covered Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Miami International Airport officials reversed  
their decision to ban a magazine with Fidel Castro on the cover 
after receiving complaints from the mayor and civil liberties 
groups. 
</P>
<P>
	Airport officials banned the June issue of Cigar Aficionado on  
Thursday, saying the cover with Castro was flattering to the 
communist leader. The issue contained a travel guide to Cuba. U.S. 
policy prohibits Americans tourists from traveling to Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The ban was lifted Sunday, and the magazine should be on sale at  
airport newsstands soon, said Gary Dellapa, director of the 
Miami-Dade Aviation Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though we have to be sensitive to the Cuban exile  
community here, in the end, we have to come down on the side of 
what has been the tradition in the United States of freedom of 
expression and freedom of the press,'' Dellapa said. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Civil Liberties Union threatened a lawsuit. The  
magazine's managing editor, Gordon Mott, said that by seeking to 
silence alternative opinions about Cuba, the county was acting like 
Castro's regime. Miami-Dade County Mayor Alex Penelas said the ban 
could constitute censorship. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took personal offense to the false depiction of reality in  
the pictures, images and information in the article,'' Penelas, who 
is of Cuban descent, said in a memo sent Sunday to the county 
manager and aviation officials urging them to lift the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	``However, ... censorship is wrong across the board, even when  
it involves issues and subjects we strongly disapprove of,'' he 
wrote. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
