<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Welcoming Japanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- He threw out the ceremonial first pitch at a  
Cubs game and played tourist on his way to Washington, but visiting 
Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi went the cultural route today 
with a personal tutorial on the history of the Bonsai and a dinner 
graced by piano virtuoso Van Cliburn. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton was playing host to the Japanese leader in a  
pavilion on the White House South Lawn replete with its own garden 
entrance. Shrubbery lined the light jade-colored walls of the 
pavilion, with some greenery even delicately interwoven in the 
chandeliers. 
</P>
<P>
	The two leaders received a tutorial in horticulture earlier in  
the day from Saburo Kato, chairman of the Nippon Bonsai 
Association. In the White House Blue Room, adorned for the occasion 
by Bonsai trees brought in from the National Arboretum, Clinton 
presented Obuchi with a 300-year-old tree as a gift. The pair 
listened attentively as Kato then explained the way the roots grow 
and the trees curve. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were absolutely fascinated by this,'' said White House  
Social Secretary Capricia Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi played high-level tourist over the weekend, throwing the  
first pitch to Sammy Sosa at a Cub's game and ringing the bell to 
close floor trade at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Obuchi was 
just as excited to hear that piano legend Van Cliburn would perform 
for the dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The members of the delegation were ecstatic,'' Marshall said.  
``Prime Minister Obuchi loves the classics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cliburn, who has performed for every president since Harry  
Truman, made his own selections for the evening, which included 
pieces by Chopin, Brahms and Rachmaninoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Author Arthur Golden, who penned the popular ``Memoirs of a  
Geisha,'' and Sidney Poitier were joining more than 300 guests at 
the official dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service, along with the White House staff,  
assisted in creating the garden and floral arrangements around the 
pavilion. Azaleas and lugustrums bedecked the sides of the tent, 
while fresh lilacs and white peonies topped the tables. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar pavilion style set-up welcomed Emperor Akihito of  
Japan when he visited the Clintons nearly five years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Even White House dessert chef Ronald Messnier got in on the  
garden theme, preparing a plate set with a Bonsai tree of green and 
brown chocolate sitting along a bridge over a river of green kiwi 
sauce. 
</P>
<P>
	The dinner menu celebrated the season, with such specialties as  
chilled green pea and zucchini soup. Ginger and black bean 
marinated salmon with jasmine rice and herbed lamb over potatoes 
starred in a dinner filled with unusual combination of vegetables 
and greens. 
</P>
<P>
	White House chef Walter Scheib brought in honshimeji mushrooms,  
a delicate Japanese mushroom for the dinner, and created purees of 
artichoke and eggplant for the dishes. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold base plates and cream china were set on dark celadon table  
cloths with green satin stripes. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
