<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duke Not Ready To Throw in Towel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- David Duke lost again, though he did  
surprisingly well and wasn't ready to write his own political 
obituary. 
</P>
<P>
	After placing third in Saturday's election to replace Bob  
Livingston in Congress, the former Ku Klux Klan grand wizard backed 
off earlier statements that this would probably be his last race. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not ruling anything out for the rest of my life,'' Duke  
told about 150 supporters in his Saturday night concession speech. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Gov. Dave Treen placed first but did not get the majority  
needed for outright victory. State Rep. David Vitter was second and 
will face Treen in a May 29 runoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke, a Republican, was only three percentage points behind  
Vitter, despite having sharpened his racial rhetoric in recent 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke's relatively strong showing was better than pollsters had  
predicted and it surprised Louisiana State University political 
scientist Wayne Parent. 
</P>
<P>
	``One fifth of that district voted for someone who wrote a book  
as radical as `My Awakening,''' Parent noted Sunday, a reference to 
Duke's recently released 700 page autobiography. 
</P>
<P>
	In the book, Duke promotes theories of black people's  
genetically inferior mental abilities, calls for a separate 
homeland for blacks and suggests an ``Aryan'' revolution may be 
needed in the future ``to free our people and secure our 
survival.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Complete but unofficial returns showed Treen with 36,547 votes,  
or 25 percent and Vitter with 31,652 votes, or 22 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke had 27,967 votes, or 19 percent. Ophthalmologist Monica  
Monica, also a Republican, received 22,855 votes, or 16 percent. 
State Rep. Bill Strain, a Democrat, received 16,372 votes, or 11 
percent. Four other candidates split the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Most polls had shown Duke, who served a partial term in the  
state Legislature from 1989-91, with no more than 10 percent 
support. 
</P>
<P>
	It was Duke's best showing since the 1991 governor's race, when  
he displaced faltering incumbent Buddy Roemer, then lost a runoff 
spot against former Gov. Edwin Edwards. 
</P>
<P>
	Duke benefited Saturday from a relatively light turnout of about  
36 percent and a splintered vote among the seven Republicans and 
two Democrats, all conservatives who ran on Louisiana's ``open 
primary'' ballot. His candidacy also was buoyed by the continued 
angst of white middle class voters feeling threatened by 
affirmative action. 
</P>
<P>
	The race was proof of Duke's oft-repeated campaign mantra: ``I  
fly under radar,'' meaning his supporters are reluctant to 
acknowledge their choice to pollsters. 
</P>
<P>
	That was evidenced even by one of those who attended his  
would-be victory party Saturday night in the suburb of Metairie. 
Sharon, who would not give her last name, confessed to some 
discomfort with Duke's KKK history. 
</P>
<P>
	``I do disapprove of that and I think he might still have those  
ties,'' she said. ``I don't entirely trust him, but a lot of the 
things he says I do support.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had run a campaign denouncing affirmative action, welfare  
queens, and the New Orleans school system's removal of George 
Washington's name from a school because he was a former slave 
holder. 
</P>
<P>
	Parent said he doubts Duke will ever make it to Congress.  
However, his strong showing means he will not fade away. ``I do see 
this keeping him around for another day, where he can stay around 
and shake up another race,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
