<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Four Arrested at Cuba-O's Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Four people were arrested for running onto the  
field during the baseball game between the Baltimore Orioles and a 
Cuban all-star team Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The protesters, one juvenile and three adults, were charged with  
trespassing, said Baltimore police spokesman Rob Weinhold. Their 
identities were not released. 
</P>
<P>
	The first three arrests occurred in the middle of the fourth  
inning. The last violation, which occurred with one out in the 
fifth, escalated into a wild scene in center field. 
</P>
<P>
	The protester ran onto the field carrying a sign that said:  
``Freedom -- Strike out against Castro.'' He was tackled and thrown 
to the ground by second base umpire Cesar Valdez, who is from Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Valdez also punched the man before being pulled away by  
Baltimore outfielder B.J. Surhoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Police then restored order and took the man off the field.  
</P>
<P>
	One of the men arrested during the fourth inning was taken away  
almost immediately by security officials. Another was tackled but 
wriggled out of his jacket and ran around the bewildered Cuban 
players before he was caught again. 
</P>
<P>
	As he was led past the Cuban dugout and the Cuban delegation, he  
yelled at them while the Cubans booed and gave him the thumbs-down 
sign. 
</P>
<P>
	At least one of the protesters wore a T-shirt that said ``40  
years is too much,'' in an apparent reference to Fidel Castro's 
leadership of Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Rolando Suarez Cobian, director of Caritas Cubana, a Roman  
Catholic relief agency, said the Cuban delegation was not insulted 
by the protest, but was only interested in watching the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are merely slowing the game down,'' he said. ``This is a  
joke.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
