<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nets sign Muresan for Two Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Gheorghe Muresan, the tallest player in NBA  
history, was back on the court in the nation's capital Monday night 
-- wearing the other team's uniform. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Monday, the New Jersey Nets signed the 7-foot-7 former  
Washington center for the final two games of the season. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm happy to be with a team,'' Muresan said during pregame  
warmups before the Nets-Wizards game at MCI Center. ``It feels 
good. It helps me be more comfortable for next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muresan, who hasn't played in nearly two full seasons due to  
injuries, did not take a physical and isn't expected to play in the 
final two games. The Nets made the move so they would have an 
inside track at signing him for next season. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our interest is sincere,'' said Nets general manager John  
Nash, who used to have the same job with the Wizards. ``I know what 
he can do. The last time he played for the Wizards, they were in 
the playoffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muresan was Washington's second-round pick in 1993. He played  
four seasons for the team, averaging 10.6 points and 6.8 rebounds 
per game. 
</P>
<P>
	But he missed the entire 1997-98 season because of a suspected  
stretched tendon in his right leg. The problem was later diagnosed 
as compressed nerves in his back, requiring surgery that caused him 
to write off this season as well. Muresan also recently sprained 
his left ankle, slowing his rehabilitation. 
</P>
<P>
	By signing him before the end of this season, the Nets can  
re-sign Muresan without salary cap restrictions. Nash said he 
expects serious negotiations to begin Aug. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey concludes its season Wednesday against Milwaukee.  
</P>
</TEXT>
