<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:32:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hi Ho Pimlico, Here Comes Lukas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Bring on the Preakness. Trainer D. Wayne  
Lukas may be ready for another Triple Crown roll. 
</P>
<P>
	The newest member of thoroughbred racing's Hall of Fame won his  
fourth Kentucky Derby on Saturday with Charismatic, giving him 11 
victories in Triple Crown races. 
</P>
<P>
	At Pimlico on May 15, Lukas will try for his fifth Preakness win  
with Charismatic and Cat Thief, who finished third behind Menifee 
in the 125th Derby at Churchill Downs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Charismatic will go forward another notch,'' Lukas  
said Sunday morning. ``I think Charismatic has a few good ones 
left.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, with Chris Antley aboard for the first time, took  
the lead from stablemate Cat Thief with less than a 16th-of-a-mile 
to go, then held off a furious rush by Menifee for a neck victory. 
</P>
<P>
	An early celebration by Antley nearly doomed Charismatic,  
though. 
</P>
<P>
	About three jumps from the finish line, and with Menifee flying  
down the stretch, Antley began shaking his right index finger 
toward the Churchill Downs grandstand. He never saw Menifee coming. 
</P>
<P>
	``He got excited and gave the No. 1 sign,'' Lukas said, able to  
joke about the incident to a large crowd gathered outside his barn. 
``If Menifee had caught us, that finger would be in glass in 
formaldehyde in the barn right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas, whose horses won six Triple Crown races in a row,  
starting with the 1994 Preakness and ending with the 1996 Kentucky 
Derby, said his colts would arrive at Pimlico sometime next week, 
perhaps May 12. 
</P>
<P>
	``Cat Thief fits Baltimore well,'' Lukas said. ``Even in defeat,  
he ran his best race for me. He'll make it interesting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In one of the most bruising Derbys on record, Charismatic weaved  
his way around the track and avoided the bumps and bruises 
sustained by most of the horses -- and jockey Gary Stevens -- in the 
field of 19 3-year-olds. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was the roughest Derby I've ever ridden in,'' Stevens  
said after his 11th-place finish aboard General Challenge, one of 
three horses sent out by Bob Baffert in his quest for an 
unprecedented Derby three-peat. 
</P>
<P>
	``At one point, Charismatic and Prime Timber came together, put  
the squeeze on me, picked me up and carried me about four strides. 
I don't know how I didn't fall.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stevens apparently developed painful stomach cramps during the  
race as he attempted to keep his gelding out of trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	The filly Excellent Meeting, who with General Challenge were  
sent off as the 9-2 favorite by the crowd of 151,051, second 
largest in Derby history, finished fifth after moving up from 15th 
place with a quarter-mile left. Prime Timber, Baffert's other Derby 
entry, was fourth. 
</P>
<P>
	``General Challenge got the worst of it,'' Baffert said. ``It  
looked like he was dragging his right leg, but he's OK today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas' colts will have plenty of company in the 1 3-16th-mile  
Preakness, which has a 14-horse limit compared to the Derby's 20. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the top four Derby finishers -- Charismatic,  
Menifee, Cat Thief and Prime Timber -- Baffert said his other star 
filly Silverbulletday, winner of the Kentucky Oaks, is being 
pointed to the Preakness. Excellent Meeting and General Challenge 
will get a rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Others heading to the Preakness from the Derby field include:  
trainer Nick Zito's duo of Stephen Got Even and Adonis, 14th and 
17th, respectively; Kimberlite Pipe (sixth); and Lemon Drop Kid 
(ninth). 
</P>
<P>
	Possibles include Vicar (18th) and Worldly Manner, who was  
seventh in his first official start as a 3-year-old after only a 
trial race in Dubai. The colt was purchased for $5 million by the 
Maktoum family's Godolphin Racing stable after he won the Del Mar 
Futurity on Sept. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	Non-Derby starters set for the Preakness include Derby Trial  
winner Patience Game, Federico Tessio winner Talks Cheap and 
Millions. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, went off at 31-1  
and returned $64.60 on a $2 win ticket -- third highest in Derby 
history behind Donerail's $184.90 in 1913 and Gallahadion's $72.40 
in 1940. The winner paid $27.80 for place and $14.40 for show. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee returned $8.40 and $5.80, and Cat Thief paid $5.80 to  
show. 
</P>
<P>
	The Derby had a record purse of $1,186,200, with the winner's  
share another record $886,200. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, the most seasoned horse in the field with 15  
starts, gave owners Bob and Beverly Lewis their second Derby 
victory in three years. The Lewises' Silver Charm -- trained by 
Baffert -- won in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the first time I ever rooted for a Lukas horse that last  
50 yards,'' Baffert said. ``When I knew I was out of it, I thought 
Charismatic. It was neat for the Lewises. They were in shock. I had 
fun watching them in the winner's circle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Baffert reloads, Menifee's trainer Elliott Walden ended up  
just like last year -- second. In 1998, his Victory Gallop was 
runner-up to Real Quiet. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now I know what the Buffalo Bills feel like,'' Walden said.  
``But he's a strong horse, he seized the opportunity, turned for 
home and was right there. I thought it was a good race, and we'll 
try again in Baltimore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The filly Three Ring finished last after her saddle slipped at  
the start and she was quickly out of contention. 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas, Baffert and Zito were vying for the unofficial title as  
``Trainer of the Decade,'' since each entered the Derby with two 
wins each in the '90s. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the trainer of the '90s,'' Baffert said. ``He's in the  
Hall of Fame and I'm not. He should have been in there a long time 
ago. Like Gretzky, they should have waived the (eligibility) rule 
and put him right in there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And by the time the Hall of Fame inductions ceremonies take  
place in August at Saratoga, Lukas may have added a few more Triple 
Crown race titles to his resume. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
