<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldier Killed in Lebanon </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TYRE, Lebanon (AP) -- Guerrillas detonated a roadside bomb in  
southern Lebanon on Monday as an Israeli patrol passed, killing one 
soldier and wounding another. 
</P>
<P>
	In an earlier attack, the same Hezbollah guerrilla group wounded  
a pro-Israeli militiaman in the Israeli-occupied zone. 
</P>
<P>
	An Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem said an Israeli soldier  
was killed and another was moderately wounded in the roadside 
bombing, and a militiaman of the South Lebanon Army was slightly 
wounded in a mortar and rocket attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Lebanese officials said the bomb was detonated by remote control  
as Israeli infantrymen were walking along a coastal road at 
Bayadah, a small village in the occupied zone. The village is 12 
miles south of the port of Tyre and about six miles north of the 
Israeli border. 
</P>
<P>
	The Iranian-backed Hezbollah claimed responsibility for the  
explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly an hour earlier, Hezbollah guerrillas fired mortar shells  
and rockets at a militia outpost overlooking the Kfar Tibnit 
crossing between the occupied zone and Lebanese 
government-controlled territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's fatality brought to nine the number of Israeli soldiers  
killed in southern Lebanon this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Mounting casualties have prompted calls in Israel for an end to  
the occupation of southern Lebanon. The calls have increased as 
Israel prepares for general elections on May 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Hezbollah is leading a guerrilla war to oust some 1,500 Israeli  
troops and 2,500 members of the pro-Israel South Lebanon Army 
militia from the occupied zone. 
</P>
<P>
	The 440-square-mile zone was set up by Israel in 1985 in a bid  
to shield its northern towns from cross-border guerrilla attacks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
