<DOCNO> APW19990503.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 09:45:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reggie Lewis Suit Goes to Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- When Boston Celtics captain Reggie Lewis collapsed  
and died while practicing jump shots in 1993, he left a pregnant 
wife, thousands of fans and a team of doctors wondering what went 
wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	In the years since, a battle of reputations has been waged  
between Lewis' family and some of the city's most prominent 
physicians. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, they started fighting it out before a jury.  
</P>
<P>
	Lewis' widow says the doctors who treated her husband in his  
last months misdiagnosed and mistreated a fatal heart condition. 
The doctors contend Lewis used cocaine and lied about it, making an 
accurate diagnosis impossible. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm looking forward to everyone finally hearing the truth  
about Reggie and how his life could have been saved,'' Donna 
Harris-Lewis said in a statement released just before the trial 
began. ``When this is over, I hope and pray justice will finally be 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The malpractice suit pits Harris-Lewis against Dr. Gilbert  
Mudge, who led the specialists, and Drs. Mark Creager and Peter 
Friedman, who were consultants. 
</P>
<P>
	A third consultant, Dr. John Rutherford, recently reached a  
settlement with Harris-Lewis, the terms of which have not been 
disclosed. 
</P>
<P>
	Superior Court Judge Thayer Fremont-Smith imposed a gag order  
and none of the main players in the case would comment publicly. 
</P>
<P>
	But the story of Lewis' death and the finger-pointing that  
followed has played itself out very publicly in a city that loved 
the Celtics and adored the team's brightest star when he died at 
27. 
</P>
<P>
	It all began April 29, 1993, when Lewis collapsed during a  
playoff game against the Charlotte Hornets. A ``Dream Team'' of New 
England Baptist Hospital doctors assembled by the Celtics diagnosed 
him with arrhythmia, a potentially life-threatening, career-ending 
heart condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The grim conclusion led Lewis to seek a second opinion from Dr.  
Mudge, of Brigham and Women's Hospital, one of Boston's most 
respected cardiologists. 
</P>
<P>
	Mudge reported that Lewis suffered from a neurological disorder  
that causes fainting spells. With proper treatment, he said, Lewis 
could return to professional basketball. 
</P>
<P>
	Three months later, on July 27, Lewis died while shooting hoops  
in the off-season at Brandeis University in Waltham. 
</P>
<P>
	The state medical examiner listed the cause of death as  
adenovirus 2, a common virus that could have led to inflammation of 
the heart, widespread scarring of tissue and, ultimately, a fatal 
cardiac arrest. 
</P>
<P>
	Autopsy consultants later said Lewis had ``athlete's heart'' -- a  
left ventricle enlarged from pumping massive amounts of blood. 
Examinations of Lewis' body showed no evidence of cocaine use, 
which could have been an explanation for the scarring. 
</P>
<P>
	Plaintiff attorney Robert Harley said in opening statements that  
Lewis died because his heart arrhythmia was misdiagnosed. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the proper treatment had been given, Reggie Lewis would be  
here today,'' Harley said. ``In all likelihood (he) would be 
playing for the Celtics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Mudge later said that two weeks before Lewis died, he  
acknowledged using cocaine in the past, but said he had stopped. 
The lack of full disclosure early in the treatment process made it 
impossible to make a proper diagnosis, Mudge has claimed. 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis has vehemently denied her husband ever used  
cocaine. In the last several months, the two sides have sparred 
over the right to bring up the alleged drug use at trial. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 21, Fremont-Smith ruled that jurors can hear the  
accusations -- if the doctors' lawyers can prove cocaine was a 
factor in misdiagnosing Lewis. 
</P>
<P>
	``If a person uses cocaine, it can cause structural damage to  
the heart,'' Fremont-Smith said. ``It does become relevant, in my 
mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Harris-Lewis, who still lives in the Boston area with her son,  
7-year-old Reggie Jr., and daughter, 5-year-old Reggiena, has 
maintained she tried to get evidence of alleged drug use excluded 
because the charges only ``sensationalize and hide the true 
issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And she has said she brought the lawsuit only to restore her  
husband's name. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 18:13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Oil Refinery Calls For 200 Layoffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE AMALIE, U.S. Virgin Islands (AP) -- The Hovensa oil  
refinery in the U.S. Virgin Islands will postpone several capital 
and maintenance projects and ask contractors to reduce their work 
force by 200 employees. 
</P>
<P>
	The firm -- a joint venture between Amerada Hess of New York and  
Petroleos de Venezuela -- announced the cuts Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The job furloughs will be ``across the board'' from pipefitters  
to heavy equipment operators, said Alex Moorhead, vice president of 
human resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Moorhead said most of the employees will probably be rehired  
next year, after the company secures a loan to build $500 million 
coker plant to process heavy Venezuelan crude oil. 
</P>
<P>
	Hovensa's refinery on the island of St. Croix employs 900 of its  
own workers and about 1,300 contract workers. 
</P>
<P>
	Commerce officials on the island said they worried retailers and  
the government would be affected as the layoffs began. 
</P>
<P>
	``The people who would have spent, will no longer spend,'' said  
Senate President Hargrave Richards. ``Secondly, the government 
that's already struggling to make ends meet loses income tax 
revenue.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
