<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Colo. Students To Return to Class  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Chatfield High School welcomed students  
today from former rival Columbine High School, who will return to 
class for the first time since a deadly rampage nearly two weeks 
ago. Chatfield students will have morning classes. The roughly 
2,000 Columbine students, whose school is still a police crime 
scene, will attend afternoon sessions. Three large banners adorned 
Chatfield, one reading: ``Welcome Columbine.'' The schools are 
about three miles apart. But some Columbine students are eager to 
return to the scene of the shooting that left 15 people dead. ``I'd 
rather go back to Columbine, just to have closure,'' 18-year-old 
senior Tiffany Typher said. 

</P>
<P>
	Incendiary Device at Neb. School  
</P>
<P>
	PAPILLION, Neb. (AP) -- An incendiary device was found today at a  
school where a written threat was received last week, and a 
15-year-old boy later admitted being responsible for both, 
authorities said. LaVista Junior High was evacuated and the Omaha 
Police bomb squad was called in after the bottle with flammable 
liquid was found in a restroom around 9:15 a.m. The bomb squad 
removed it and detonated it outside the school building. The 
teen-ager was suspended indefinitely and turned over to police. 
Classes were allowed to resume. 

</P>
<P>
	Tests Show POWs Have Injuries  
</P>
<P>
	LANDSTUHL, Germany (AP) -- Tests show the three U.S. soldiers who  
were held captive in Yugoslavia for more than a month may not have 
been treated as well as first thought. Army doctors say the 
soldiers, for the most part, are in good shape, but checkups 
revealed fractured ribs and a broken nose. The men also have scars 
and bruises from their capture. The cause of the injuries wasn't 
revealed. But the soldiers enjoyed their first full day of freedom 
today as they were reunited with their families. 

</P>
<P>
	Allied Planes Said To Hit Bus  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Yugoslav media is reporting that  
allied warplanes mistakenly hit a bus today, causing heavy 
casualties. There was no immediate confirmation from NATO on 
reports of a noontime airstrike on a bus traveling from the western 
Kosovo city of Pec to Rozaje in neighboring Montenegro. A news 
agency claimed that 20 people were killed in the attack. The target 
was thought to have been a nearby police and army checkpoint, the 
Montenegro-based news agency said. The Serb Media Center said the 
bus was full of women and children. 

</P>
<P>
	Case From Starr Probe Tried  
</P>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A jury has been chosen for the only  
criminal trial to result from Kenneth Starr's investigation into 
President Clinton's affair with a former White House intern. Julie 
Hiatt Steele is accused of obstructing that probe. Jurors were 
instructed that the trial will include ``some mention'' of Starr, 
and of Kathleen Willey, who accused the president of making an 
unwanted sexual advance. Ms. Steele at first supported Ms. Willey's 
version of events, but then recanted. 

</P>
<P>
	Court Rejects Volvo Buyers' Appeal  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by  
a group of auto purchasers in Puerto Rico who won, and then lost, a 
$129 million award against Volvo. The court turned away the 
purchasers' attempt to revive their accusations that Volvo 
illegally schemed to overcharge them. About 9,000 individuals and 
corporations who bought Volvos in Puerto Rico between 1983 and 1993 
sued the car manufacturer and the local companies that imported and 
sold the cars. The defendants were accused under the federal 
racketeering law of conspiring to overcharge customers by using a 
company in Liechtenstein to inflate the prices. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Up 153  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just before 2 p.m. EDT, the Dow industrials were  
up 153.77 to 10,942.81. Advancing issues on the New York Stock 
Exchange led decliners 1,843-1,022. The Nasdaq was down 16.56 to 
2,526.29. 

</P>
<P>
	Moehler Suspended in Sandpaper Case  
</P>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Detroit Tigers pitcher Brian Moehler  
was suspended today for 10 days for doctoring baseballs. The 
right-hander was ejected from a game Saturday against Tampa Bay 
when an umpire discovered a piece of sandpaper attached to his 
thumb. Moehler denied scuffing the ball or having sandpaper on his 
thumb. He claimed it was dirt the umpire saw. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  
</P>
</TEXT>
