<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race Deaths Raise Safety Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- It was planned as a big opening act for the  
83rd Indianapolis 500. It turned instead into another deadly 
reminder of the dangers of being a spectator at auto races. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to go on,'' Indy Racing League founder Tony George  
said Sunday as authorities tried to piece together evidence from an 
accident in the VisionAire 500 that killed three spectators in the 
grandstands. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight other spectators were injured, including a 9-year-old girl  
who was in critical condition, when debris from a three-car wreck 
flew into the seats near the exit of the fourth turn at Lowe's 
Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night's race marked the first time in the four-year  
history of the IRL that a second event was scheduled for the month 
of May, which had been reserved exclusively for the circuit's 
marquee race, the Indianapolis 500. IRL officials thought holding a 
race in the cradle of stock-car country would help boost interest 
in their open-wheel series leading up to the May 30 event at Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a business for us,'' George said. ``It's also a sport  
and a livelihood, and our fans who support us would want us to go 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 50,000 people were on hand at the suburban Charlotte  
track when the force of the crash at speeds near 215 mph rocketed a 
wheel and suspension parts over a 15-foot-high catch fence. The 
debris flew into the grandstands and slammed into spectators, some 
of them seated as high as 39 rows above the 1.5-mile, high-banked 
superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	As shrieking spectators sought help, rescue workers converged on  
the bloody area in a scenario eerily similar to that at Michigan 
Speedway last July 26, when three spectators were killed in a Champ 
Car race. The cause in that event also was a broken wheel and 
suspension parts that hurdled a catch fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every once in a while, unfortunately, auto racing raises the  
black side of itself,'' Lowe's Motor Speedway president H.A. 
``Humpy'' Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	George, whose circuit has been fighting to overcome a thin  
schedule and a lack of high-dollar sponsors and big-name drivers, 
said the IRL has made big gains in safety and will keep trying to 
improve. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't plan for every possible scenario,'' he said. ``We  
just do our level best, and unfortunately, sometimes that may not 
be enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Concord police said that because the accident occurred on  
private property and there didn't appear to be any criminal intent 
by anyone, they didn't plan any investigation but would assist if 
asked. Wheeler said the IRL and the speedway planned their own 
probes to augment the efforts of their insurers, ``to make sure 
that this never happens again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to keep wheels from flying off at impact, the  
Formula One circuit this year began requiring its teams to use 
tethers designed to keep the wheels and suspension connected to the 
main body of the machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Such tethers are not required on either Champ Cars or IRL  
machines, in part because some racing authorities think the devices 
may solve one problem while creating another. 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Mehl, executive director of the IRL, said there is concern  
that while tethers may prevent parts from flying off cars and 
hitting fans, they also may put drivers in greater danger because 
the parts could snap back and hit them instead. A tethered wheel 
also could be especially dangerous if it is launched into the 
stands in a slingshot fashion, Mehl said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL wants to study the issue more, Mehl said.  
</P>
<P>
	``You must be very cautious that you don't make regulations that  
will make things worse,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The height of Charlotte's catch fence conforms to industry  
standards, but it was difficult to tell how much higher the fence 
would have had to be to keep the debris from reaching the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have very little direct film of the accident,'' Mehl said.  
</P>
<P>
	The three people killed were Randy D. Pyatte, 21, and Jeff  
Patton, no age available, both of Connelly Springs, and Dexter B. 
Mobley, 41, of Statesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the eight people hospitalized were released by Sunday  
night. The lone exception was Hailey McGee, 9, of Conover, who was 
in critical condition at Carolinas Medical Center in Charlotte with 
bruises to her brain and lungs. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred in the last race of a three-year  
sanctioning agreement between the IRL and the speedway, prompting 
questions about whether the track might not seek to renew its 
agreement with the circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Further clouding the issue is the fact that the Charlotte track  
is owned by Speedway Motorsports Inc., which controls tracks that 
hold five of the 11 races on this year's IRL schedule. Should the 
IRL lose the support of SMI, it could spell serious trouble for the 
fledgling circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wheeler, who in addition to running the Charlotte track also  
serves as SMI's president, said the company remains committed to 
helping the IRL establish itself as a low-cost alternative to the 
Champ Car circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have pretty strong feelings about the IRL,'' he said.  
``They're trying to do the right thing.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 13:54:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Recommends Death for Charles Ng </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- A jury recommended the death penalty  
today for a man convicted of killing 11 people in a sex-and-torture 
spree at a mountain cabin in the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury deliberated 15 hours over three days before announcing  
its verdict in the case against Charles Ng, 38, the subject of one 
of the longest and costliest homicide prosecutions in California 
history. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng showed no reaction as the verdict was read.  
</P>
<P>
	Judge John J. Ryan will decide at Ng's sentencing June 29  
whether to accept the jury's recommendation or order Ng to serve 
life in prison without parole. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng, a former U.S. Marine from Hong Kong, was convicted in  
February of murdering six men, three women and two baby boys in 
1984 and 1985. Prosecutors said the women were imprisoned, tortured 
and raped after being lured to a cabin belonging to Ng's 
accomplice, Leonard Lake. 
</P>
<P>
	Charred human remains and the victims' belongings were found at  
the cabin in the Sierra Nevada foothills 150 miles east of San 
Francisco. Lake, a survivalist, lived there and had built a bunker 
with a prisoner's cell. He killed himself after a shoplifting 
arrest in 1985. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng (pronounced ``ing'') was arrested later that year in Canada,  
where he fought extradition for five years. The trial was 
transferred to Southern California because of pretrial publicity, 
and the case dragged on as Ng hired and fired attorneys. The cost 
of the case has been estimated at $14 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Ng denied killing anyone and said he didn't know Lake planned to  
kill either. But jurors watched graphic videotapes in which Lake 
and Ng were seen tormenting bound women. In one of them, a woman 
pleads for her baby and Ng coldly replies that the baby is 
``sleeping like a rock.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the penalty phase, Ng's parents flew in from Hong Kong and  
tearfully testified that he had been abused as a child. Several 
people also testified about Ng's good character, including former 
Marines, prison guards and a 66-year-old woman who was briefly Ng's 
lover. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Turkish Premier To Form New Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's president chose the incumbent  
premier today to form the country's next government, a development 
sure to please the pro-secular military. 
</P>
<P>
	Premier Bulent Ecevit's Democratic Left Party won the largest  
number of parliament seats -- 136 -- with 22 percent of the vote in 
the April 18 election. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will seek a coalition government which will work in  
harmony,'' Ecevit said after meeting with President Suleyman 
Demirel. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit, 73, needs the support of at least two other parties to  
gain a majority in parliament. The constitution allow 45 days for 
the formation of a new government. If the deadline isn't met, the 
president has the authority to form an interim government and 
declare new elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit is expected to join forces with the far-right Nationalist  
Movement Party, which became the second-largest party in parliament 
with 129 seats. 
</P>
<P>
	The Democratic Left Party and the Nationalist Movement Party  
share similar views on foreign affairs, the country's Kurdish 
rebellion and the economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit is also expected to invite the center-right Motherland  
Party to join a coalition. His party worked successfully with 
Motherland for almost a year in a coalition government until 
shortly before the elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit said he planned to begin talks with party leaders by  
Wednesday after conferring with his own lawmakers Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	He made it clear that he would not ask the Islamic Virtue Party  
to share power. ``It is out of the question for us to make any 
compromises from the country's basic principal of a secular 
republic,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Virtue lost 33 seats to take 111 in the elections. It is opposed  
by the military, which has led a campaign against the Islamic 
movement since its strong showing in the 1995 elections. 
</P>
<P>
	During the swearing-in ceremony on Sunday, one of Virtue's  
female deputies, Merve Kavakci, attempted to take the oath with her 
head covered in Islamic fashion. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit broke off the ceremony in protest and forced the speaker  
to call for a recess. Kavakci left the session without being sworn 
in. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, prosecutor's office launched an inquiry into possible  
charges of inciting hatred based on religious differences, the 
Anatolia news agency said. If tried and convicted, Kavakci could 
receive up to three years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey's establishment sees the scarves as a political statement  
challenging this overwhelmingly Muslim nation's secular system. 
Parliament rules do not specifically ban Islamic headscarves, but 
civil servants are forbidden to wear them. 
</P>
<P>
	Ecevit became a national hero for ordering the invasion of  
Cyprus 25 years ago. The capture of Kurdish rebel leader Abdullah 
Ocalan in February was another victory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:26:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Turkish Premier To Form New Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey's president chose the incumbent  
premier today to form the country's next government, a development 
sure to please the pro-secular military. 
</P>
<P>
	Premier Bulent Ecevit's Democratic Left Party won the largest  
