<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Church Quits Southern Baptist Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- A church that helped found the Southern  
Baptist Convention in 1845 has quit the denomination over its 
fundamentalist stand on such issues as the role of women. 
</P>
<P>
	First Baptist Church of Greenville voted 500-47 Sunday to sever  
its affiliation with the nation's largest Protestant denomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``This vote is about integrity,'' the Rev. Hardy Clemons said in  
a sermon before the vote. ``Our call is to be honest about who we 
are.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First Baptist, with about 2,500 members, had already stopped  
contributing to the convention in 1993. Then, last summer, the 
convention declared that women should ``submit graciously'' to 
their husbands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a struggle with that statement over the submission of  
women,'' said Louise Stanford, a leader of the breakaway movement. 
``But it was really the culmination of 20 years of frustration.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First Baptist also expressed concern about what it considers a  
lack of academic freedom in seminaries controlled by the 
convention. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wish them well,'' said Herb Hollinger, a spokesman for the  
convention in Nashville. ``This church has had unhappiness with us 
for a while.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The convention channels money for missions, publishes Sunday  
school materials and oversees its seminaries but has no direct 
power over local churches. 
</P>
<P>
	It reported more than 15 million members in 1998, a decline of 1  
percent from the previous year. It was the first membership decline 
since 1926. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
