<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gumbel Set To Return to Morning TV </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bryant Gumbel is about to get back into the  
morning television game. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS has called a news conference for Tuesday, where it is  
expected to announce that Gumbel will take over as host of its 
beleagured morning show, network executives speaking on condition 
of anonymity said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The network will also unveil plans to build a new storefront  
studio for ``This Morning'' that will be similar to the Rockefeller 
Center studio used by Gumbel's former employers on NBC's ``Today'' 
show, the sources said. 
</P>
<P>
	Gumbel has largely been off the air since the cancellation of  
his newsmagazine, ``Public Eye with Bryant Gumbel,'' last year. He 
left ``Today'' after 15 years in 1997 to sign a lucrative contract 
with CBS. 
</P>
<P>
	His agent, Ed Hookstratten, did not immediately return a call  
for comment on Monday. CBS would not discuss its news conference 
plans. 
</P>
<P>
	``This Morning'' has run a consistent third in the ratings  
behind ``Today'' and ABC's ``Good Morning America.'' The ABC show 
raised the stakes in the morning news competition earlier this year 
when it brought Charles Gibson and Diane Sawyer in as temporary 
hosts. 
</P>
<P>
	Ratings for ``Today'' blossomed after it began televising from a  
studio with a window to the street in Rockefeller Center. ABC 
subsequently began building a Times Square studio, and CBS hopes to 
use space on Fifth Avenue near Central Park. It is expected to be 
ready in late fall or early winter. 
</P>
<P>
	CBS is not expected to reveal Gumbel's co-host on Tuesday.  
Network executives have reportedly considered ABC's Elizabeth 
Vargas and Deborah Norville, who was briefly Gumbel's partner on 
``Today.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
