<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Blitz of Travel Software </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Never mind the first robin of spring, the annual blitz of travel  
software is a more certain indication that winter is history. 
</P>
<P>
	Ever since CD-ROM drives made storing large amounts of PC data  
cheap and convenient, trip-planning software has blossomed. As 
Americans hit the road, beginning in May, to haul back vacationing 
college students or to take family vacations, the manufacturers 
promise instant, accurate trip planning and bountiful information 
on conveniences and attractions along the way. 
</P>
<P>
	And they will customize a trip for your driving style and  
preferences -- quickest route, preferred route, scenic route. 
Packages range from $30 to $50 and include a GPS interface. 
</P>
<P>
	GPS -- Global Positioning System -- is a series of satellites that  
can send signals telling a hand-held widget where it is on the 
earth, at least within a few score feet. 
</P>
<P>
	When hooked to a laptop computer running the appropriate  
software, it can tell you your position, heading and speed. What it 
can't tell you is why you would want to spend a couple of hundred 
dollars for information that, in most cases, may also be obtained 
by glancing at the speedometer and the highway signs. 
</P>
<P>
	May is when we retrieve our daughter from William and Mary  
college in Williamsburg, Va., about 380 miles south of Summit, 
N.J., a suburb of New York City. Most of the journey is on I-95, 
which, between New York City and Washington, D.C., does double duty 
as the circle of hell used to punish those who sinned in 
automobiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Delorme's AAA Map'n Go version 5.0 had just arrived for review,  
so I installed it to review alternatives. The installation program 
thoughtfully advised a ``typical'' installation requiring 50 
megabytes of hard disk space and keeping the CD-ROM in the drive 
when the program runs. 
</P>
<P>
	The user interface and tutorials are first-rate, as are the  
on-screen and printed maps. And when asked, the software coughed up 
lists of restaurants and lodging that are sortable by price and AAA 
Diamond rating and type. It will also tell you about radio stations 
along the way, including coverage area and format. And it can help 
you find ARMs, law enforcement and auto repair at highway exits. 
</P>
<P>
	All of which is nifty, but the heart of the idea here is  
directions. And those can bear some watching. 
</P>
<P>
	On the I-95 version of the Williamsburg trip, for example, the  
software suggested a route covering 373 miles in six hours and 54 
minutes. But that included cutting across Washington, D.C., on city 
streets -- perfect sense to a computer and insanity if it's anywhere 
near the morning or evening rush. 
</P>
<P>
	The package did better on an alternative route down to Cape May,  
N.J., across on a ferry boat and then south on U.S. 13, Ocean 
Highway, duplicating exactly a route doped out earlier with a road 
atlas and experience. And it correctly pointed out that while the 
slower-paced and very scenic route added only 19 miles when 
compared to the I-95 damnation derby, it also added two hours of 
travel time. 
</P>
<P>
	Bottom line: travel planning packages can be handy, but don't  
rely on them completely. 
</P>
<P>
	System requirement for Delorme's AAA Map'n Go 5.0: Windows  
95/98/NT 4.0 or later on at least a 66-megahertz 486 with eight 
megabytes of RAM (16 is better), CD-ROM drive, SVGA 256-color 
graphics. 
</P>
<P>
	Delorme software is available at computer stores. The estimated  
price is $29. If you live where there are no computer stores, they 
will take your money at (800) 452-5931 or at www.delorme.com. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Questions and comments are welcome. E-mail via the Internet to  
lblasko(at)ap.org, or send regular mail to Larry Blasko, AP, 50 
Rockefeller Plaza, New York, NY 10020. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
