<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National League Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	With an awesome display of pressure pitching, Curt Schilling  
lived up to his end of the pitchers' duel with Kevin Brown. 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling got out of a bases-loaded jam with no outs in the  
sixth inning to protect a one-run lead, and the Philadelphia 
Phillies went on to beat the Los Angeles Dodgers 12-3 Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't give up until they take the ball out of my hand,''  
Schilling said. ``I don't give up, give in, anything. I don't ever 
concede a run, because nothing happens until I throw the ball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With 34,608 fans on their feet in the sixth, Schilling put on an  
overwhelming escape act -- going 3-0 on two hitters with the bases 
loaded but getting three straight outs without giving up a run. 
</P>
<P>
	``It works both ways,'' Schilling said. ``When a crowd is into  
the game, they get me going. It also gets the hitter anxious. 
You've got to feed off that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling (4-1) allowed three runs and six hits, including Todd  
Hundley's two-run homer. He struck out eight and had a season-high 
four walks. 
</P>
<P>
	Brown (2-2) allowed a season-high six runs in six innings and  
could not get out of a bases-loaded jam in the sixth. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just one of those days where nothing went right,'' Brown said.  
</P>
<P>
	In other games it was, Atlanta 5, Cincinnati 3; Milwaukee 6,  
Arizona 5; St. Louis 8, Montreal 7 in 10 innings; New York 2, San 
Francisco 0; Pittsburgh 8, Colorado 5; Chicago 3, San Diego 2; and 
Houston 3, Florida 2. 
</P>
<P>
	At Philadelphia, Doug Glanville homered and drove in three runs  
as the Phillies ended a four-game losing streak, stopped the 
Dodgers' five-game winning streak and denied manager Davey Johnson 
his 1,000th career victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Gary Sheffield led off the sixth with a walk, Raul Mondesi  
singled and Dave Hansen walked, loading the bases with the Phillies 
leading 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	With the count 3-0 on Hundley, Schilling stepped off the mound  
to tie his shoe and went back to work as the crowd stood and 
cheered. 
</P>
<P>
	Hundley fouled off three pitches, then struck out swinging at a  
split-fingered fastball for the first out. 
</P>
<P>
	``Gutsy pitch,'' Phillies manager Terry Francona said. ``He  
probably had to throw it, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Schilling then went 3-0 on Todd Hollandsworth, but got a called  
strike, two foul balls and a swinging strike on a rising fastball 
for the second out. Adrian Beltre hit a smash to Marlon Anderson at 
second to end the inning. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies scored three runs in the bottom half to put the  
game away. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Braves 5, Reds 3    	
</P>
<P>
	At Atlanta, Javy Lopez had a pair of run-scoring doubles as the  
Braves knocked out former teammate Denny Neagle (0-1) after 2 1-3 
innings to win their fifth straight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was hopped up, but that had nothing with the way I pitched.  
It would have been the same way against anybody,'' said Neagle, who 
gave up four runs and seven hits in his shortest start since July 
15, 1994. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerald Williams hit a solo homer and rookie Odalis Perez (1-1)  
got his first regular-season career win. 
</P>
<P>
                      *Brewers 6, Diamondbacks 5    	
</P>
<P>
	At Milwaukee, pinch-hitter Marquis Grissom had a three-run homer  
in the eighth inning off Gregg Olson (0-2), who blew a save for the 
fourth time in eight chances this season. Milwaukee stopped a 
five-game home losing streak. 
</P>
<P>
	Matt Williams homered twice for Arizona, raising his total to a  
league-leading 10. 
</P>
<P>
	David Weathers (2-0) took the loss.  
</P>
<P>
                   *Cardinals 8, Expos 7, 10 innings    	
</P>
<P>
	At Montreal, Fernando Tatis, who hit a three-run homer in the  
first inning, slid home to break a 6-all tie in the 10th. Willie 
McGee then scored on a wild pitch by Ugueth Urbina (2-3). 
</P>
<P>
	Chris Widger homered for the Expos in the bottom of the 10th  
against Juan Acevedo (2-1), who blew his first save in four chances 
when Jose Vidro tied it with a three-run homer. Scott Radinsky got 
his second save. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Mets 2, Giants 0    	
</P>
<P>
	At New York, Dennis Cook (5-0) became the NL's first five-game  
winner when shortstop Ramon Martinez dropped Rickey Henderson's 
eighth-inning fly ball, allowing Matt Franco to score the game's 
first run off John Johnstone (3-1). 
</P>
<P>
	John Olerud followed with an RBI single as the Mets extended  
their winning streak to five. John Franco earned his ninth save. 
</P>
<P>
                        *Pirates 8, Rockies 5    	
</P>
<P>
	At Pittsburgh, Mike Benjamin hit a two-run triple in a four-run  
fifth as Pittsburgh took two of three games from Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	Pirates starter Jason Schmidt (4-1) was knocked out after  
allowing five runs and six hits in five innings. Mike Williams 
pitched the ninth for his fourth save. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Walker hit his sixth homer in 15 at-bats. John Thompson  
(0-3) took the loss. 
</P>
<P>
                          *Cubs 3, Padres 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Chicago, Gary Gaetti hit a go-ahead two-run single in the  
eighth as San Diego was swept for the first time in 74 series. 
</P>
<P>
	Their streak of 73 series without a sweep was the fourth-longest  
this century, and the longest in more than 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodney Myers (2-0) got one out for the win, and Rod Beck earned  
his sixth save. 
</P>
<P>
	Roberto Rivera (1-2) took the loss.  
</P>
<P>
                         *Astros 3, Marlins 2    	
</P>
<P>
	At Miami, Shane Reynolds (5-1) became the first NL starter with  
five wins and Carl Everett drove in two runs as Houston won its 
fourth straight. 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds limited the Marlins to eight hits in 7 2-3 innings.  
Billy Wagner pitched the ninth for his ninth save. 
</P>
<P>
	Alex Fernandez (1-2) had another setback as he tries to come  
back from shoulder surgery. He left in the second with a pulled 
right groin and was put on the disabled list. 
</P>
