<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Twister Kills 10 in Midwest  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A tornado that witnesses said was at least  
a half-mile wide tore through Oklahoma Monday night killing at 
least four people, while a Wichita, Kan., tornado killed at least 
six. In Oklahoma City, power lines popped and debris flew as the 
twister moved along from Chickasha, about 35 miles southwest of 
Oklahoma City, and cut through the heavily populated Oklahoma City 
metro area. TV reports showed hundreds of homes destroyed east of 
Oklahoma City. ``We are getting so many injuries we are just 
tagging them and bringing them in,'' said Shara Findley, a 
spokeswoman for Hillcrest Health Center in Oklahoma City. Midwest 
Regional Medical Center said it was treating at least 100 injured. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: NATO Terms Must Be Met  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- If Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic will  
accept NATO's demands for the withdrawal of his troops, the return 
of refugees and the deployment of an international security force, 
then a halt to NATO bombing is possible, President Clinton said. 
Clinton also said Monday that ``there's plenty to talk about'' 
within the terms set by NATO, which require ``at least the 
beginning of withdrawal of Serb forces.'' After a news conference, 
Clinton conferred with Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, who 
reported on his talks with Milosevic last Friday. Chernomyrdin said 
after the meeting, ``We got closer to a diplomatic solution.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Jackson: Don't Demonize Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson returned from  
Yugoslavia Monday and urged President Clinton to call Slobodan 
Milosevic and release two Yugoslav prisoners of war as a goodwill 
gesture that can lead to peace. A senior administration official 
said there are no plans to meet Jackson's two requests. But Jackson 
said Clinton did not reject his appeal outright, so he remains 
hopeful he president will respond. Jackson gave Clinton the letter 
Jackson received from Milosevic in Belgrade. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Arrested In Colo. Shooting Case  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The attorney for the man arrested on  
suspicion of supplying the Columbine High School gunmen with a 
semiautomatic handgun said his client knew nothing of the impending 
massacre. Mark Manes ``was horrified when it happened,'' said 
attorney Robert Ransome. Manes, 22, of Littleton, was booked for 
investigation of providing a handgun to a minor, a charges that 
carries a maximum six years in prison. He was released on bond. 
Manes, who once attended Columbine, was the first person since the 
April 20 shootings to be arrested on charges of helping Eric 
Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, arm themselves. 

</P>
<P>
	Jordan Working with Arabs, Israel  
</P>
<P>
	AMMAN, Jordan (AP) -- Relations with Israel will not suffer as  
Jordan patches up ties with its Arab neighbors, King Abdullah said 
Tuesday. However, he expressed a thinly veiled impatience with 
Israeli peace policies. The Jordanian monarch made the comments in 
his first television interview since ascending to the throne in 
February after the death of his father, King Hussein. He spoke to 
CNN in a broadcast aired late Monday. Meetings with Israeli 
government officials and goodwill gestures common under Hussein 
have become rare under Abdullah. 

</P>
<P>
	Aetna Selling Plan For Uninsured  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna Inc. is launching a no-frills health  
insurance policy to help the 25 million working Americans who are 
uninsured. The program, called Affordable HealthChoices, will be 
sold to employers who can't afford policies for their workers or 
have had to drop insurance benefits because of higher premiums. 
Aetna's policy will cost as little as $46 per person, or $156 per 
family, per month. The program has been approved in Texas, 
Connecticut and the District of Columbia. Aetna hopes to soon get 
approval by regulators in 25 other states. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Above 11,000  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average sped past  
11,000 Monday. The index rose 225.65 to close at 11,014.69. It took 
just 24 trading days for the Dow to move from 10,000 to 11,000. 
Japan's financial markets were closed Tuesday for Between Day, a 
national holiday. 

</P>
<P>
	Four Arrested at Cuba-O's Game  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Four people were arrested for running onto the  
field during the baseball game between the Baltimore Orioles and a 
Cuban all-star team Monday night. The protesters, who were not 
immediately identified, were charged with trespassing, said 
Baltimore police spokesman Rob Weinhold. The first three arrests 
occurred in the middle of the fourth inning. The last violation, 
which occurred with one out in the fifth, escalated into a wild 
scene in center field. The protester ran onto the field carrying a 
sign that said: ``Freedom -- Strike out against Castro.'' He was 
tackled and thrown to the ground by second base umpire Cesar 
Valdez, who is from Cuba. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by BRADLEY BROOKS  
</P>
</TEXT>
