<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed; Dow Up 62.42 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in late morning, with the Dow  
Jones industrials at record highs amid strength in manufacturers' 
shares, but the Nasdaq composite lower as investors continued to 
sell technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	At 11 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 62.42 at 10,851.46. On Friday the Dow ended 32 points higher to 
close at its fourth consecutive record high, after coming very 
close to 11,000 at one point in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	But broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 3.98 at 1,339.16, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was off 4.63 at 2,538.22. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing shares took off, pushing the Dow higher, after a  
report from the National Association of Purchasing Management 
showed that its index of manufacturing activity declined 1.5 
percentage points, to 52.8 percent, in April. The survey indicated 
the manufacturing sector is expanding, but at a slower rate. 
Analysts had expected the index to rise 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM report followed an earlier report from the Commerce  
Department that showed Americans' personal income rose 0.4 percent 
in March, but their spending kept pace, leaving the nation's 
savings rate at a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	After the purchasing managers' report, bond prices erased early  
losses. The 30-year Treasury bond was up 5/32, yielding 5.66 
percent. The strength in the bond market helped push manufacturing 
stocks higher, said William Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor 
Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got a nice bounce off the (manufacturing) report, which  
came in a little bit weaker than expected,'' Meehan said. ``We're 
being carried by the economically sensitive stocks again. You'd 
have a difficult time moving cyclicals, or anything else, if you 
continued to see the bond market going lower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues led decliners by 4 to 3 on the New York Stock  
Exchange, where volume came to 229.9 million shares, down from 
Friday's pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
