<DOCNO> APW19990503.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 09:45:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Rises 97.65; Nasdaq Falling / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed at midday, with the Dow Jones  
industrials at record highs amid strength in manufacturers' shares, 
but the Nasdaq composite lower as investors continued to sell 
technology issues. 
</P>
<P>
	At noon on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was up  
97.65 at 10,886.69. On Friday the Dow ended 89.34 lower at 
10,789.04, after coming within 39 points of 11,000 and setting 
three record highs last week. The Dow closed at a record 10,878.38 
last Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed today. The Standard &AMP; Poor's  
500 index was up 7.66 at 1,342.84, and the Nasdaq composite index 
was off 3.95 at 2,538.90. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing shares took off, pushing the Dow higher, after a  
report from the National Association of Purchasing Management 
showed that its index of manufacturing activity declined 1.5 
percentage points, to 52.8 percent, in April. The survey indicated 
the manufacturing sector is expanding, but at a slower rate. 
Analysts had expected the index to rise 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	After the purchasing managers' report, bond prices erased early  
losses. The 30-year Treasury bond was up 5/32, yielding 5.66 
percent. The strength in the bond market helped push manufacturing 
stocks higher, said William Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor 
Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got a nice bounce off the (manufacturing) report, which  
came in a little bit weaker than expected,'' Meehan said. ``We're 
being carried by the economically sensitive stocks again. You'd 
have a difficult time moving cyclicals, or anything else, if you 
continued to see the bond market going lower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was led higher by Goodyear, up 2 7/16 at 59 5/8;  
International Paper, up 2 1/4 at 55 5/8; and DuPont, up 2 7/16 at 73 1/8. 
Oil stocks, which have benefitted lately from strong oil prices, 
were higher again today. Dow component Exxon was up 1 13/16 at 84 7/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial shares improved with bond prices. American Express was  
up 1 3/8 at 132 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks, however, were lower, as investors continued  
last week's strategy of taking profits in them. Dow member IBM was 
down 1 7/8 at 207 5/16. Microsoft was down 2 1/8 at 80 3/16 in leading 
volume in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM report followed an earlier report from the Commerce  
Department that showed Americans' personal income rose 0.4 percent 
in March, but their spending kept pace, leaving the nation's 
savings rate at a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues led decliners by 7 to 4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange, where volume came to 341.81 million shares, down from 
Friday's pace of 402.73 million. 

</P>
</TEXT>
