<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:11:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exxon Appeals Valdez $5.3B Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Nearly five years after an Alaska jury awarded  
$5.3 billion in punitive and compensatory damages to those hurt by 
the 1989 Exxon Valdez oil spill, Exxon has yet to pay a single 
dollar to the plaintiffs. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Exxon lawyers told a three-judge panel of the 9th  
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals that the award was not be justified 
considering what it had already paid. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, a federal court jury in Anchorage issued the damages to  
35,000 fishermen, Native Americans, cannery workers and landowners 
for the destruction caused by the spill in Prince William Sound. 
</P>
<P>
	Exxon appealed, contending it had paid enough: $2.2 billion for  
the cleanup, $1 billion to settle state and federal lawsuits and 
$300 million for lost wages to 11,000 fishermen and business 
operators. 
</P>
<P>
	``The grounding of the Exxon Valdez and the resulting oil spill  
was a terrible accident which Exxon deeply regrets,'' John Daum, a 
lawyer for Exxon, told the judges in a standing-room-only 
courtroom. 
</P>
<P>
	But Daum added, ``Piling on an additional $5 billion in damages  
will not achieve anything not already achieved long before this 
trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to contesting the size of the punitive damages,  
Exxon is appealing the way the $287 million compensatory damage 
award was calculated. 
</P>
<P>
	But lawyers for the plaintiffs argue the award is appropriate  
considering the type and amount of damage caused by the oil. They 
also argue it takes an amount as large as $5 billion to punish a 
company as wealthy as Exxon. 
</P>
<P>
	``The punishment fits the crime,'' said Brian O'Neill, a lawyer  
for the plaintiffs. ``It's one year's income for them, and most 
fisheries lost one year's income'' due to the spill. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Charles E. Wiggins questioned whether the plaintiffs had  
even proven Exxon's liability for the spill. O'Neill said the 
company admitted liability in a stipulation to the jury, which made 
it unnecessary to prove it in court. 
</P>
<P>
	``Putting a drinking alcoholic in charge of a supertanker is  
inherently negligent conduct,'' O'Neill said, referring to skipper 
Joseph Hazelwood, who admitting drinking alcohol and leaving the 
bridge the night of the spill. 
</P>
<P>
	On that night, Hazelwood ordered the 984-foot-long tanker to  
shift position to avoid icebergs in Valdez Arm. Hazelwood then went 
below to his cabin, leaving 3rd Mate Gregory Cousins in control of 
the vessel. Cousins ran the vessel onto Bligh Reef just after 
midnight on March 24, 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	The resulting 11 million gallon spill, which remains the  
nation's worst, polluted more than 1,000 miles of Alaska shoreline, 
killed tens of thousands of birds and marine mammals and disrupted 
fishing. 
</P>
<P>
	During the trial, four people testified the accident wouldn't  
have happened if Hazelwood had been on the bridge instead of 
relinquishing it to Cousins, O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A sober Cousins wasn't as good as a drunk Capt. Hazelwood,''  
O'Neill said. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the oil giant also asked the appeals court to order a  
new trial, alleging one juror was intimidated and threatened by 
other jurors and the court bailiff during the 1994 trial in 
Anchorage. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge H. Russel Holland previously rejected that  
allegation, writing in his ruling that the juror's memory was not 
credible. The plaintiffs want the appeals court to affirm Holland's 
ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The plaintiffs argued that bailiff Don Warrick was joking when  
he brandished his gun to juror Doug Graham, took out a bullet and 
suggested Graham put another juror ``out of her misery.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Graham said he didn't take the comment seriously, O'Neill said.  
</P>
<P>
	Warrick initially lied about the incident, but later admitted it  
to U.S. marshals and was fired from his job. 
</P>
<P>
	A third appeal filed by Exxon involved the issue of whether a  
group of Seattle seafood processors known as the ``Seattle Seven'' 
is entitled to a share of the $5 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Prior to the start of the 1994 trial, the processors reached a  
$70 million settlement with Exxon. The confidential settlement 
agreement required the seafood processors to pursue their share of 
any punitive damages at trial and then turn the proceeds over to 
Exxon. 
</P>
<P>
	The Seattle Seven's share comes to more than $700 million. The  
plaintiffs contend Exxon would hardly be punished if it could pay a 
share of the damages to itself. 
</P>
<P>
	Holland agreed in 1996 and rejected Exxon's claim to the money,  
calling the maneuver an ``astonishing ruse.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A ruling by the appeals panel was expected to take at least six  
months. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
