<HEADLINE> 7 Die in Church Bus Crash in N.M. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARTESIA, N.M. (AP) -- Six girls traveling home after a weekend  
retreat with fellow churchgoers were killed when a camper broke 
away from a pickup truck and struck the bus in which they were 
riding. 
</P>
<P>
	A man driving a pickup truck behind the church bus also was  
killed in Sunday's accident on mountainous terrain on U.S. Route 82 
west of Artesia. 
</P>
<P>
	The westbound pickup truck swerved and a section of the camper  
being towed by the pickup ``tore along the side of the bus,'' state 
police Capt. John Balderston said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It cut through the left passenger side of the bus; it appears  
that the children that were seated next to the windows were the 
ones that were the victims,'' Balderston said. The girls, ages 
about 12 to 17, were killed instantly. 
</P>
<P>
	Balderston said it wasn't known why the pickup truck swerved,  
but investigators were interviewing the driver, a 75-year-old man. 
</P>
<P>
	The pin used to secure the trailer hitch to the truck was  
broken, Balderston said, but he couldn't say whether the break 
caused the accident or was a result. 
</P>
<P>
	High wind might have been a factor in the crash, too, Balderston  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The young victims were among about 80 people from Green Lawn  
Church of Christ in Lubbock, Texas, who had spent the weekend at 
Pine Springs Summer Camp, an isolated, mountainous retreat in 
Lincoln National Forest. The camp near Mayhill is about 150 miles 
southwest of Lubbock. 
</P>
<P>
	Back at Green Lawn Church, hundreds of teen-agers and parents  
sobbed, held hands and sang hymns after word spread of the 
accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``What do you do in the midst of a tragedy like this?'' minister  
Dale Mannon said in a prayer. ``There is nothing pretty about 
death. We don't pretend to know why these things happen. But we do 
know that you, Father, know what it is like to watch a child die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The dead girls were identified as Talitha Beaman, 17; Sara  
English, 15; Sara Johnson, 13; Megan Flynn, 15; Heather Dauman; and 
Ashton Qutby. The last two girls' ages were not available. 
</P>
<P>
	The victim in the third vehicle was identified today as William  
Libby, 60, of Albuquerque. 
</P>
<P>
	Two people were in serious condition today at University  
Hospital in Albuquerque. Three others were in stable condition and 
a fourth was awaiting discharge today from an Alamogordo hospital. 
Twenty-one others people were treated and released. 
</P>
<P>
	Congregant Sarah Johnson said her daughter was on the trip but  
escaped injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every one of those kids is mine, just as if I had them  
myself,'' she said. ``There are no words .... Right now, we just 
need to pray. We know that they are in a better place and it's up 
to us to be there for the parents.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Johnson is not related to victim Sara Johnson.  
</P>
</TEXT>
