<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Corn, Soybeans Gain; Wheat Sinks / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Corn and soybean futures advanced Monday on the  
Chicago Board of Trade, while wheat retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn and soybeans gained after private forecasters said a wet  
weather system heading for Midwest growing regions could linger 
through part of next week, significantly slowing farmer fieldwork. 
</P>
<P>
	The rally was muted, however, amid continued conflicting views  
on the extent of the rain system, including how much precipitation 
will fall and over how large an area. Prices also were pressured 
amid expectations the government would report improved planting 
occurred in the past week as dry weather returned to growing areas 
during the latter part of last week and into the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by expectations a crop tour of  
winter wheat growing regions this week will find above-average 
yields that could lead to increased estimates for the early summer 
harvest. A bumper crop would come at a time when there still is 
plenty of last year's crop in storage amid a period of relatively 
weak export demand. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 4 cents to $2.64 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1 3/4 cents to $2.20 1/2 a bushel; July oats fell 1/2 cent to 
$1.17 3/4 a bushel; July soybeans rose 2 3/4 cents to $4.89 1/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Meat and livestock futures were mostly lower on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle fell .10 cent to 62.72 cents a pound; May  
feeder cattle rose .02 cent to 71.17 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .50 cent to 58.57 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .17 
cent to 59.17 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
