<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Soldiers Celebrate Their Freedom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RAMSTEIN, Germany (AP) -- Three U.S. servicemen celebrated their  
freedom today after more than a month in Yugoslav custody, happily 
awaiting the arrival of their families at a U.S. base in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers spent Sunday evening calling families and friends,  
watching television and relaxing before having a good night's sleep 
at Landstuhl Regional Medical Center, a U.S. military hospital, 
chief of clinical services Col. Mack Blanton said today. 
</P>
<P>
	``They rested, woke up this morning very well and are in good  
spirits, eager to be reunited with their families,'' said Lt. Col. 
Sharon DeRubo, chief of clinical nursing at Landstuhl. 
</P>
<P>
	Blanton said initial tests showed the soldiers were ``reasonably  
healthy'' and had ``only minor injuries in their captivity from 
handcuffs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The soldiers were flown from Croatia to a U.S. Air Force base in  
Ramstein on Sunday, where they were greeted with salutes from their 
Army buddies and wild cheers from a flag-waving crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Their arrival capped an emotional, daylong journey by land and  
air from Yugoslavia's capital with civil rights leader Jesse 
Jackson, who had successfully appealed to Yugoslav President 
Slobodan Milosevic to release them. 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson hoped President Clinton would reciprocate by offering a  
respite from airstrikes, now in their sixth week. However, NATO 
refused to reward the gesture and the alliance continued to pound 
Yugoslavia, delivering more than 600 bombing run Sunday over a 
24-hour period. 
</P>
<P>
	The freed soldiers, dressed in Army fatigues, were exuberant and  
appeared healthy, standing tall and walking briskly. But they still 
showed signs of the cuts and bruises they suffered when captured 
March 31 on a patrol mission along the Macedonia-Yugoslav border. 
</P>
<P>
	Family members were arriving at Landstuhl later today to reunite  
with their loved ones. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a great relief to be free,'' Staff Sgt. Christopher J.  
Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich., said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were treated very well,'' Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of  
Los Angeles. ``We're doing good, we're healthy. As you can see 
we're very happy. Mostly happy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	First medical tests showed Ramirez had ``a little bit of  
swelling on his right lower leg'' that required further X-rays, 
Blanton told a news conference today. He also had a small cut on 
the top of his head that was stitched while he was in captivity. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone underwent a CAT scan to check for internal damage, but  
``in general his condition is good,'' said Blanton. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Spec. Steven Gonzales, 22, of Huntsville, Texas,  
``turned out fine'' in initial checkups and has no further medical 
tests scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
	DeRubo put it more directly. ``They look good, they feel good,''  
she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the three soldiers ``took excellent care of  
themselves'' while in captivity, doing pushups and sit-ups to stay 
fit and drinking and eating ``at the right time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson, who accompanied the soldiers out of Yugoslavia, flew  
onto Washington today to meet with Clinton and deliver a letter 
from Milosevic with the Yugoslav president's proposals to resolve 
the crisis over Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Clinton expressed his gratitude to Jackson and  
said he was pleased at the soldiers' release. ``All of America is 
anticipating their safe return.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton did not immediately comment on the proposal to meet with  
Milosevic. 
</P>
<P>
	``As we welcome our soldiers home, our thoughts also turn to the  
over 1 million Kosovars who are unable to go home because of the 
policies of the regime in Belgrade,'' Clinton said in a White House 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, Ramirez, and had left the Army's 1st Infantry division  
base in Schweinfurt, 50 miles southwest of Frankfurt, in March for 
Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	They were taken captive while patrolling the Yugoslav-Macedonia  
border as part of a peacekeeping mission, seven days after NATO 
launched its bombing campaign in Yugoslavia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
