<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 05:25:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government Photos Capture Century </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Through 100 years of upheaval and creation,  
the handheld camera has recorded the contrasting moods of the 20th 
century in billions of photographs, from generation-spanning family 
albums to images of indelible graphic power. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government has been taking and collecting  
photographs from the century's beginning, using the camera to 
document, investigate, advocate, promote, propagandize and just 
show the look and feel of everyday America. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Archives holds more than 8 million photographic  
prints, negatives and slides and transparencies in one gigantic 
American family album. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, curators have culled the collection for the best, choosing  
190 images to reflect the energy, achievement, tragedy and humor of 
the century as seen through the purposes of government. The show, 
``Picturing the Century,'' runs through July 4, 2001 at the 
archives. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last half of the 19th century photography was important,  
but bulky and slow. American photographers preserved Abraham 
Lincoln's weary profile, showed the horror of Civil War 
battlefields and convinced Congress with their images that the 
natural glories of the American West were treasures worth 
preserving. 
</P>
<P>
	Everything sped up in the 20th century, and the government's use  
of photography was no exception. There was fast film, fast 
developing, small cameras and, towards century's end, digital 
photography to select and transmit images by computer almost as 
fast as snapping a shutter. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the photographers in the archives show are unknown,  
including those who recorded the Easter Parade on Fifth Avenue in 
New York in 1900 or hardscrabble Steadman Avenue in Nome, Alaska, 
in July of that year with prospectors standing near the Horse Shoe 
Cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	Some are famous:  
</P>
<P>
	--Lewis Hine, documenting child labor in American industry  
recording or, in the signature image of the show, a powerhouse 
mechanic working with an outsized wrench, the arch of his back 
mirroring the curve of the steam pump he is working on. 
</P>
<P>
	--Dorthea Lange, recording the bread lines, work camps and  
migrants of the Great Depression. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ansel Adams, whose photograph of the silver curve of the Snake  
River below the Grand Tetons is in the archives because the 
Interior Department commissioned Adams in 1941 to install a series 
of photo murals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Photographs are created deliberately; they seek to convey  
meaning and suggest an interpretation of a particular moment in 
history,'' says Bruce I. Bustard, the National Archives curator who 
assembled the show. 
</P>
<P>
	``Old pictures are time machines,'' he wrote in the catalog of  
the show. ``They allow us to look back in history, freeze a moment 
in time, and imagine ourselves as part of the past. ... Looking at 
historic photographs helps us imagine what it was like when the 
first airplane took off, when a landing craft ramp fell open on 
D-Day, or when the first human being stepped onto the moon.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The images collide and meld.  
</P>
<P>
	Men shower in a municipal bath in New York City in 1903. A  
mailman delivers in rural Maine in 1930. Demonstrators, decades 
apart, demand votes for women and an end to the war in Vietnam. A 
World War II Flying Fortress disintegrates in flight over Germany. 
Nine black World War I soldiers display their French medals for 
gallantry in action. San Francisco lies in earthquake ruins in 
1906. A rugged U.S. Mail Service pilot suits up for the winter of 
1926. A long line of tourists slide the snowy slopes in Mount 
Rainier National Park in 1917. 
</P>
<P>
	Presidential libraries supplied several of the images: Harry  
Truman striding purposefully near the Washington Monument; Franklin 
Roosevelt in a wheelchair; John Kennedy playing with his son, John 
Jr., in a beached rowboat; Lyndon Johnson being sworn in aboard Air 
Force One after Kennedy's assassination, Richard Nixon preparing to 
board a helicopter to leave the White House for the last time. 
</P>
<P>
	White House photographer Jack Kightlinger captured Johnson, his  
head cradled on his right arm, his face hidden, his shoulders 
slumped and sagging, listening to his son-in-law's tape-recorded 
voice recounting his experiences in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kightlinger's photograph seems to perfectly capture Johnson's  
political agony,'' the catalog says. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	EDITOR'S NOTE: Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on Congress, the  
White House and Washington's history for more than 30 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
