<HEADLINE> Do We Thrive Today by New Rules? / Commentary  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                        *AP Business Analyst    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- It was only a short while ago that the economic  
world was much, much different from what it is today. In fact, no 
more than perhaps five or six years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	It was all very understandable too. Everyone knew that inflation  
was a constant threat and that there was a natural level of 
unemployment, perhaps 6 percent, below which inflation would ignite 
due to labor shortages. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve chief Alan Greenspan was among those who worried  
most about the inflation threat. He and insightful economists at 
big-name schools could even explain the threat by means of 
equations. 
</P>
<P>
	It went like this:  
</P>
<P>
	You can push the jobless rate to a level beyond which it just  
doesn't pay off. That is, a paucity of job seekers means the least 
productive workers hold jobs, and skilled workers demand more 
money. 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, output per staff-hour slows and may even turn  
negative. Costs rise and so do prices. Rising prices lead to higher 
interest rates. And then to layoffs. And then recession. 
</P>
<P>
	That was then. Not today. Today, we have low unemployment, low  
costs, low prices and no great threat of inflation or recession. 
And, you might add, growing disrespect for the old notions. 
</P>
<P>
	Do these curious commandments from the early 1990s that were  
supposed to be good for all time -- do they apply anymore? 
</P>
<P>
	Ah, that's the question. Really, lots of questions. For example,  
can we maintain a savings rate below 5 percent without running into 
trouble? Well, consider: We now have a zero rate. Worse, below 
zero. 
</P>
<P>
	Below zero means we not only spend our paychecks, but borrow to  
spend more. And we defend the new way; learned theses explain that 
we know we'll earn more next year so why not spend it today? 
</P>
<P>
	Not long ago we believed that federal budget deficits were  
perhaps eternal. We had reason to think so after 25 straight years 
that the government spent more than its revenues. But now we have 
surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	What happened? Lots of ex-post facto explanations are offered,  
but almost noone anticipated surpluses even a year before they 
arrived. And the reasons why they developed are still disputed. 
</P>
<P>
	The trade imbalance continues. A few years ago we were warned  
that imbalances could bring down the economy. Now, creative 
academics defend the swell of cheaper imports as anti-inflationary. 
</P>
<P>
	So much has changed in a few years. Economic theory, financial  
behavior, shopping habits, workplace goals, the stock market, 
communications, entertainment, college courses, sports, values..... 
</P>
<P>
	Okay, economists, you who were so quick and smart with your  
answers just a decade ago: Let's see you mold this into one 
credible, understandable theory that will last into the new 
millennium. 
</P>
<P>
	Or at least tell us: Are we living well with reality? Is our  
behavior aberrant? Are the old rules of the game about to come down 
on our heads with a wallop that will send us back to the past? 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
