<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Swiss Group Wins Philippine Bidding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- A consortium including Glencore  
International AG of Switzerland won the bid Monday for Philippine 
Associated Smelting and Refining Corp., which is being privatized 
by the government. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale of PASAR, one of the largest copper smelting plants in  
Asia, marks the first stab at privatization by the administration 
of Philippine President Joseph Estrada. 
</P>
<P>
	Glencore is a global trading and marketing concern with  
interests in various commodities. It came up with the highest bid 
of 3.232 billion pesos ($85 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Glencore, through its subsidiary Copper Smelting Investments  
Ltd., holds a 40 percent stake in the winning consortium. A 
Philippine group, led by former Agriculture Secretary Carlos 
Dominguez, holds a 60 percent stake. Dominguez is chairman of 
Copper Smelting Investments. 
</P>
<P>
	The Glencore group bested three other bidders, the government  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite its dominance in copper smelting, PASAR has not had  
sufficient capital to maintain its 16-year-old plant. 
</P>
<P>
	The 37.8 percent government stake in PASAR being sold represents  
90 percent of the government's holding in the copper smelting 
company. The rest will be sold to smaller investors in an initial 
public offering. 
</P>
</TEXT>
