<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Texas AG Probed in Tobacco Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Investigators are looking into whether former  
Texas Attorney General Dan Morales improperly tried to help a 
lawyer friend win a half-billion-dollar share of the state's 
tobacco settlement, The Associated Press has learned. 
</P>
<P>
	Morales' successor, Attorney General John Cornyn, said both his  
office and the FBI are investigating Morales' actions regarding 
Houston attorney Marc D. Murr, a 20-year Morales friend and former 
colleague at a law firm. 
</P>
<P>
	Murr originally asked for $520 million of the $17.3 billion  
settlement, even though other attorneys who worked on the case say 
Murr did little to help. A state arbitration board cut the amount 
to $260 million, but that figure is being disputed, too. 
</P>
<P>
	Two sources close to the attorney general's office said the FBI  
is examining computer files and paper documents to determine 
whether Morales backdated four contracts and letters in an attempt 
to make it appear that Murr was involved in the case longer than he 
really was. 
</P>
<P>
	No one has alleged that Morales benefited financially. And  
Morales has denied any wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think that once all of the facts and circumstances have been  
reviewed, there's no doubt in my mind the conclusion will be 
evident that no unethical or improper activity on the part of any 
of the lawyers occurred, including my office,'' Morales told the 
AP. 
</P>
<P>
	Murr did not return calls for comment but has said he spent  
2,000 hours working with Morales on strategy and the settlement. 
His attorney, Roy G. Minton, said that he has cooperated with 
Cornyn's investigation but that the FBI has never approached him. 
</P>
<P>
	The FBI did not return telephone messages.  
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge David Folsom in Texarkana scheduled a  
hearing for Thursday to look into the matter. 
</P>
<P>
	Morales led Texas' effort to sue the tobacco industry in 1996  
for reimbursement of Medicaid funds spent on Texans' 
smoking-related illnesses. The tobacco companies settled with Texas 
in January. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal with Texas was separate from the $206 billion  
settlement the tobacco industry reached with 46 states in November. 
</P>
<P>
	Five private attorneys who helped represent the state in the  
Texas settlement were eventually awarded a total of $3.3 billion in 
fees. 
</P>
<P>
	Murr asked for $520 million for his role as an adviser to  
Morales. Last fall, a state arbitration panel approved $260 million 
for Murr even though some people involved in the tobacco lawsuit 
said they had never even heard his name. 
</P>
<P>
	A national arbitration panel set up to handle lawyer fee  
requests nationwide recommended in December that Murr get only $1 
million. 
</P>
<P>
	``People act as though this would be OK as long as Dan Morales  
doesn't get any money out of it,'' said Pete Schenkkan, a lawyer 
who represents six legislators trying to block payment to Murr. 
``Two hundred and sixty million for doing nothing, without proving 
you did anything, on the say-so of your personal friend, is 
outrageous.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The amount Murr gets is subject to approval by Folsom, who said  
he wants to know why Morales and Murr chose all three retired 
judges who recommended the $260 million. Murr's attorney said there 
was nothing wrong in doing that. 
</P>
<P>
	Morales, a Democrat, said the state investigation led by Cornyn,  
a Republican, is politically motivated against plaintiffs' 
attorneys like Murr. 
</P>
<P>
	Murr made no courtroom appearances and his name was on none of  
the hundreds of court documents filed before the lawsuit was 
settled. But Morales said Murr's assistance was ``critical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The pair met two decades ago while both were at Houston's  
Bracewell &AMP; Patterson law firm. Murr also represented Morales in a 
1990 libel suit. 
</P>
<P>
	Morales decided in 1997 not to run for a third term. He had said  
he would go into investment banking, but has not announced he has 
joined any firms. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
