<DOCNO> APW19990503.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tough Guy John Elway Walks Away </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	He didn't look nearly as tough as we remembered him.  
</P>
<P>
	Maybe it was because John Elway was wearing a suit instead of a  
mud-stained jersey. Or because he was peering into television 
lights at a roomful of reporters, instead of into driving snow with 
a clock ticking down somewhere in the background and a toothless 
linebacker snarling back at him. 
</P>
<P>
	But maybe, just maybe, it was because Elway, after 16 years of  
absorbing beatings, isn't as tough as we remember him. That was his 
take on retirement, too. You just hope he knows there is no shame 
in that. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't do it physically anymore,'' Elway said, ``and that's  
really hard for me to say.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's funny the things we learn about our athletes when the games  
are no longer in front of them. 
</P>
<P>
	At the January news conference in Chicago making his retirement  
official, Michael Jordan showed flashes of both the predator's calm 
and the contrary nature that made him the deadliest closer sport 
had ever seen. 
</P>
<P>
	Jordan's words said he was gone. But he took great pains to let  
everybody know he could change out of his suit any time the mood 
struck him and still own any basketball court he stepped on. 
</P>
<P>
	Weeks later, Wayne Gretzky unlaced his skates for the last time  
and sat down on a podium in New York still wearing his uniform. The 
night before, he had called a half-dozen reporters who covered him 
for most of his career to say thanks. Someone asked at the news 
conference following the game whether he was finding it difficult 
to take his jersey off. 
</P>
<P>
	The question assumed Gretzky felt he hadn't played out the  
string. That wasn't it at all. It was just the child prodigy aiming 
to please his audience one final time. ``They told me,'' Gretzky 
explained through an embarrassed grin, ``that you guys were 
waiting.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday in Denver, Elway fought harder to keep his composure  
than he ever had to in a football game. Every time he said he was 
ready to turn the corner, another memory would pounce and the tears 
would well up at the corner of his eyes. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Jordan, he couldn't come back without an unacceptable  
drop in the level of his play. But unlike Gretzky, he didn't seem 
to be at peace with his decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never want to stop competing,'' he said. ``I just can't  
compete at this level anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If the stories are true, the organization Elway rewarded with  
his loyalty and countless sacrifices was willing to pay him back in 
kind. The Broncos kept his spot open until he told them ``no'' more 
than once. They left the team as is. Owner Pat Bowlen didn't 
rearrange the furniture by making trades or mortgage the future to 
draft any of the handful of promising quarterbacks dispersed in 
this year's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Mike Shanahan even offered to let Elway skip training  
camp. And the first half of the season, if that was what it was 
going to take. Elway told them no again: ``I'm all in ... or I'm 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is out, finally, because of chronic problems with his left  
knee, which first surfaced his senior year at Granada Hills High in 
1978. He underwent surgery that year to repair torn cartilage and 
threw off that knee without an anterior cruciate ligament in the 
joint ever since. 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Elway's back and his hamstrings served notice that  
the rest of his 38-year-old body was joining the rebellion. At some 
point after he won his second Super Bowl in January, Elway was 
forced to admit it was better to remember the pain than endure it. 
</P>
<P>
	Later Sunday, Elway sat for an interview with ESPN's Roy  
Firestone, the master of the schmaltzy interview. The funny thing 
is that he was more composed than anybody had seen him all day. 
Asked how he wanted to be remembered, Elway didn't hesitate. He 
wanted to be remembered as a tough guy. 
</P>
<P>
	That's why he recalled a play from the third quarter of the 1998  
Super Bowl against Green Bay. The score was 17-17 and Terrell 
Davis, the running back who may have extended Elway's career by two 
seasons, was still woozy from a hit. Denver's offense had only 
managed one first down since the first quarter. And so, on 
third-and-6 from the Packers' 12-yard-line, Elway couldn't find 
anyone open and took off to his right. 
</P>
<P>
	When he got to the 6, three Packer defenders -- linebacker Brian  
Lewis, safeties LeRoy Butler and Mike Prior, a combined 650 pounds 
of stopping power -- had set up a roadblock. Elway set an example by 
trying to vault over the top. He didn't get to the end zone, but 
soon after the Broncos did. Not long after that, they won. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always hated that (insult) about making quarterbacks wear  
dresses. That was the play that made me a football player,'' he 
said, ``instead of a quarterback.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlitke@ap.org. 
</P>
