<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Giants' Kent Hits for Cycle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jeff Kent hit for the cycle in his first four  
at-bats against Pittsburgh on Monday night, becoming the first San 
Francisco Giants player to do so since Robby Thompson on April 22, 
1991. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent is the 19th player in Giants' history to hit a single,  
double, triple and homer in the same game -- something Giants star 
Barry Bonds has never done. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent singled in the first inning before hitting a three-run  
homer in the third for his first RBIs since April 20. He tripled to 
center field in the fifth and doubled down the left-field line in 
the seventh. 
</P>
<P>
	His first three at-bats came against Pirates starter Chris  
Peters and the double came off Marc Wilkins. 
</P>
<P>
	Kent is only the second player to hit for the cycle since Three  
Rivers Stadium opened in July 1970. Joe Torre, now the New York 
Yankees' manager, hit for the cycle on June 27, 1973 for the St. 
Louis Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The last player to hit for the cycle was Colorado's Neifi Perez,  
who did it last July 25 against St. Louis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
