<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain, Soybean Futures Mixed / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were mixed early  
today on the Chicago Board of Trade as weather forecasts provided 
conflicting views on crop outlooks. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices found support from forecasts that a slow-moving weather  
pattern will bring showers and thunderstorms to Midwest growing 
areas over the next five days, delaying fieldwork. But corn and 
soybeans also were pressured by the view that mild temperatures and 
clear skies over the weekend had allowed farmers to make 
significant gains on planting. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured by expectations that a tour of  
fields this week will show yields are well above average, which 
could lead to a bumper harvest at a time when export demand is 
relatively weak. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 2 1/4 cents to $2.65 3/4 a bushel; July  
corn fell 1/4 cent to $2.18 1/2 a bushel; July oats fell 1 1/4 cents to 
$1.17 a bushel; July soybeans rose 1/4 cent to $4.86 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork bellies futures advanced on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle and lean hogs were mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .18 cent to 63 cents a pound; May feeder  
cattle was unchanged at 71.15 cents a pound; June lean hogs rose 
.28 cent to 59.35 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .85 cent to 
59.85 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
