<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 05:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Newsmagazines a Dominant News Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The SWAT team hadn't left Columbine High School  
when executive producer Neal Shapiro scrapped that evening's 
``Dateline NBC,'' shelving an investigation into falsified reports 
at a crime lab. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, NBC went on the air with a minute-by-minute account of  
the school shooting, a report on how teens get guns and a Tom 
Brokaw interview with a psychiatrist. 
</P>
<P>
	Shapiro's quick change act -- and the deluge of newsmagazine  
reports on Columbine that followed -- illustrated the changed 
landscape of network TV news like no other story before it. 
</P>
<P>
	Prime-time magazines are covering breaking news more  
aggressively and, together with CNN, MSNBC and Fox News Channel, 
are where more Americans turn to get their news fix. 
</P>
<P>
	The nightly news shows, home of potentates Brokaw, Dan Rather  
and Peter Jennings, continue to see their dominant role -- as well 
as their viewership -- shrink. 
</P>
<P>
	Gone are the days when TV magazines were often a repository for  
canned stories with little relation to the day's headlines. 
</P>
<P>
	``Each and every one of these newsmagazines have set themselves  
up to be fire stations -- they've got the equipment, they're ready 
to respond, they're just waiting for the next disaster to happen,'' 
said Russ Ptacek, publisher of NewsTV Report, which monitors the 
content of news shows. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dateline NBC'' and ABC's ``20/20'' have a greater opportunity  
to track breaking stories because, just like the evening news, 
they're on five times a week. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people who work on `Dateline' rose up through the  
breaking news ranks,'' Shapiro said. ``We like it. We're interested 
in it. For some people who work on the magazines there's a culture 
not to respond to it. They're not used to it and scared by it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newsmagazines aren't interested in every breaking story.  
Important ones like the economy or Yugoslavia don't get much 
attention because they don't lend themselves to a heart-tugging, 
narrative style. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbine was the perfect story, however. It had harrowing  
survivors' tales, the heart-rending stories of innocent victims and 
it touched on hot-button societal issues like guns and violence in 
the media. 
</P>
<P>
	By Ptacek's count, prime-time newsmagazines on ABC, CBS, NBC and  
Fox ran 43 separate stories on Columbine High in the 10 days 
following the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dateline NBC'' alone did stories on school pressures, ways to  
improve school security, the SWAT officers who were first on the 
scene, victims of previous school shootings, gun laws and the 
dreams that died with the Columbine victims. 
</P>
<P>
	With the proliferation of newsmagazines on the air these days,  
``you're getting the kind of competition for stories and the kind 
of coverage that you've never had before,'' said Jeff Fager, 
executive producer of CBS's ``60 Minutes II.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Viewers clearly responded: Six of the 12 top-rated prime-time  
shows in the week after the shooting were newsmagazines that 
reported on Columbine. Only the Monica Lewinsky interview scored 
higher ratings for ``20/20'' this year than its edition the day 
after Columbine. 
</P>
<P>
	Such success virtually guarantees the trend will continue.  
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the expectation that the magazines should be a vehicle  
for following big stories is such that CBS was criticized -- and 
admitted its mistake -- for not devoting a prime-time hour to 
Columbine the day after the shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Nightly news ratings were up in the wake of the massacre, too.  
This season, 48 percent of television sets in use at the time are 
tuned to the NBC, ABC or CBS half-hour news summaries when they're 
on -- no small accomplishment at a time of dwindling viewership. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet over the long haul, the shows are leaking viewers. In 1980,  
the three shows had an audience share of 72. The shows have an 
average of 23.6 million households watching this year, down from 
26.8 million 10 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say fewer Americans are home in time to watch the  
evening news than in the days Walter Cronkite summed up the world. 
TV viewers also have the option of getting their news elsewhere 
whenever they want, or simply watching something else. 
</P>
<P>
	That's driven the efforts to deliver the news in other ways.  
CBS's Rather has lobbied to have a later evening news broadcast, 
and ABC News President David Westin has talked of incorporating a 
regular news update into the newsmagazines. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC touts its all-day machine of outlets: ``Today'' in the  
morning, MSNBC all the time, and the nightly news at ``Dateline'' 
in the evening. 
</P>
<P>
	Shapiro said he speaks frequently with David Doss, his  
counterpart on the ``NBC Nightly News,'' and the two horse-trade 
for stories. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsmagazine take on stories, however, is usually far  
different than on a straight broadcast: human dramas are played up 
and storytelling techniques used. Since they are in prime-time, 
they have greater entertainment value. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have more time to do it -- more time to put the stories  
together and more time to devote to the topic,'' Shapiro said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
