<HEADLINE> Nomo Makes Minor League Appearance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Ala. (AP) -- Hideo Nomo earned his way back to the  
major leagues by pitching seven scoreless innings Sunday for 
Double-A Huntsville. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo was signed to a minor league contract Thursday by the  
Milwaukee Brewers. He will be called up Friday, given a $250,000, 
one-year contract, and start that night at San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a very good atmosphere for me today,'' Nomo said  
through a translator. ``I was very comfortable throwing the ball. I 
am looking forward to going back to the major leagues, and I hope 
to do well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo allowed five hits, one walk and struck out seven in  
Huntsville's 6-0 win against Greenville. 
</P>
<P>
	``He mixed his pitches up very well this afternoon,'' said Mike  
Caldwell, roving pitching instructor for the Brewers. ``His 
velocity was as high when he came out as when he started. He 
certainly knows how to pitch. If he can put the ball where he wants 
it he can be effective.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo even went 2-for-3 at the plate with two RBIs.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was good to hit well today but honestly it was  
accidental,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nomo is trying to resurrect a career that began with him winning  
the National League Rookie of the Year award with the Los Angeles 
Dodgers in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	He was traded to the New York Mets last season and released this  
spring. He then signed a minor league deal with the Chicago Cubs 
and was released after three straight bad outings at Triple-A Iowa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
