<HEADLINE> Cuba Leader Says Game Not Political </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Cuba has no hidden political agenda connected  
to Monday night's game between the Baltimore Orioles and Cuba's 
national team, the communist country's minister of sports said 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a sports exchange, a peaceful exchange between our two  
peoples,'' Humberto Rodriguez Gonzalez said at a news conference 
before the second matchup Monday night between the Orioles and 
Cuban players. ``It is a friendly gesture ... and a peaceful 
gesture. We will be watching two marvelous teams.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gonzalez said people protesting the game are misguided. ``I  
believe sincerely they are wrong,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He brushed off questions about opposition to the game by Cuban  
exiles, saying, ``We are not concerned about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the Cuban team in Baltimore is much better than the one  
that lost to the Orioles 3-2 in Havana on March 28. He reiterated 
that several top players who didn't play in the first game because 
they were involved in national playoffs will be in the lineup this 
time. 
</P>
<P>
	But German Mesa, the hero in Cuba's win over the United States  
during the 1991 Pan American Games held in Havana, will not be. 
</P>
<P>
	When asked if Mesa were under restrictions, Gonzalez said he  
trained hard but didn't make the team. 
</P>
<P>
	The big salaries made by some major league players in the United  
States is not an incentive for Cuban players to defect because they 
play for love of the sport and their country, Gonzalez said. Those 
players who have defected are looked down upon by their countrymen, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are not a source of inspiration for our people,''  
Gonzalez said. ``There is no money in the world able to move 
feelings when you are true to them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
