<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Creditors' Bankruptcy Rights Helped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today strengthened  
creditors' rights against those of shareholders in some bankruptcy 
cases in which an insolvent firm is being reorganized. 
</P>
<P>
	The court ruled in a Chicago case that unsecured creditors can  
bar shareholders from putting up new money to retain ownership of a 
reorganized firm, if no one else was given a chance to come up with 
an alternative plan. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's 8-1 ruling reverses a lower court decision that let a  
Chicago real estate partnership's shareholders provide new capital 
to keep their ownership over the objections of unsecured creditors. 
Other federal courts had refused to allow similar arrangements. 
</P>
<P>
	Justice David H. Souter wrote for the court that the plan ``is  
doomed'' because it let the shareholders retain ownership ``without 
extending an opportunity to anyone else either to compete for that 
equity or to propose a competing reorganization plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case involved the 203 North LaSalle Street Partnership, a  
real estate limited partnership whose main asset is 15 floors of a 
downtown Chicago office building. 
</P>
<P>
	The partnership owes Bank of America National Trust and Savings  
Association, a subsidiary of BankAmerica Corp., more than $93 
million secured by a mortgage on the property that was due in 
January 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	When the partnership could not pay off the loan, the bank began  
foreclosure proceedings. The partnership then filed for 
reorganization under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law, 
which halted the foreclosure. 
</P>
<P>
	A bankruptcy judge valued the office building property at $54.5  
million, leaving the bank with an unsecured claim of $38.5 million. 
The judge estimated the bank would get only 16 percent of the 
unsecured amount. 
</P>
<P>
	The bankruptcy judge approved a reorganization plan that let the  
shareholders retain their ownership by providing new capital, 
rejecting objections by the bank, which wanted to foreclose on the 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld the judge's  
decision, saying such plans can be approved when shareholders 
provide ``new value'' to a reorganized company. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, the Supreme Court did not say whether bankruptcy law  
allows such a ``new value'' rule. But the justices said the plan in 
today's case could not be approved because the investment 
opportunity was provided exclusively to the old shareholders. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given that the opportunity is property of some value, the  
question arises why old equity (the shareholders) alone should 
obtain it, not to mention at no cost whatever,'' Souter wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	His opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and  
Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Anthony M. Kennedy, Ruth Bader 
Ginsburg and Stephen G. Breyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Justices Clarence Thomas and Antonin Scalia joined the result in  
a separate opinion. 
</P>
<P>
	Dissenting was Justice John Paul Stevens, who said he believed  
the appeals court correctly approved the plan. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Bank of America National Trust and Savings  
Association vs. 203 North LaSalle Street Partnership, 97-1418. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
