<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Prostate Blood Test in Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- A new blood test under development could help  
doctors better assess a man's risk of prostate cancer without the 
use of a biopsy, according to a study released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The test, used with one that is already in wide use, could catch  
the cancer earlier. As with many cancers, earlier detection 
improves the likelihood of survival. 
</P>
<P>
	Men 40 and older and those at a high risk have received annual  
Tandem free prostate-specific antigen tests since the early 1990s. 
The test shows when protein levels rise in the bloodstream, an 
indicator of cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	The new test, known as hK2, measures the human kallikrein 2  
enzyme. Both hK2 and the older test were developed by Hybritech 
Inc. of San Diego, which funded the study. 
</P>
<P>
	A study of 937 men showed that the two tests used together  
identified 91 percent of the men who were cancer-free and 40 
percent of those who had prostate cancer and needed further 
evaluation. 
</P>
<P>
	The combination of tests can help catch 95 percent of prostate  
cancers and reduce needless biopsies in the group by 20 percent, 
the researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a need to catch cancer at a more curable level,''  
said lead researcher Dr. William J. Catalona, a professor of 
urologic surgery at Washington University School of Medicine in St. 
Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Catalona presented his findings to a meeting of the American  
Urological Association. 
</P>
<P>
	Prostate trouble is a common problem for aging men. The  
walnut-sized gland, which is involved in semen production, 
frequently becomes enlarged in older men and is susceptible to 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	Every year, an estimated 184,500 American men develop prostate  
cancer and more than 41,000 die from it, according to the American 
Cancer Society. 
</P>
<P>
	Used in combination, the two tests could help patients because  
doctors are cautious about ordering biopsies -- which often cost 
$1,200 or more -- on the roughly 17 percent of men who have 
intermediate levels of prostate-specific antigen (PSA) in the 
bloodstream, Catalona said. 
</P>
<P>
	An expert not involved in the study said the PSA ranges are not  
an absolute guide to who needs biopsies but are instead a 
weathervane. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. John Whitesel, chief of urology at the University of  
Colorado, said an additional test ``certainly would help us 
diagnose sooner. The earlier we can diagnose, the better chance we 
have to cure the disease.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
