<DOCNO> APW19990503.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:43:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> White House Welcoming Japanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- He threw out the ceremonial first pitch at a  
Chicago Cubs game and played tourist on his way to Washington, but 
visiting Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi went the cultural 
route Monday with a personal tutorial on the history of the Bonsai 
and a dinner entertained by piano virtuoso Van Cliburn. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton feted the Japanese leader in a pavilion on the  
White House South Lawn replete with its own garden entrance. 
Shrubbery lined the light jade-colored walls of the pavilion, with 
some greenery even delicately interwoven in the chandeliers. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi sat at a table with Ethel Kennedy, a touching reminder of  
his trip to the United States as a graduate student in 1963 when he 
was granted a meeting with her husband, then-Attorney General 
Robert F. Kennedy. Obuchi described the meeting as having a major 
impact on his decision to launch a political career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can only wonder at the inexplicable manner in which destiny  
plays out,'' Obuchi said through a translator. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton, in his official toast, said the graciousness Obuchi saw  
in Kennedy had indeed made a lasting impression. 
</P>
<P>
	``We see it today reflected in your own decency and  
generosity,'' Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	During that visit to Washington 36 years ago, Obuchi stayed at  
the YMCA, which charged $1.50 a night. But things have changed, he 
noted. 
</P>
<P>
	``Well, this time no charge,'' the Japanese leader quipped in  
English. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Ambassador to Japan Tom Foley said that when Obuchi took  
office it was clear he was a ``nice guy,'' yet some questioned 
whether that was what Japan really needed. But the prime minister 
soon proved his political mettle. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's doing very well,'' Foley said. ``He's enjoying the esteem  
of his own citizens as well as of Americans.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As evidence of that, about 340 guests turned out for the event,  
enjoying cocktails in the East Room before packing into red 
trolleys that cruised down a back driveway of the White House to 
the dinner pavilion. 
</P>
<P>
	First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton greeted guests in a black and  
white sash presented to her by Mrs. Chizuko Obuchi over a 
floor-length black sequin Donna Karan gown. 
</P>
<P>
	The two leaders received a tutorial in horticulture earlier in  
the day from Saburo Kato, chairman of the Nippon Bonsai 
Association. In the White House Blue Room, adorned for the occasion 
by Bonsai trees brought in from the National Arboretum, Clinton 
presented Obuchi with a 300-year-old tree as a gift. The pair 
listened attentively as Kato then explained the way the roots grow 
and the trees curve. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were absolutely fascinated by this,'' said White House  
Social Secretary Capricia Marshall. 
</P>
<P>
	Obuchi played high-level tourist over the weekend, throwing the  
first pitch to Sammy Sosa at a Cubs game and ringing the bell to 
close floor trade at the Chicago Mercantile Exchange. Obuchi was 
just as excited to hear that Cliburn would perform for the dinner. 
</P>
<P>
	``The members of the delegation were ecstatic,'' Marshall said.  
``Prime Minister Obuchi loves the classics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cliburn, who has performed for every president since Harry  
Truman, made his own selections for the evening, which included 
pieces by Chopin, Brahms and Rachmaninoff. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Park Service, along with the White House staff,  
assisted in creating the garden and floral arrangements around the 
pavilion. Azaleas and lugustrums bedecked the sides of the tent, 
while fresh lilacs and white peonies topped the tables. 
</P>
<P>
	A similar pavilion style set-up welcomed Emperor Akihito of  
Japan when he visited the Clintons nearly five years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Even White House dessert chef Ronald Messnier got in on the  
garden theme, preparing a plate set with a Bonsai tree of green and 
brown chocolate sitting along a bridge over a river of green kiwi 
sauce. 
</P>
</TEXT>
