<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Revises Economic Forecast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SINGAPORE (AP) -- The future of Singapore's economy depends on a  
recovery in the global electronics sector and the strength of 
industrial and Asian countries, the Monetary Authority of Singapore 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The country's central bank noted Singapore's forecast for  
economic growth in 1999 has been revised upward to a range of zero 
to 2 percent. The new forecast -- up from an earlier forecast of 
between 1 percent contraction and 1 percent growth -- was announced 
over the weekend by Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong. 
</P>
<P>
	``The actual outcome hinges critically on a recovery in the  
global electronics industry and strength of the industrial and 
Asian economies, which of late have shown significant signs of 
improvement,'' the Monetary Authority said in the first issue of 
its on-line Quarterly Bulletin. 
</P>
<P>
	The bulletin also said that ``inflation is expected to remain  
negative in the first half of the year and return to positive 
territory in the second half in line with an expected recovery in 
the economy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The bank noted that manufacturing output was dragged down in  
1998 because of a long slump in the global electronics sector. It 
said that in the first two months of 1999, output rose 6.1 percent 
and electronics output was up 14 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nevertheless, prospects for the (electronics) industry remain  
uncertain,'' it said. ``While inventory levels have declined 
steadily since May last year, the trends in shipments are less 
clear.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
