<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Some 'Reality Shows' May Be Staged </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Fox network promised today to clearly  
explain to viewers when its ``reality'' shows don't depict reality, 
following a report that alleged a chase shown on ``World's Wildest 
Police Videos'' was staged. 
</P>
<P>
	The syndicated newsmagazine ``Inside Edition'' said a segment  
that aired March 25 allegedly showed a felon using pepper spray on 
an officer and taking off on a high-speed car chase before being 
apprehended by police with guns and a dog. 
</P>
<P>
	The incident happened in Lowndes County, Georgia. The show's  
host, former Oregon Sheriff John Bunnell, told viewers that ``our 
cameras were there when the call came in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But ``Inside Edition'' quotes Sgt. J.D. Yeager of the Lowndes  
County Sheriff's Department as saying the tape was a staged 
re-creation of a chase that took place nearly 10 years earlier. The 
woman portraying the felon was actually a police officer. 
</P>
<P>
	Another segment depicting a suspect beaching a boat and then  
being tackled by pursuing police officers was actually a police 
training video, the newsmagazine said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Stajonovich, who produces the ``World's Wildest Police  
Videos'' series of specials for Fox, did not immediately return a 
telephone call seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Fox said that in the future, any video that does not reflect  
reality would be clearly identified as such by a text message 
appearing on the screen. 
</P>
<P>
	``Network policy remains to clearly identify all re-creations,  
re-enactments and training video within any reality program,'' Fox 
said in a statement. ``Producers must adhere to this policy, as Fox 
does not intend to mislead its viewers or misrepresent footage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A Fox spokeswoman could not say whether that policy had been  
followed during ``World's Wildest Police Videos.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fox has been a leader in developing reality shows, which have  
attracted big ratings as well as controversy. Other networks have 
tried their own versions. 
</P>
<P>
	The newsmagazine also alleges that a video of a rampaging  
elephant shown in a 1997 special, ``When Animals Attack,'' actually 
depicted an actor and trained elephant recreating an earlier 
attack. Viewers were not told it was a recreation, the show said. 
</P>
<P>
	Producers of Fox's ``Busted on the Job'' series routinely make  
up stories to go along with some of its tapes, such as one that 
shows a woman urinating on her boss's furniture, the show said. 
</P>
<P>
	Erick Nelson, who produces ``Busted on the Job,'' said he makes  
a comedy show and occasionally changes details to protect people 
caught in embarrassing acts. 
</P>
<P>
	``My feeling is it's the Christian thing to do to change some  
details so people who see it can't say, `was that you I saw on 
television?''' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said his show never airs doctored videos.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heston: Gun Laws Not the Answer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The federal government should do a better job  
of sending gun violators to prison rather than coming up with new 
gun control laws, National Rifle Association President Charlton 
Heston says. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics who link the school shootings in Littleton, Colo., to  
the NRA's success in stopping new gun restrictions should look 
instead to the government's failure to enforce the 2,000 gun laws 
already on the books, Heston said Sunday on ABC's ``This Week.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Attorney General Eric Holder, appearing on the same show,  
said laws enacted during the Clinton administration have kept 
firearms out of the hands of criminals and contributed to a drop in 
gun violence without imposing on the rights of law-abiding 
citizens. ``How has the universe changed for people who have a 
legitimate right to have a gun?'' he asked. 
</P>
<P>
	A scaled-back NRA convention in Denver on Saturday drew 8,000  
protesters, many saying the NRA's hardline opposition to gun 
control was one reason the two youths who killed 12 of their fellow 
students and a teacher in suburban Littleton, Colo., had such easy 
access to powerful firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem is not the availability of arms,'' but the  
government's poor record in prosecuting both juveniles and adults 
for gun violations, Heston said. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the NRA did support trigger locks, didn't oppose bans on  
some ammunition clips and favored instant criminal checks on buyers 
at gun shows, as long as files were not kept on American citizens. 
``That smells of tyranny,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But the veteran film actor opposed an administration proposal to  
extend the waiting period for background checks under the Brady law 
to prevent felons from buying handguns. ``I'm not interested in 
seeing them denied purchase,'' he said. ``I'm interested in seeing 
them imprisoned.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heston said that if invited, he would attend a proposed White  
House summit on juvenile violence. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton, seizing the initiative as the nation recoiled  
from the Colorado shootings, last week introduced a broad 
gun-control measure that would raise the legal age for handgun 
possession from 18 to 21, hold negligent parents liable, halt 
imports of all high-capacity ammunition clips and limit handgun 
purchases to one a month. 
</P>
<P>
	His bill also would require child-safety locks on all guns sold,  
impose background checks on buyers for all gun-show sales and 
require a three-day waiting period for all handgun purchases. 
Today, most checks to verify a would-be purchaser doesn't have a 
criminal record are done instantaneously. 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said the  
Republican-led Congress was willing to look at steps to tighten 
existing laws, but he agreed with Heston that the real need was for 
more aggressive prosecution. The two suspects in Littleton broke at 
least 17 laws in their assault, Lott said on CNN's ``Late 
Edition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Senate Judiciary Committee Chairman Orrin Hatch, interviewed on  
``Fox News Sunday,'' said that since Clinton took office gun 
violation prosecutions have been cut in half. ``This administration 
hasn't been very serious about guns,'' the Utah Republican said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., a leading advocate of gun control,  
praised the Clinton package but acknowledged that enacting even 
modest new laws will be tough. One survey found that only 4 percent 
of Americans think new gun control laws aren't needed, he said, and 
``I think that 4 percent is all in the Congress.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
