<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Are Little Changed / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- U.S. treasury bonds barely changed Monday after  
a key manufacturing report eased concerns that the economy is 
overheating. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose 3/32  
points, or by $0.94 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which 
moves in the opposite direction, fell to 5.65 percent from Friday's 
5.66 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Purchasing Management said in a  
report released Monday that the nation's manufacturing sector 
continued to expand for the third straight month in April. But the 
growth was less robust than in the previous month. 
</P>
<P>
	That, combined with more moderate spending growth, could be  
among the first signs of an expected economic slowdown, some 
analysts speculated, easing fears of inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Rising inflation reduces the value of fixed-income investments,  
such as bonds. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
were unchanged, while intermediate maturities ranged between 
unchanged and down 3/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a 
financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on three-month Treasury bills was 4.60 percent as the  
discount rose 0.05 percentage point from late Friday to 4.48 
percent. Six-month yields rose to 4.67 percent, while the discount 
increased 0.03 percentage point to 4.50 percent. One-year yields 
jumped to 4.77 percent as the discount rose 0.01 percentage point 
to 4.54 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, rose to 5.13 percent from late Friday's 4.94 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 123 5/16 from 123 1/2 late Friday. The 
average yield to maturity rose to 5.30 percent from 5.28 percent 
late Friday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
