<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Incendiary Device at Neb. School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LaVISTA, Neb. (AP) -- An incendiary device was found today at a  
school where a written threat was received last week, and a 
15-year-old boy later admitted being responsible for both, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	LaVista Junior High was evacuated and the Omaha Police bomb  
squad was called in after a pop bottle with flammable liquid and 
fuse was found in the trash can of a boys' restroom around 9:15 
a.m. The bomb squad removed the device and defused it outside the 
school building. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities said a written threat had been received at the  
school last Friday. The school also was evacuated then, but nothing 
was found. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the handwriting in the written threat, authorities  
already were questioning a boy this morning when another student 
found the bottle device, Principal Jim Glover said. The device had 
apparently been placed in the restroom earlier this morning, 
authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glover said the 15-year-old admitted making the threat and  
placing the device. He was suspended indefinitely and turned over 
to police. 
</P>
<P>
	Classes at the school were allowed to resume, but about 200 of  
the school's 870 students were taken home by parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I wanted was him home,'' said one parent, Shelly DeLuna.  
</P>
<P>
	LaVista Junior High is in the Papillion-LaVista School district  
in suburban Omaha. The incident is the latest in a slew of bomb 
threats, gun arrests and other problems at schools across the 
nation since the attack on Columbine High School in Littleton, 
Colo., on April 20. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
