<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Author Criticized for Superstore Ad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- As Frank McCourt now knows, it's hard to be  
neutral in the battle of the booksellers. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Booksellers Association overwhelmingly passed a  
resolution over the weekend criticizing the author of ``Angela's 
Ashes.'' McCourt, whose book had once been named by independent 
book stores as their favorite to sell, had appeared in a television 
ad for the on-line superstore barnesandnoble.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they (independent stores) had wanted me to do a commercial  
I would have done one for them, too. I'm not a politician. I just 
did what my publisher requested,'' said McCourt, a featured speaker 
at BookExpo America, where the resolution was approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Other authors have plugged superstores -- Tom Clancy and Stephen  
King also made barnesandnoble.com ads -- but McCourt's endorsement 
was especially upsetting to independents because they see his 
success as their success, too. 
</P>
<P>
	No one, especially McCourt, imagined that his memoir about  
growing up in poverty in Ireland would sell more than 2 million 
copies. And independents believe they had a lot to do with that. 
It's what they feel their stores are all about -- spreading the word 
about a book the big chains won't take a chance on. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the market we serve,'' said Richard Howorth, president  
of the ABA, which has a core membership of some 3,300 independent 
stores. The expo, a three-day convention and trade show that ended 
Sunday, is the publishing industry's annual national gathering. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution called for a letter to McCourt to be drafted,  
expressing the ABA's disappointment. But the wording may not 
matter; McCourt said he won't bother reading it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never asked for an apology in my life and I've never  
given one. What I do I do. ... If I get a letter from them it'll go 
back unopened,'' McCourt said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the author said he would be ``very careful'' if asked to  
do another Barnes &AMP; Noble ad. And his publisher seemed sorry it 
ever got him involved. 
</P>
<P>
	``I regret that, because of the complications of the retail  
environment today, what seemed like a simple decision became so 
much more complicated,'' said Susan Moldow, vice president and 
publisher of Scribner, an imprint of Simon &AMP; Schuster that 
distributes both McCourt and King. 
</P>
<P>
	The resolution by the ABA, which has lost nearly 2,000 stores in  
the past decade, highlighted a weekend of tough talk and action. 
</P>
<P>
	The association aggressively promoted its answer to Amazon.com  
and other on-line sellers, BookSense.com, to be open for business 
late summer. And individual members accused Barnes &AMP; Noble, 
Amazon.com and other ``bad corporate citizens'' of everything from 
false advertising to stealing customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are fighting for our lives,'' Howorth said.  
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, booksellers also were talking books. Major upcoming  
releases include ``'Tis,'' McCourt's sequel to ``Angela's Ashes''; 
Edmund Morris' ``Dutch,'' his long-awaited book about former 
President Ronald Reagan; Sue Grafton's latest lettered mystery, ``O 
is For Outlaw,'' and ``Hannibal,'' Thomas Harris' sequel to his 
novel ``The Silence of the Lambs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But McCourt wasn't the only writer who stumbled into the war  
between independents and superstores. Bill Murray, who looked like 
he's done a lot of stumbling in his lifetime, got dragged in, too. 
</P>
<P>
	A featured breakfast speaker Saturday, Murray was promoting his  
upcoming golf book/memoir ``A Cinderella Story.'' He shared the 
dais with Frances Mayes, author of the bestseller ``Under the 
Tuscan Sun,'' and with Julia Child, who has a new cook book coming 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	With the crowd laughing each time he so much as twitched, Murray  
noticed an odd silence when he mentioned his book was being 
published by Doubleday, a division of Random House, which has 
invested in barnesandnoble.com. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not one speck of applause,'' he uttered. ``Julia got a  
standing ovation and Doubleday got NOTHING!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now, there was applause. He waited for it to end, then added.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm VERY happy to be with them.''  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
