<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tape Figures in Marine Pilot Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A crew member who was in the back seat  
when a Marine jet killed 20 people in Italy testified today he 
advised the pilot and navigator to get rid of a videotape shot 
during the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	Appearing at Capt. Richard Ashby's obstruction of justice trial,  
Capt. Chandler Seagraves testified that he met Ashby, the pilot, 
and the jet's navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, a few days after 
the accident in the tent city area of the Aviano, Italy, air base 
where they were stationed. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Ashby and Schweitzer asked him what they should do with  
the videotape, which Schweitzer had shot before the jet hit the 
cable. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said I'd get rid of it,'' he testified. At an unspecified  
later date, Seagraves said Schweitzer told him the tape was gone. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagraves' testimony was interrupted by another mistrial motion  
made by Ashby's attorneys. The judge, Col. Alvin Keller, listened 
to arguments by the two sides and did not immediately rule on the 
motion. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby's lawyers objected to a prosecutor raising the issue of  
the crew members' silence about the videotape. Attorney Frank 
Spinner said raising that issue violated his client's Fifth 
Amendment right against self-incrimination. Keller had already 
rejected a mistrial motion on similar grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagraves, 29, of Nineveh, Ind., was a crewman on the EA-6B  
Prowler that clipped a gondola cable near Cavalese, Italy, on Feb. 
3, 1998, killing 20 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, 32, of Mission Viejo, Calif., is charged with obstruction  
of justice and conspiracy for helping destroy the video. The case 
is expected to go to the jury this week. If convicted of the two 
charges, Ashby could be sent to prison for up to 10 years or be 
dismissed from the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagraves' testimony began the second week of Ashby's trial.  
</P>
<P>
	He said the four crew members met individually with Italian  
officials the day after the accident. ``I knew they obviously were 
looking into what was going on, but at that time, that was the 
least of my concerns,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors were trying to establish that Ashby knew there was a  
criminal investigation under way when he helped destroy the video. 
Ashby has admitting taking the tape from the jet, but maintains he 
didn't intend to obstruct justice because he didn't know a such a 
probe was under way. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagraves, Ashby, another backseat crewman and Schweitzer all  
were charged with involuntary manslaughter after the accident near 
Cavalese, Italy. Ashby was acquitted of the charges, and 
authorities dismissed the charges against the others. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer, 31, of Westbury, N.Y., pleaded guilty to the  
obstruction charges. In April, a jury recommended his dismissal 
from the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer testified Friday that he made the tape of himself in  
the plane before the accident, intending it as a souvenir. After 
the tragedy, he told Ashby to take the videotape from the jet, 
Ashby gave him the tape a few days later, and Schweitzer threw it 
into a bonfire. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he feared his picture might be used along with those of  
the bloody accident scene. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I could think about was my face and the blood in the  
snow,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
