<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women To Press Lawmakers on Medicare </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Advocacy groups are appealing to women to be  
vigilant of lawmakers looking to make changes to Medicare this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Women rely more on the nation's health insurance program for the  
elderly and disabled because they tend to live longer and have 
lower incomes than men, according to a new report released Monday 
by the Older Women's League, which is leading the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Three out of every five Medicare beneficiaries are women, and  
among those over age 85 women outnumber men two to one, the report 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Also, elderly women spend 22 percent of their generally smaller  
incomes on out-of-pocket health care costs, compared to 17 percent 
spent by men. 
</P>
<P>
	The report cautioned women ``to pay close attention to changes  
that have already taken place in the Medicare program and to 
proposals for reforming it further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the help of other advocacy groups, including the  
Alzheimer's Association, the group has also distributed 30,000 
cards that women across the country can mail to members of 
Congress. 
</P>
<P>
	Without changes, Medicare is expected to run short of cash by  
2015 -- just as baby boomers are retiring. However, past attempts to 
alter the program have proven politically perilous, attracting 
powerful opposition to proposals such as raising the Medicare 
eligibility age or increasing beneficiary cost-sharing. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting with Vice President Al Gore at the White House on  
Monday, OWL members offered support for a Clinton administration 
proposal to add money from government surpluses to Medicare. Many 
Republicans and some congressional Democrats have insisted that 
cost-saving reforms must come first. 
</P>
<P>
	President Clinton has said he will send lawmakers a more  
comprehensive plan for overhauling Medicare in time for their 
consideration this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
