<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Food Companies Relying on Tie-Ins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- There's a feeding frenzy at this week's annual  
supermarket industry show, but food isn't on the table. The hype 
this year is not about new products, store design or nutrition but 
can be summed up in two words: ``Star Wars.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Movie executives weren't the only ones already seeing dollar  
signs in their eyes from the much-anticipated prequel to the hit 
trilogy. With little more than two weeks to go before the 
much-awaited ``Star Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' the 
Food Marketing Institute show became a showcase for companies lucky 
enough to win tie-ins with the film. 
</P>
<P>
	Participants flocked to Pepsi and Frito-Lay's huge ``Star Wars''  
setup, which showed movie trailers of the upcoming film, mockups of 
some of the main characters and the 24 different ``collector'' cans 
consumers can buy. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepsi executives and others who are unveiling promotional ``Star  
Wars'' tie-ins this week had nothing but smiles despite huge 
amounts of money being paid to LucasFilm for the rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``The universe is the limit; we're anticipating a huge  
incremental sales jump from this particular campaign,'' said Greg 
McIntee, a Pepsi vice president of customer marketing and category 
management. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lucas has a real understanding of what captures the  
imagination, while we are all about good taste and fun,'' McIntee 
said Monday. ``We think that is going to mutually drive both 
businesses in hard numbers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Across the cavernous convention hall, another popular stop was  
Favorite Brands International, which had set up a ``Star Wars'' 
computer game on a large-screen television as it showcased Farley 
fruit snacks that come in the shape of major characters from the 
new film. 
</P>
<P>
	The licensing deal is, on average, adding about 20 cents to each  
package, said Favorite Brands product manager Marie Gould. But the 
added cost is worth it, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's a kids-oriented product -- and a lot of snack foods are  
-- licensing has become more important at getting their attention 
and giving the impression of being on the cutting edge,'' Gould 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	While industry participants did see new items such as the  
world's largest pickle for Vlasic's hamburger dill and product line 
extensions such as Rold Gold cheddar-cheese flavored pretzels, 
observers noted a dearth of innovations at the show, which runs 
through today. 
</P>
<P>
	Information Resources Inc. and New Product News magazine found  
in a new study that 1998 saw the fewest number of new products come 
to market in four years as companies see a smaller return on those 
products in terms of sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, of the top 10 products of last year, only three were in  
the food and beverage category: Frito-Lay's WOW chips at No. 1, its 
Deli Style chips at No. 8 and Pepsi's One cola at No. 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The diminishing returns manufacturers are seeing on new  
introductions has caused promotional tie-ins to films and 
television shows such as Looney Tunes to see increased acceptance, 
no matter what the cost. 
</P>
<P>
	Such attitude come in part because grocers fighting with space  
limitations typically are reluctant to stock newer products unless 
they are guaranteed a large return nearly immediately. And the 
widespread industry consolidation has led to increased stocking of 
store-brand items as supermarkets see lower costs by getting bigger 
and sharing distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	Gould of Favorite Brands noted the new ``Star Wars'' products  
found nearly 100 percent store acceptance in just a month, while it 
typically takes up to six months to receive only 30 percent 
acceptance. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
