<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Last Microsoft Witnesses Identified </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Microsoft will use testimony from a rival  
executive at America Online, and an IBM executive will testify for 
the government among the six final witnesses in the Microsoft 
antitrust trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft said Monday it will question AOL Senior Vice President  
David Colburn as a hostile witness when the trial resumes. It will 
ask him about AOL's recent $9.9 billion purchase of Netscape 
Communications Corp., and the implications of that extraordinary 
deal on the technology industry and on the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft argues that AOL's new alliance with Netscape  
illustrates that competition is thriving and government 
intervention is unnecessary in such an important part of the 
booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	Colburn testified previously for the government, explaining  
AOL's decision in March 1996 to distribute Microsoft's Internet 
software over rival Netscape's. Microsoft said in court papers 
that, among other topics, its lawyers want to question Colburn 
about the ``completeness and candor'' of his prior testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department and 19 states said they will call Garry  
Norris, a former director at IBM Corp.'s personal computer 
division, who is expected to testify about Microsoft's alleged 
bullying practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Until Monday's announcement, a curious hole in the government's  
case has been the lack in its lineup of witnesses from any of the 
nation's computer makers. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft also will use testimony from Gordon Eubanks, who  
stepped down weeks ago as president and chief executive officer of 
Symantec Corp., which makes a popular anti-virus program and other 
software utilities that run using Microsoft's Windows operating 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks, a longtime Microsoft ally, left to become president of  
Oblix Inc., a small computer automation company whose investors 
include Netscape and Novell Inc. -- some of Microsoft's biggest 
rivals. 
</P>
<P>
	Eubanks told The New York Times last year, ``Microsoft has done  
some bad things.'' But he added that Microsoft's chairman, Bill 
Gates, is a victim of American culture's trend of attacking and 
tearing down successful people. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview last summer with an Internet trade publication,  
Eubanks said he does not believe the courtroom is the best way to 
solve technology problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``My own opinion is that the marketplace is a better arbiter of  
these issues,'' Eubanks said then. 
</P>
<P>
	The government said it also will call back Edward Felten, a  
Princeton University computer expert who previously testified it 
was possible to disable Microsoft's Internet software. 
</P>
<P>
	The company contends its Internet software is integrated with  
Windows and can't be removed without crippling the operating 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	The witnesses also will include two returning economists who  
stumbled through parts of their earlier testimony, Richard 
Schmalensee, a dean at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, 
and MIT economist Franklin Fisher. 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher, who testified for the government, slipped when he told  
Justice lawyer David Boies in January that Microsoft's behavior 
``on balance'' hasn't harmed consumers ``up to this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fisher caught himself moments later and amended his answer to  
explain that he believed the impact on consumers eventually will be 
felt. 
</P>
<P>
	``We will live, as it were, in a Microsoft world in which  
choices are the choices that Microsoft makes,'' Fisher said. ``I 
don't think that's good for consumers, but those effects have only 
just begun.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Schmalensee, who appeared for Microsoft, also stumbled on the  
stand in January, when Boies confronted him with an essay 
Schmalensee wrote 16 years ago that appeared to contradict his 
testimony. 
</P>
<P>
	``My immediate reaction is, what could I have been thinking?''  
Schmalensee said, adding that the essay ``does not provide a good 
indication of my present views.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One critic described Schmalensee as damaged by his earlier  
admission. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think his performance in the courtroom was much less  
polished and convincingly presented than one would have expected,'' 
said William Kovacic, an antitrust expert at George Washington 
University. ``It's somewhat risky to bring him back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The witnesses will take the stand during the trial's rebuttal  
phase, an important opportunity for each side to refine its 
courtroom positions by trying to buttress the weakest parts of its 
arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	``You want to nail down those parts of your case,'' said Robert  
Litan, a former senior Justice Department official. ``You want to 
make sure any potential weaknesses are cleaned up, tie up loose 
ends.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The trial has been in a lengthy recess since Feb. 26 and is not  
expected to resume before May 24. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
