<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Parental Supervision Cuts Risks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Parents who keep close tabs on their  
children's whereabouts and activities are less likely to produce 
kids involved in risky behavior, according to a new study. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers found that children living in Baltimore public  
housing who felt their parents set limits and talked with them 
about their concerns were far less likely to use alcohol and 
marijuana, sell drugs or have unprotected sex than their 
counterparts without parental intervention. 
</P>
<P>
	But the study, being presented today at the annual meeting of  
the Pediatric Academic Societies in San Francisco, also found that 
as the children grew older, the influence of their friends became 
even greater, even if parental monitoring stayed the same. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the University of Maryland researchers who led the study,  
Dr. Susan Feigelman said that there is nothing wrong with parents 
who monitor their children's friends. She noted the circumstances 
behind the Littleton, Colo., high school shooting tragedy. 
</P>
<P>
	The two teen-agers who killed themselves and 13 others were  
members of the Trenchcoat Mafia, a group of students who often 
dressed and acted in opposition to other students. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a theory that part of being a good parent is  
influencing the groups your kids hang out with,'' Feigelman said. 
``For Colorado, how do kids get into mafia behavior? Well, they're 
hanging out with the mafia to begin with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers surveyed 383 children, ages 9 to 15, periodically  
over a four-year period beginning in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The children were asked every six months for two years and then  
annually in the third and fourth years whether their parents knew 
where they were after school, if they were expected to call and say 
where they were going and with whom, if their parents knew where 
they were at night, if parents discussed those plans with the 
children and asked where they were going. 
</P>
<P>
	About 1 percent of the children who said they were highly  
monitored in this way sold drugs in the first six months of the 
study, compared to 10 percent of those who said they had little 
parental supervision. 
</P>
<P>
	Eighteen months later, however, 5 percent of children who were  
closely monitored said they were dealing drugs, while the 
percentage of children who had far less supervision and were 
selling drugs rose only slightly, to 12 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Similar patterns emerged regarding drug and alcohol use and  
unprotected sex. Feigelman said peer groups became more important 
as the children got older. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
