<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Clinton Meets Chernomyrdin on Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin emerged from  
a meeting with President Clinton today, saying the two ``got closer 
to a diplomatic solution'' to the Kosovo standoff. Chernomyrdin did 
not elaborate, except to say that he and the president discussed 
``the circumstances and the conditions'' under which NATO would 
pause its air assault on Yugoslavia. Clinton said earlier that ``we 
could have a bombing pause'' if Slobodan Milosevic accepts NATO's 
demands for the withdrawal of his troops, the return of refugees 
and the deployment of an international security force. The Rev. 
Jesse Jackson, who negotiated the release of three American POWs, 
had urged a break in the bombing in response. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-POWs Reunited With Families  
</P>
<P>
	LANDSTUHL, Germany (AP) -- Upbeat and safe at a U.S. military  
hospital in Germany, three servicemen released by Yugoslavia were 
joyfully reunited with their families on their first full day of 
freedom today. Army doctors pronounced the soldiers in generally 
good shape, but checkups also revealed fractured ribs and a broken 
nose, raising questions about how they were treated during their 
capture and month in captivity. Each had a private reunion with 
family members who had arrived in Germany on overnight flights from 
the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Man Arrested in Colo. Shooting Case  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- A man was arrested today on suspicion of  
supplying the semiautomatic pistol used in the Columbine High 
massacre. Mark Manes, 22, surrendered and was jailed on $15,000 
bail for investigation of providing a handgun to a minor. He could 
get six years in prison. Meanwhile, Columbine students returned to 
classes today at a nearby school. Banners welcoming Columbine's 
nearly 2,000 students adorned Chatfield High School. For the rest 
of the school year, Chatfield students will attend classes in the 
morning, while Columbine students will attend an afternoon session. 

</P>
<P>
	Cause of Ark. Boat Accident Sought  
</P>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- Investigators said today they will take  
underwater pictures of the boat that dragged 13 tourists to their 
deaths in hopes of learning how the accident happened. The World 
War II-vintage tourist boat had been in the repair shop two days 
before it sank in Lake Hamilton on Saturday, drowning 13 of its 21 
passengers. Investigators want to know if repair work done to the 
boat's drive-shaft was the cause of the accident, or if two other 
seals in the boat's hull were responsible. They say a videotape of 
the wreck on the lake bottom will help. 

</P>
<P>
	U.N. Rules To Halt 'Cybersquatting'  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- A U.N. agency said today it has finished drawing  
up rules to halt the practice known as cybersquatting in time for 
the new Internet name-assigning body to adopt them this month. The 
rules try to address a wide range of concerns while protecting 
well-known trademarks for use as Web addresses, said Francis Gurry, 
assistant director-general of the World Intellectual Property 
Organization. The intent is to stop people from registering Web 
addresses involving company trademarks in hopes of getting the 
companies to pay to buy the rights to the address. 

</P>
<P>
	Wrestling Fragrance in the Works  
</P>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Perfumania Inc. and World Championship Wrestling  
announced today they would join forces to manufacture and market a 
new, upscale line of fragrances. The new line will be 
cross-marketed to the WCW's television audience of 35 million, and 
in Miami-based Perfumania's 288 stores nationwide. The fragrances 
should be available for sale via Perfumania's Internet store in 
November. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Jones Ends Above 11,000  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average sped past  
11,000 today, shattering the record for the fastest rise between 
1,000-point milestones. The index rose 225.65 to close at 
11,014.69. It took just 24 trading days for the Dow to move from 
10,000 to 11,000. The Nasdaq dropped 7.27 points to 2,535.58. On 
the NYSE, gainers led losers 2,024-1,011. The Nasdaq composite 
index closed down 7.27 at 2,535.58. 

</P>
<P>
	White Sox Pound Angels 8-1  
</P>
<P>
	ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Magglio Ordonez hit a three-run homer and  
drove in four runs, and Frank Thomas became the Chicago White Sox's 
career leader in extra-base hits today in an 8-1 win over the 
Anaheim Angels. John Snyder (4-1), pitched his first complete game 
of the year and the second of his career. He held the Angels to 
four hits and no walks. The only run against him scored on Mo 
Vaughn's groundout in the first inning. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  

</P>
</TEXT>
