<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tragedy Alters Littleton Image </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The day the kids came running -- weeping  
and wailing and terrified -- Martin Steele was washing his van in 
the driveway. Melody Giebler was looking after someone else's 
children. Sandy Williams was giving a friend a manicure. And Ben 
Martin couldn't get to his home because the danger was too great. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon, the stream of young people running for their lives from  
Columbine High that bright warm midday on April 20 was followed by 
a flood of police cars and FBI agents and sheriff's deputies, of TV 
cameras and reporters and photographers, of ambulances and SWAT 
teams and anguished parents. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt like I was living in another world,'' Mrs. Giebler  
said. ``Nothing ever happens over here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The murderous rampage at Columbine robbed her neighborhood of  
that claim, possibly forever. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbine High sits on a wide boulevard next to Clement Park, a  
lush green haven of hills at a busy intersection south of Denver. 
Branching off the thoroughfares are tidy streets lined with cozy 
houses. 
</P>
<P>
	The police and the rescuers and the journalists are gone. Now  
it's the pilgrims who park on the byways. Every day, rain or shine, 
they trudge across the road to the park, often clutching bouquets 
to leave at the makeshift shrine where visitors have also placed 
condolence letters and teddy bears. 
</P>
<P>
	And some nights still, the chop-chop-chop of a helicopter  
shatters the dark peace. Could be police. Could be more TV people. 
</P>
<P>
	The day the kids came running, Mrs. Giebler, a 37-year-old  
daycare provider, threw open her front door to offer refuge and use 
of her telephone. Frantic teens needed to call home. Three boys 
were distraught, unable to locate their siblings at the school. 
Mrs. Giebler, who has a son, 10, and daughter, 7, said: ``I just 
thought, if these were my children, I'd want them to be able to 
call home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As for Mrs. Giebler herself, she said, ``I felt like I couldn't  
breathe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	FBI in the backyard. Armed and helmeted SWAT teams tramping down  
the street out front. She counted four ambulances, an armored car 
and a long truck someone told her was where bombs were taken. 
</P>
<P>
	The family was rattled. Last week, her son was still vomiting,  
morning and night. ``I look over my shoulder a lot more,'' Mrs. 
Giebler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Police told anxious parents to gather down the street at Leawood  
Elementary School. Youngsters who had escaped the massacre at 
Columbine could find their parents there. 
</P>
<P>
	Two young sisters raced to Sandy Williams' house. She was the  
lady who did their nails. She let them in and calmed them down. But 
she was stunned to see mothers and fathers milling in the street, 
dazed and anxious. Some wept. One man, unfamiliar with the 
cul-de-sacs and cross streets and demanding to be reunited with his 
daughter, got a lift from Miss Williams nearer to Columbine. 
</P>
<P>
	Miss Williams trembled. She cried, too.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was like they were all in shock,'' Miss Williams said. ``I  
think that's what upset me the most,'' she said, thinking of her 
20-year-old daughter, and son, 15, who attends another high school. 
``To see them not know their kids were there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That night, Donna and Martin Steele, both 71, had planned to  
mark 48 happy years of marriage, 34 of those years spent in their 
ranch house on the road by the park. It was also Mrs. Steele's 
birthday. The day quickly dissolved into the unimaginable. 
</P>
<P>
	When Steele tried to offer help, authorities ordered him to get  
inside ``because you're in the line of fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Suddenly the home where they raised five children, where their  
15 grandchildren come to visit, would never be the same. 
</P>
<P>
	``You watch it all on television for a week, then you watch it  
in the backyard, and it gets you down,'' said Steele, a retired 
General Mills sales representative. 
</P>
<P>
	Now the couple find their home no longer what they thought it  
was. 
</P>
<P>
	Said Mrs. Steele: ``Walking alone in the park will be very  
difficult to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Martin's bedroom offers a view of the high school, from  
which he graduated in 1996. He is now studying graphic design and 
is a devotee of Mohandas Gandhi. On the day the kids came running, 
the 20-year-old was prevented by two teachers from going to his 
house, where the back yard butts up against Columbine High's 
campus. 
</P>
<P>
	``Just total shock,'' was his feeling that day. Now he is taking  
a petition door-to-door, hoping to persuade school authorities to 
hang pictures of the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and Gandhi in the 
schools. By the end of last week, he had collected 90 signatures. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want nonviolence,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
