<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Army Whistleblower Returns To Work </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A safety manager fired for blowing the  
whistle on problems at an Army nerve gas incinerator is to return 
to work tomorrow, five years after his employer let him go for 
``poor management skills.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Steven Jones' return to the Tooele Chemical Agent Disposal  
Facility in Utah's western desert was ordered last month by a 
federal appeals court nearly two years after the Labor Department 
ruled that his firing was illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones said he was fired for refusing to certify that the  
incinerator was safe, delaying its startup by two years. EG&AMP;G 
Defense Materials Inc., the Army contractor destroying much of the 
nation's stockpile of nerve and mustard gas, insists Jones was 
fired for poor management skills after less than three months on 
the job. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is appealing the Labor Department ruling but was  
forced to take Jones back in the meantime. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones flagged more than 1,000 design flaws and mechanical  
problems at the plant. Emissions from the plant have been within 
federal standards, but critics say the risks to humans are unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	EG&AMP;G spokesman Mark Mesesan said Monday the company will welcome  
Jones back even as it appeals his reinstatement. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll treat him the same as we do any new or returning  
employee,'' Mesesan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jones has collected $50,000 in damages from EG&AMP;G. He kept only  
$2,000 after paying his lawyers, who are owed a total of $750,000. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tooele plant is the first chemical weapons incinerator in  
the continental United States. It was built to destroy more than 27 
million pounds of chemical weapons held in earthen and concrete 
bunkers in the desert 50 miles west of Salt Lake City. 


</P>
</TEXT>
