<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Supreme Court Actions Monday </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	The Supreme Court took the following actions Monday:  
</P>
<P>
	--Made it easier for U.S. officials to deport some illegal aliens  
whose lives or freedom would be threatened in their home country. 
The unanimous ruling limited federal courts' power to second-guess 
immigration officials who decide such aliens should be deported 
because they committed ``serious nonpolitical crimes'' outside the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	--Allowed newspaper dealers to sue the Pulitzer Publishing Co.  
over how it distributes the St. Louis Post-Dispatch to such dealers 
for retail sale. The company is accused of discriminating by 
selling the papers to some dealers at higher prices than it charges 
other dealers. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled in a bankruptcy case that unsecured creditors can bar  
shareholders from putting up new money to retain ownership of an 
insolvent firm that is being reorganized if no one else was given a 
chance to come up with an alternative plan. 
</P>
<P>
	--Agreed to decide, in a California case, whether criminal  
defense lawyers have a duty to file an appeal after their clients 
plead guilty. A lower court threw out a man's second-degree murder 
conviction on grounds his public-defender lawyer violated his 
constitutional right to adequate legal representation by failing to 
file an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ruled in an Arizona case that federal courts, not Indian tribal  
courts, get to decide whether a federal law places limits on claims 
that nuclear industry activities caused harm on Indian land. The 
case involves the 1988 Price-Anderson Act, which limits the 
liability of companies involved in the nuclear industry. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
