<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Volvo Buyers' Appeal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today rejected an appeal by  
a group of auto purchasers in Puerto Rico who won, and then lost, a 
$129 million award against Volvo. 
</P>
<P>
	The court, without comment, turned away the purchasers' attempt  
to revive their accusations that Volvo illegally schemed to 
overcharge them. 
</P>
<P>
	About 9,000 individuals and corporations who bought Volvos in  
Puerto Rico between 1983 and 1993 sued the car manufacturer and the 
local companies that imported and sold the cars. 
</P>
<P>
	The defendants were accused under the federal  
Racketeer-Influenced Corrupt Organizations law of conspiring to 
overcharge customers by using a company in Liechtenstein to inflate 
the prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The local importer and dealership defaulted, and the lawsuit  
against Volvo went to trial in federal court in San Juan. The jury 
ruled against Volvo and awarded $43 million in damages, an amount 
tripled by the judge to $129 million under the RICO law. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1st U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out the judgment  
last July, ruling that there was no proof Volvo was involved in the 
scheme. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, the auto purchasers' lawyers said  
the 1st Circuit court should be ordered to reconsider the case in 
light of a 1997 Supreme Court decision. 
</P>
<P>
	That ruling said defendants can be convicted of racketeering  
conspiracy without proof that they agreed to commit the two acts 
required for a conviction of an actual racketeering offense. 
</P>
<P>
	Volvo's lawyers said that decision was irrelevant because the  
appeals court ruled there was no evidence that Volvo was involved 
in any fraudulent activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Bonilla vs. Volvo, 98-1425.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
