<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Investment Worry Japanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Economic paranoia is on the loose in Japan, summed  
up in the plot of a recent made-for-TV movie: 
</P>
<P>
	A U.S. bank calls in its loans to several thousand  
recession-wracked Japanese small businesses. That sends them belly 
up and clears the way for the Americans' ultimate plan -- the 
dismantling of Japan Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	As Japan struggles to get out from under its worst recession in  
a half century, a slew of books, TV dramas and articles are 
declaring that Japan is on the verge of ``economic occupation'' at 
the hands of foreign investors. 
</P>
<P>
	The backlash is ironic. In the 1980s, Japan's high-flying  
investors were the focus of popular anger in the United States over 
mammoth real estate purchases and corporate takeovers. 
</P>
<P>
	Economic analysts say today's fears among Japanese are  
unfounded, but the emotions are real. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are surprised and uneasy about the sudden surge of  
takeovers by foreign companies,'' said Seiichi Tsurumi, a senior 
analyst of domestic affairs at the Japan Institute for Social and 
Economic Affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``When they think of foreign firms, they think layoffs,'' he  
added. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts say that isn't exactly fair. The influx of foreign  
capital may actually be helping keep Japanese companies afloat and 
workers employed. 
</P>
<P>
	But the profile of foreign companies has been increasingly high.  
</P>
<P>
	Formerly unfamiliar corporate names like General Electric,  
Goodyear Tire and Merrill Lynch have moved to acquire operations 
once run by Japanese blue chips such as Japan Leasing Corp., 
Sumitomo Rubber Industries Ltd. and Yamaichi Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Even Nissan Motor Co. -- a name that literally means ``Made in  
Japan'' -- has sold off a 37 percent stake in itself to the French 
automaker Renault. 
</P>
<P>
	Media reaction has been intense, even panicky.  
</P>
<P>
	Tabloids carry articles about foreign machinations to ``Buy  
Japan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	One respectable weekly magazine featured horror stories about  
Japanese workers toiling under American-style capitalism's harsh 
corporate management practices. 
</P>
<P>
	Another ran a story about foreign firms' ``occupation'' of key  
office space in crowded downtown Tokyo. That term is especially 
sensitive in Japan, which was occupied by American troops for seven 
years after World War II. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite all the fuss, the business community is hardly being  
overrun by foreigners. 
</P>
<P>
	As recently as 1996, Japan's trade ministry found that  
affiliates of overseas companies accounted for just 1.3 percent of 
total sales in Japan and 0.5 percent of overall employment. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, many Japanese workers worry that foreign influence will  
break down the old paternalistic relations between labor and 
management. 
</P>
<P>
	But that already has been happening, and not necessarily because  
of outside investors. Japanese companies are increasingly dumping 
traditional perks like lifetime employment and seniority-based 
promotion to cut costs to cope with falling profits. 
</P>
<P>
	For some workers, that trend makes foreign companies not a  
menace, but an opportunity. Thus the flip side of the media 
tempest. 
</P>
<P>
	Next to the books warning about economic occupiers, books on how  
to succeed by working for foreign companies have started cropping 
up on shelves at bookstores in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	One of them, written by the former head of Coors Brewing Co.'s  
unit in Japan, translates roughly as ``So You Want to Work for a 
Foreign Company?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The target audience appears to be younger Japanese, who have  
been among the hardest hit groups by skyrocketing unemployment. 
They also tend to be more open-minded than their elders when it 
comes to foreign bosses. 
</P>
<P>
	Kiyoshige Mizuno, a graduate of Tokyo's prestigious Sophia  
University, never dreamed of working for a non-Japanese firm until 
his employer, Japan Leasing, failed in the biggest corporate 
collapse in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Now GE Capital Corp. owns most of Japan Leasing and the  
37-year-old Mizuno has quit to work for the newly established 
Japanese unit of Hudson Advisors LLC, a Dallas-based firm that 
liquidates real estate assets. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can no longer rely on the Japanese way of doing things,''  
Mizuno said. ``We must survive in the global system.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
