<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Limited Spinning Off Girls Chain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Limited Inc. plans to spin off its very  
successful Limited Too girls clothing chain this summer and sell 
its majority interest in its Galyan's Trading Co. sporting goods 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	The news came Monday as the Columbus, Ohio-based retailer  
reported that it expects its first- and second-quarter earnings to 
top Wall Street analysts' estimates. The retailer also announced 
that it will buy back up to 15 million shares of its common stock. 
</P>
<P>
	The strong earnings forecast, which came after financial markets  
closed, is the latest evidence that the Limited is on the road to 
recovery after an aggressive restructuring effort has helped get 
the struggling retailing giant back on track. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what we've been waiting for at the Limited,'' said  
Maura Hunter Byrne, a retail analyst at Salomon Smith Barney. 
</P>
<P>
	The company lost customers in the mid-1990s to other merchants  
who offered more casual, classic clothes and lower prices. But the 
Limited has worked hard to win back shoppers by improving its 
fashion offerings and coming up with fresh retailing concepts -- 
like Limited Too and Bath &AMP; Body Works. 
</P>
<P>
	In Monday's announcement, the Limited said it expects  
first-quarter earnings per share of 14 cents, a 56 percent gain 
from 9 cents a year ago and above the 10 cents expected by 
analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	The company attributed the gains to strength at its Limited Too  
stores, its Express and Lerner New York chains, which cater to 
young women looking for trendy styles; its large-size Lane Bryant 
stores; and its Intimate Brands division, which includes Victoria's 
Secret and Bath &AMP; Body Works stores. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to the earnings news, the Limited announced its  
plans to spin off Limited Too to shareholders in late July or 
August 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had expected such a move, given the 319-store chain's  
great success in recent years. Sales have grown from $259 million 
in 1996 to $377 million in 1998, and its profits have significantly 
improved. 
</P>
<P>
	Geared for girls ages 7 to 14, Limited Too stores are filled  
with trendy merchandise, such as nail polish in outrageous colors, 
funky accessories and hip clothing styles. 
</P>
<P>
	The Limited Too spinoff follows a similar move by the Limited  
last year with Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch, the casual apparel retailer 
aimed at teens and young adults. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it allows (Limited Too) to pursue their growth  
initiatives unhindered by us,'' said Tom Katzenmeyer, vice 
president of investor relations at the Limited. He added that the 
plans for the Limited Too include a catalog and a Web site. 
</P>
<P>
	The Limited also announced that it will sell its majority stake  
in Galyan's to the investment firm of Freeman Spogli &AMP; Co. The 
deal, which is expected to close this summer, will leave the 
Limited with a 40 percent stake in the company. 
</P>
<P>
	The Limited expects to receive about $190 million from sale of  
Gaylan's, which operates 16 stores and had revenues of $220 million 
last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the stock buyback, Limited shareholders can sell a portion  
or all of their shares to the company at a price no less than $50 a 
share and no more than $55 a share. The buyback will commence on 
May 4 and continue until June 1. 
</P>
<P>
	In trading before the announcement, the Limited's stock rose 87 1/2  
cents to $44.62 1/2 on the New York Stock Exchange. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
