<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rejects Appeal From Newspaper </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today refused to kill a  
lawsuit against a newspaper company accused of illegal 
discrimination because it allegedly sells papers at varying prices 
to independent contractors for resale in different service areas. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices, without comment, rejected an appeal by the  
Pulitzer Publishing Co., which is being sued for how it distributes 
the St. Louis Post-Dispatch to ``branch dealers'' for sale in 
vending machines and at retail stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Seventeen of the 37 branch dealers who sell the Post-Dispatch  
sued Pulitzer Publishing, saying they are forced to pay higher 
prices than other branch dealers for the papers they buy in bulk 
each day from the company's Missouri plants. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit alleges violations of the federal Robinson-Patman  
Act, which bans a seller's price discrimination if it affects 
interstate commerce and injures competition among the seller's 
customers. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of the branch dealers who sued operate in Illinois; the  
rest in Missouri. According to the newspaper's lawyers, the dealers 
operate within clearly defined service areas and do not compete 
against each other. 
</P>
<P>
	But the dealers said they do compete against each other via the  
2,000 vending machines they stock with newspapers each day. ``All 
of the 2.5 million residents of the greater St. Louis metropolitan 
area are potential customers of each branch dealer,'' they told the 
justices. 
</P>
<P>
	A federal judge threw out the lawsuit, ruling that she lacked  
jurisdiction because the 17 dealers failed to prove any competitive 
relationship between them and others who allegedly were offered the 
different prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The 8th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reinstated the lawsuit  
last December, ruling that the dealers do not need to prove any 
such competition to give the judge the authority to hear the case. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be that the (dealers) will be unable to prove any  
competitive relationship, and consequently no competitive harm,'' 
the appeals court said. ``Those shortcomings of proof, however, do 
not deprive the district court of jurisdiction -- that is its power 
-- to hear the case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Pulitzer Publishing Co. vs. Godfrey, 98-1382.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
