<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:22:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Border Blues for Albanians </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AHMAT, Albania (AP) -- Sami Kraja peered through binoculars at  
two men standing on a distant ridge, the one marking Albania's 
border with Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	``There, you see?'' he said, pointing at the spot from where  
mortar fire descended on this mountain village early Sunday. The 
men were Serb fighters, and Kraja, a local Albanian policeman, 
insisted they were responsible for shelling the village the 
previous two nights. 
</P>
<P>
	No one in this tiny hamlet of rock-walled homes and tree-limb  
fences was injured, but craters marked the nearby fields. 
</P>
<P>
	The Serb attacks have evoked fear and anger, causing many  
villagers to flee the border area while questioning why the 
Albanian government won't let them fight back. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have two choices -- to fight or to leave. But the government  
won't let us fight, so we must leave,'' said Bashkim Ahmati, riding 
on a small tractor hauling a wagonload of blankets, mattresses, 
clothes and other possessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Serb shelling and minor attacks have increased along the stretch  
of border between Albania and Kosovo, from the Morini crossing near 
Kukes to the Bajram Curri area further north. 
</P>
<P>
	The rebel Kosovo Liberation Army has training bases and supply  
routes into Kosovo, and has been fighting Yugoslav and Serb forces 
inside Kosovo for control of the border area. 
</P>
<P>
	Closer to Kukes, in the mountains above the town of Kruma, Serb  
shelling and gunfire on the villages below would normally provoke a 
military response from Albania, said Kraja, who carries an 
automatic rifle. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have firepower, but we are ordered to not reply, because  
all of this is political by the Serbs,'' he said, standing outside 
a home in the village of Ahmat. ``They want to spread the 
conflict.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A crater in a small garden in back of the house contained  
fragments of a mortar round. Red roof tiles along the edge were 
damaged or missing, and several windows were broken. 
</P>
<P>
	Xhelil Ahmati, an elderly villager wearing a white cone-shaped  
hat common in rural Albania, said the house belonged to his 
brother, who had fled a few days earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	An Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe worker  
said, on condition of anonymity, that Serb forces had increased 
border attacks in recent days, including firing a round that 
damaged an OSCE vehicle on Saturday in another village. 
</P>
<P>
	The worker also said the Serbs fired anti-tank missiles Friday  
at the Albanian border office at Qaf e Prushit, a closed border 
crossing above Kruma, setting the building on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	Kraja said most of Ahmat's 1,800 residents and the 2,000 Kosovo  
refugees staying with them had fled in recent days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have 13 refugees in my house,'' he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:22:01 </DATE_TIME>
