<DOCNO> APW19990503.0180 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball Snagger Shares His Secrets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Just call him the baseball kid.  
</P>
<P>
	Home runs, pop-ups, line drives, fungoes, foul tips and the  
occasional pepper throw -- Zack Hample has caught them all. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd watch the games on TV and see fans catch balls. The camera  
would focus on them, they'd hold up the ball, dance around and 
everybody would cheer. The first time I saw it happen at a game, I 
was hooked. I wanted a ball,'' Hample said. 
</P>
<P>
	Now -- more than 1,200 baseballs and 18 stadiums later -- the king  
of snagging balls hit or thrown by the pros is sharing his secrets 
in ``How to Snag Major League Baseballs,'' (Aladdin Paperbacks, 
$3.99, 140 pages). 
</P>
<P>
	There's the obvious: Bring a glove and sit in a section where  
you know a player regularly whacks the ball. ``You're more likely 
to get hit by lightning than catching a home run ball,'' says the 
21-year-old Manhattan native who goes to Guilford College in 
Charlotte, N.C. 
</P>
<P>
	But there are other surefire ways to get a game ball, he writes.  
The book -- one part biography and two parts tips with a splash of 
trivia -- takes readers on a step-by-step guide of how to leave a 
stadium with a baseball. 
</P>
<P>
	The process begins with when to arrive at a ballpark, how to get  
a player to throw a ball your way, how to sneak into better seats 
and where to sit to catch game balls. 
</P>
<P>
	There's also a section on baseball-catching ethics: Don't try to  
catch a ball meant for another fan during batting practice, don't 
steal a game ball out of somebody's glove, and always say thank 
you. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know this works because I have more than 1,200 balls,'' said  
Hample, who started writing the book two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	His father, Stuart Hample, an author of children's books, admits  
he enabled his son's baseball fever by letting him go to so many 
games. But he says he's thankful his son put his energy into 
something he enjoyed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that he took all this passion and put it into  
something and then was able to put it in a book is marvelous,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Hample began collecting balls in 1990 during a New  
York Mets game. Over time, he picked up tricks of his trade: Take 
both teams' hats to the game and learn different languages. 
</P>
<P>
	He caught his 1,000th ball in June 1996 at Shea Stadium. Then  
Atlanta Braves pitcher Pedro Borbon Jr. was heading to the bullpen 
when Hample asked him in Spanish: ``Dame la bola, por favor?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because he was wearing a Braves cap, Borbon threw him the ball.  
</P>
<P>
	Hample admits he goes to extremes for his ball-catching  
obsession -- jumping railings, seats and, sometimes, people. He's 
been scraped, cut, bruised and whacked in pursuit of baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	``The ball lasts forever, the injury goes away,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hample has every ball he's ever caught. All are documented and  
filed away -- literally. Most are stored in a four-drawer filing 
cabinet in his bedroom in his family's Manhattan apartment. The 
rest are stored in a plastic tub. 
</P>
<P>
	``Space has been a problem. But I'll sleep on them if I have  
to,'' he said. ``I'm not going to get rid of them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He's had plenty of offers though. For the very first ball he  
caught, he was offered $50. He turned the guy down, saying he 
wouldn't sell it for $500. 
</P>
<P>
	He's got a Mark McGwire ball thrown to him by the slugger, then  
a member of the Oakland Athletics, and he caught New York Yankee 
Mike Stanley's first home run of the 1992 season. 
</P>
<P>
	Mike Heffner of Leland's Auction House in New York says some of  
Hample's collection is probably worth big money. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are people out there who have spent millions of dollars  
on baseball collectibles,'' he said. ``If he's got more than 1,200 
balls, he's probably got something ... a collector would pay big 
money for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But for Hample, it's about catching balls.  
</P>
<P>
	``If I wanted to see a game, I would watch it on TV and have a  
better view,'' he said. ``I go to the game to catch baseballs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Now he's looking to catch a World Series ball and at least one  
ball in every major league stadium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
