<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Forest, Brush Fires Hit Northeast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BASS RIVER TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- Light rain today helped  
extinguish hot spots remaining from a weekend forest fire that 
charred more than 11,000 acres of southern New Jersey's Pine 
Barrens. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller fires burned brush and forest during the weekend  
elsewhere in the Northeast, including Vermont, Maine, New 
Hampshire, Connecticut and New York. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pine Barrens fire started Friday and was quickly spread by  
30 mph wind. 
</P>
<P>
	About two dozen people were evacuated from two campgrounds, but  
the camps reopened Saturday. No injuries were reported and the fire 
was declared under control Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere, the southern third of Shenandoah National Park in  
Virginia was closed to hikers and motorists today and campers were 
evacuated because a 1,000-acre forest fire. Park officials didn't 
know how many people were affected. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shenandoah fire started Saturday when wind carried an ember  
from a planned burn that was set to regenerate a declining species 
of pine that needs fire to reproduce, park officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	In upstate New York, fire crews were back at work today on a  
300-acre forest fire in rugged terrain near Rotterdam, about 15 
miles northwest of Albany. It briefly burned to with 100 feet of 
several houses. 
</P>
<P>
	New York had its second driest April on record, according to the  
National Weather Service. The state Department of Environmental 
Conservation rescinded all open fire permits last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Some 75 people were evacuated from their homes Sunday at  
Bellport, N.Y., about 75 miles east of New York City on Long 
Island, because of thick smoke from a 100-acre forest fire. The 
smoke also shut down part of a nearby highway and a branch of the 
Long Island Rail Road. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0182 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:31:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> St. Louis in Command Despite Tie </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- The St. Louis-Phoenix first-round series is even.  
That's not to say it's equal. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues are clearly in command going into Game 7 on Tuesday  
night, their power play so dominant the Coyotes have developed a 
siege mentality. And their speed tips the balance time after time. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues have outshot Phoenix 196-147, making up in volume what  
they lacked in efficiency while losing three straight games by 
one-goal margins. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coyotes, on the other hand, are on the verge of blowing a  
3-1 first-round lead for the third time in a decade, and worried 
about losing their coach if they do. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Blues' 5-3 victory Sunday in St. Louis, coach Jim  
Schoenfeld confirmed that his job is on the line if the Coyotes, 
who haven't advanced past the second round since 1987, make another 
early playoff exit. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coyotes had a 2-1 lead on Detroit last year, Schoenfeld's  
first with the team, before the Red Wings won the next three. The 
former Winnipeg Jets also led Edmonton 3-1 in 1990 and Vancouver 
3-1 in 1992, but lost each series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'd rather be going in having won two than losing two,'' St.  
Louis defenseman Al MacInnis said. ``Momentum is a funny thing, but 
we have it now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Former Coyote Jeff Finley said the Coyotes have reason to be on  
edge. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've had two chances to close it out and haven't been able  
to do it,'' he said. ``They've had leads in both games. Right from 
the start they've been saying how their franchise hasn't gotten 
past the first round, and they've put a little bit of pressure on 
themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MacInnis has two of St. Louis' nine power-play goals -- a  
playoff-series record by a Coyotes opponent -- and is the key on 
special teams. 
</P>
<P>
	Finley, another defenseman, was with Phoenix in 1997, when the  
Coyotes had a 3-2 lead on Anaheim but couldn't finish the Mighty 
Ducks. He represents a new factor -- the Blues' improvement 
throughout the series. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Coyotes won Game 3 by a 5-4 score despite being  
outshot 38-18, St. Louis coach Joel Quenneville began emphasizing 
the need to cash in on rebounds. 
</P>
<P>
	Finley, who had never scored a playoff goal, had two shots  
before he broke a 3-3 tie 8:59 into the third period. 
</P>
<P>
	``We wanted to get the rebounds, and we think that's going to be  
the difference in the series,'' said Craig Conroy, another tardy 
contributor who scored his first two goals Sunday. ``We've learned 
what we have to do, and we have to keep doing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	St. Louis is in its 20th consecutive postseason and swept  
Anaheim last year to advance for the second time in three years. In 
1991, the Blues overcame a 3-1 deficit to eliminate Detroit in the 
first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Coyotes forward Dallas Drake acknowledged the Blues' tenacity,  
but defended Schoenfeld's guarantee of a job-saving victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm right behind him on that one,'' Drake said. ``I think we  
have the team to do it, and I think everybody will step it up a bit 
and we'll get the job done and get this Winnipeg jinx, or whatever 
the media's calling it, off our backs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't ever want to hear it again.''  
</P>
<P>
	Team captain Keith Tkachuk, who had 36 goals in the regular  
season but just one this series, also believes the Coyotes will 
snap out of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The pressure is on to win; that's the bottom line,'' Tkachuk  
said. ``The pressure's on for them to win, too. We all feel we can 
beat this team.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
