<DOCNO> APW19990503.0183 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 07:25:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Asian Stock Markets Close Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday,  
with the key index in Jakarta surging almost 6 percent to its 
highest level in a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese financial markets were closed Monday for Constitution  
Day, a national holiday. The Thai stock market was also closed for 
a holiday. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares on the Jakarta Stock Exchange soared on buying by foreign  
investors encouraged by signs of an economic recovery and a 
stronger Indonesian currency. 
</P>
<P>
	The Jakarta Composite Index rose 5.7 percent, or 28.136 points,  
to 523.358 -- its highest close since April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	The Indonesian rupiah soared to a four-month high, trading at  
7,955 against the U.S. dollar compared with its close Friday of 
8,245 rupiah to the dollar. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the central statistics bureau said the Indonesian  
economy rose 1.34 percent from the fourth quarter to the first 
quarter, the first quarterly increase in growth since the country 
was hit by the financial crisis in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Share prices in Hong Kong closed generally mixed Monday, with  
the key index edging up slightly in lackluster trading. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hang Seng Index, the Hong Kong market's key indicator of  
blue chips, rose 3.87 points, or 0.02 percent, closing at 
13,337.07. On Friday, the index had gained 153.5 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Brokers said share prices fell in the morning session as  
investors took profits following recent sharp gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Hong Kong banks cut their deposit and prime lending rates by a  
quarter point on Friday but the move had little impact on the 
market as most investors had anticipated the cut. 
</P>
<P>
	Prices rebounded late in the afternoon on futures-related  
buying, brokers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine shares closed higher following another cut in key  
central bank overnight rates, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 30-company Philippine Stock Exchange Index (PSE Index) rose  
13.04 points, or 0.5 percent, to 2,446.74. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the central bank cut its overnight borrowing and  
lending rates by 0.125 percentage point to 10.25 and 12.25 percent, 
respectively. 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere:  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Share prices closed slightly higher. The market's key  
Weighted Stock Price Index rose 12.09 points, or 0.2 percent, to 
7,383.26. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: New Zealand shares closed lower, dragged down by a  
drop in the share price of New Zealand forest products concern 
Carter Holt Harvey Ltd. and market heavyweight Telecom Corp. of New 
Zealand Ltd. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index fell 21.01 points, 
or 0.9 percent, to 2,257.27. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed lower, with a round of  
profit-taking among banks, News Corp. and the telecommunications 
sector dragging the broader market down. The All Ordinaries Index 
fell 26.6 points, or 0.8 percent, to 3,074.5. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Share prices closed slightly higher. The Korea Composite  
Stock Price Index rose 3.94 points, or 0.5 percent, to 756.53. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Malaysian share prices closed mostly higher  
following an interest rate cut. The benchmark Composite Index rose 
2.97 points, or 0.4 percent, to 677.93. 
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mostly higher. The main Straits  
Times Index rose 12.05 points, or 0.6 percent, to 1,898.24. 

</P>
</TEXT>
