<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Group Names Enemies of Free Press </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Yugoslavia, China and Cuba are among the worst  
places in the world for journalists to do their jobs, according to 
a report by the Committee to Protect Journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Slobodan Milosevic, Jiang Zemin and Fidel Castro topped CPJ's  
list of ``Enemies of the Press,'' which was released for to 
coincide with today as World Press Freedom Day. 
</P>
<P>
	CPJ president Ann Cooper said the three rulers, as well as the  
leaders of seven other regimes around the world, ``knowingly acted 
to suppress information through countless violations against 
journalists, including censorship, imprisonment, physical attack 
and even murder.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Milosevic was cited for suppressing the press through  
``intimidation, assault, crippling fines, and license denials. ... 
Milosevic's repression of all independent media has quelled every 
opposition voice, imperiled journalists' lives, and filled the 
airwaves with hate speech.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jiang was accused of presiding over ``worsening conditions for  
politically independent journalists,'' including the shutdown of 
newspapers, magazines and publishers; and the jailing of 
journalists, including an Internet entrepreneur who provided an 
e-mail address to a dissident online magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	In Castro's Cuba, CPJ reports, independent journalists face  
arrest ``for even thinking about covering a trial of dissidents or 
a public demonstration.'' Since January, 28 journalists have been 
detained in Cuba and a new law criminalizes contact with foreign 
media if it is deemed in the service of U.S. interests against 
Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the list were:  
</P>
<P>
	--Democratic Republic of Congo's Laurent Kabila, accused by the  
CPJ of ``blaming his military failures on the independent press'' 
and of detaining more than 70 journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ethiopia's Prime Minister Meles Zenawi, described by the CPJ as  
``Africa's leading jailer of journalists,'' with 12 in prison at 
the end of 1998, and another 20 incarcerated during the year. 
</P>
<P>
	--Ukraine's President Leonid Kuchma, whose tax policies and fines  
have crippled media outlets, the CPJ said. Kuchma is also accused 
of ``tacit acceptance'' of newspaper office bombings and assaults 
on journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	--Tunisia's President Zine Abdine Ben Ali, described by the CPJ  
as banning foreign publications, blocking access to certain 
Websites, and harassing journalists ``who dare to veer from a path 
of strict self-censorship.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--Malaysia's Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad, accused by CPJ of  
controlling most major media, rewarding journalists who self-censor 
negative news, and harassing foreign press. 
</P>
<P>
	--Peru's President Alberto Fujimori, described by the CPJ as  
sponsoring a campaign to discredit Peru's independent press through 
death threats against journalists, wiretapping, surveillance, smear 
tactics and arrests. 
</P>
<P>
	--Egypt's President Hosni Mubarak, who approved a law that has  
led to censorship, newspaper shutdowns, and the jailing of 
journalists for libel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
