<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cooling It All Off Revamped US Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Air conditioning has transformed 20th century  
America, from dating habits through lawmaking to space exploration, 
and a cool new show at Washington's National Building Museum 
demonstrates how it happened. 
</P>
<P>
	Mechanical cooling got a boost in the summer of 1881 when Navy  
engineers jury-rigged the first system in the White House for 
President Garfield, who had been wounded by an assassin. Using 436 
pounds of ice an hour, the system helped keep him comfortable for 
58 days. Then they moved him to the breezier New Jersey shore, 
where he died a few weeks later. 
</P>
<P>
	``This field of study presents great opportunities for effecting  
a better condition of the atmosphere of our rooms ...,'' the 
engineers reported. ``Hospitals and public buildings ought to be 
specially protected ....'' 
</P>
<P>
	Novelist Gore Vidal noted one change a century later.  
</P>
<P>
	``Before air conditioning, Washington was deserted from mid-June  
to September,'' he wrote, but now ``Congress sits and sits while 
the presidents -- or at least their staffs -- never stop making 
mischief.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the first modern air conditioners served machines, not  
people. Cotton mills can't work efficiently if the building is dry 
-- the threads snap too often. Willis Carrier succeeded in 
controlling both temperature and humidity. That was called 
``conditioning'' the cotton, and the name ``air conditioning'' 
stuck. 
</P>
<P>
	Carrier Corp. won over 80 patents on the process as it developed  
and built a major business. 
</P>
<P>
	Carnegie Hall was air conditioned in 1899, the New York Stock  
Exchange in 1902. Congress resisted for another quarter-century. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think most of the members heretofore have had the feeling  
and the belief that there was a lot of foul air in the hall,'' Rep. 
John Sandlin, D-La., said in 1928. 
</P>
<P>
	That seems to have swayed Congress, but 15 years later President  
Franklin Roosevelt wouldn't have his office cooled. 
</P>
<P>
	Half a century later, some still dislike air conditioning. They  
talk of ``tight-building syndrome'' and the first spread of 
Legionnaire's disease through a cooling duct, of the drain on the 
supply of energy, windows they can't open and a feeling of 
isolation from the real world. But three out of every four homes 
now have some air conditioning and few residents would give it up. 
</P>
<P>
	House building has been revolutionized. Dating couples no longer  
enjoy the breezy dimness of the front-porch swing. Few new homes 
have a front porch, still less the privacy of one that goes around 
to the backyard as well. 
</P>
<P>
	``Architects don't think about putting awnings on windows, or  
eaves that overhang them,'' said Chrysanthe B. Broikos, associate 
curator of the exhibit, dubbed ``Stay Cool!'' ``They don't have to 
design L-shaped buildings or T-shaped buildings or H-shaped 
buildings -- you don't need cross-ventilation anymore.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The exhibit opens with a walk through a huge silvery air  
conditioning duct. It ends with a photo of a figure floating inside 
a spacecraft. 
</P>
<P>
	``There isn't any air in outer space at all,'' Ms. Broikos  
pointed out. 
</P>
<P>
	--------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Stay Cool! Air Conditioning America'' will be at the National  
Building Museum through Jan. 2. Admission is free, but a collection 
box at the entrance asks for contributions 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:25:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tigers' Moehler Suspended 10 Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. (AP) -- Brian Moehler isn't even bothering  
to appeal his automatic 10-day suspension for scuffing baseballs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Detroit Tigers pitcher was notified of the penalty by AL  
president Gene Budig on Monday, two days after Moehler was ejected 
from a game against Tampa Bay by umpire Larry Barnett, who said the 
right-hander doctored baseballs with sandpaper. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reason why we didn't appeal was I wanted to get this  
behind us,'' Moehler said before the Tigers' game Monday night at 
Tampa Bay. ``Whether we appeal or don't appeal, people have their 
own opinions. It comes down to me wanting to pitch and soon. I 
think that's the best thing to do and just move on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Moehler, 27, said it wasn't sandpaper, merely dirt, but said he  
didn't protest his ejection during a 4-3 loss because it's not his 
nature to ``argue until I'm blue in the face.'' True to his nature, 
he notified the players' association not to appeal Budig's 
decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is tough for me because I'm a competitor and I want to  
pitch,'' Moehler said. ``I want to be out there pitching. The 
toughest part is, you don't feel like you're contributing to the 
team. I just have to keep my head up and go out there and get my 
work done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barnett, the plate umpire, said he found a small piece of  
sandpaper attached to the pitcher's left thumb after the Devil Rays 
complained he appeared to be scuffing the ball. 
</P>
<P>
	Moehler yielded three runs on four hits in the first two  
innings, then allowed just one hit during a four-inning stretch. 
Tampa Bay players said the velocity and movement of Moehler's 
pitches changed dramatically. 
</P>
<P>
	Devil Rays manager Larry Rothschild said he didn't derive any  
satisfaction out of getting somebody thrown out of the game and 
later suspended, but added ``the rules are clearly stated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to stand up for what these players need, and that's  
a level playing field,'' said Rothschild. 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit manager Larry Parrish countered that scuffing is part of  
baseball, characterizing Tampa Bay's complaints -- as well as the 
decision to ask Barnett to check Moehler -- as ``bootleg.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There's not a pitching staff in baseball that doesn't have a  
guy who defaces the ball ... If the umpires want to check things 
like that, I think half to three-quarters of the league would be 
suspended, including some Tampa Bay Devil Rays,'' Parrish said. 
</P>
<P>
	Moehler is prepared for the attention he will likely receive  
from fans around the American League. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every city I go into this year, I'm going to hear something  
from somebody,'' Moehler said. ``It's going to happen. I'm prepared 
for it. You have leather skin and you keep moving on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Section 3.02 of the Official Baseball Rules calls for the 10-day  
suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1987, Philadelphia Phillies pitcher Kevin Gross was suspended  
for 10 days by NL president A. Bartlett Giamatti after Gross was 
caught with sandpaper in his glove. That same year, AL president 
Bobby Brown suspended Minnesota pitcher Joe Niekro for 10 days for 
carrying an emery board and sandpaper in his back pocket. 
</P>
<P>
	A 14-game winner in 1998, Moehler is 3-3 with a 4.23 ERA this  
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays scored the winning run on a sacrifice fly, two  
batters after he was ejected Saturday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
