<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:02:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanche Take 3-2 Lead to San Jose </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The Colorado Avalanche take the ice  
tonight at the San Jose Arena with a 3-2 playoff advantage over the 
San Jose Sharks, two series-opening victories in California, and a 
proven record on the road. 
</P>
<P>
	All that's left is winning.  
</P>
<P>
	``We know we're a good road team, and we have proven that all  
year,'' said right wing Theo Fleury. ``We finally got the job done 
at home, we've got the lead going back to San Jose. So let's just 
go in there, play another boring road game -- and end this series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Up 2-0 after the delayed series opened in San Jose, the  
Avalanche dropped their next two games at home before taking 
Saturday night's game, 6-2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks, a game away from elimination, face a daunting task.  
The Avalanche were 23-14-4 on the road during the regular season. 
</P>
<P>
	But the Sharks still think the home-ice advantage tonight could  
take the series back to Denver for Game 7. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't happy with our performance, but we came in and won  
two out of three and kept the series alive,'' San Jose forward Jeff 
Friesen said. ``We take the series back to the Shark Tank and will 
go back to work.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sharks also face a suddenly rejuvenated Fleury, who was  
fairly quiet early in the playoffs but came back with two goals and 
an assist Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a matter of time,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche, however, weren't looking past Monday's game  
despite their advantages, Fleury added. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a long way from over,'' he said. ``They're going to bring  
their best game Monday. ... We've got one hockey game to win, and 
it's the hardest one to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sharks coach Darryl Sutter gambled and put Steve Shields in goal  
Saturday, giving Mike Vernon a night off. Vernon has won Stanley 
Cups with Calgary and Detroit over the course of his career, but 
Shields was hot down the stretch of the regular season, going 9-0-2 
in his last 11 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	Sutter wasn't about to second-guess himself after the Game 5  
loss. Because of the delayed schedule, Vernon, 36, was facing a 
possible seven games in 11 nights. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was probably going to have one bad night if he did that, so  
we're probably better off that this was how it turned out,'' Sutter 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The series was supposed to have started in Denver, but was  
delayed because of the mass shooting at Columbine High School. 
Instead, the first two games were played in San Jose. 
</P>
<P>
	Vernon, no doubt, will be back for Game 6. He wasn't dwelling on  
what might have been, had he been in goal Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's why it's called a team game,'' he said. ``Everybody  
contributes. We just weren't prepared as a team (Saturday). Now we 
have to regroup.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:23:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Race Deaths Raise Safety Questions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.C. (AP) -- It was planned as a big opening act for the  
83rd Indianapolis 500. It turned instead into another deadly 
reminder of the dangers of being a spectator at auto races. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to go on,'' Indy Racing League founder Tony George  
said Sunday as authorities tried to piece together evidence from an 
accident in the VisionAire 500 that killed three spectators in the 
grandstands. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight other spectators were injured, including a 9-year-old girl  
who was in critical condition, when debris from a three-car wreck 
flew into the seats near the exit of the fourth turn at Lowe's 
Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Saturday night's race marked the first time in the four-year  
history of the IRL that a second event was scheduled for the month 
of May, which had been reserved exclusively for the circuit's 
marquee race, the Indianapolis 500. IRL officials thought holding a 
race in the cradle of stock-car country would help boost interest 
in their open-wheel series leading up to the May 30 event at Indy. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a business for us,'' George said. ``It's also a sport  
and a livelihood, and our fans who support us would want us to go 
on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 50,000 people were on hand at the suburban Charlotte  
track when the force of the crash at speeds near 215 mph rocketed a 
wheel and suspension parts over a 15-foot-high catch fence. The 
debris flew into the grandstands and slammed into spectators, some 
of them seated as high as 39 rows above the 1.5-mile, high-banked 
superspeedway. 
</P>
<P>
	As shrieking spectators sought help, rescue workers converged on  
the bloody area in a scenario eerily similar to that at Michigan 
Speedway last July 26, when three spectators were killed in a Champ 
Car race. The cause in that event also was a broken wheel and 
suspension parts that hurdled a catch fence. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every once in a while, unfortunately, auto racing raises the  
black side of itself,'' Lowe's Motor Speedway president H.A. 
``Humpy'' Wheeler said. 
</P>
<P>
	George, whose circuit has been fighting to overcome a thin  
schedule and a lack of high-dollar sponsors and big-name drivers, 
said the IRL has made big gains in safety and will keep trying to 
improve. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can't plan for every possible scenario,'' he said. ``We  
just do our level best, and unfortunately, sometimes that may not 
be enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Concord police said that because the accident occurred on  
private property and there didn't appear to be any criminal intent 
by anyone, they didn't plan any investigation but would assist if 
asked. Wheeler said the IRL and the speedway planned their own 
probes to augment the efforts of their insurers, ``to make sure 
that this never happens again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to keep wheels from flying off at impact, the  
Formula One circuit this year began requiring its teams to use 
tethers designed to keep the wheels and suspension connected to the 
main body of the machine. 
</P>
<P>
	Such tethers are not required on either Champ Cars or IRL  
machines, in part because some racing authorities think the devices 
may solve one problem while creating another. 
</P>
<P>
	Leo Mehl, executive director of the IRL, said there is concern  
that while tethers may prevent parts from flying off cars and 
hitting fans, they also may put drivers in greater danger because 
the parts could snap back and hit them instead. A tethered wheel 
also could be especially dangerous if it is launched into the 
stands in a slingshot fashion, Mehl said. 
</P>
<P>
	The IRL wants to study the issue more, Mehl said.  
</P>
<P>
	``You must be very cautious that you don't make regulations that  
will make things worse,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The height of Charlotte's catch fence conforms to industry  
standards, but it was difficult to tell how much higher the fence 
would have had to be to keep the debris from reaching the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have very little direct film of the accident,'' Mehl said.  
</P>
<P>
	The three people killed were Randy D. Pyatte, 21, and Jeff  
Patton, no age available, both of Connelly Springs, and Dexter B. 
Mobley, 41, of Statesville. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the eight people hospitalized were released by Sunday  
night. The lone exception was Hailey McGee, 9, of Conover, who was 
in critical condition at Carolinas Medical Center in Charlotte with 
bruises to her brain and lungs. 
</P>
<P>
	The accident occurred in the last race of a three-year  
sanctioning agreement between the IRL and the speedway, prompting 
questions about whether the track might not seek to renew its 
agreement with the circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	Further clouding the issue is the fact that the Charlotte track  
is owned by Speedway Motorsports Inc., which controls tracks that 
hold five of the 11 races on this year's IRL schedule. Should the 
IRL lose the support of SMI, it could spell serious trouble for the 
fledgling circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	But Wheeler, who in addition to running the Charlotte track also  
serves as SMI's president, said the company remains committed to 
helping the IRL establish itself as a low-cost alternative to the 
Champ Car circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have pretty strong feelings about the IRL,'' he said.  
``They're trying to do the right thing.'' 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 00:12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Avalanche Take 3-2 Lead to San Jose </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- The Colorado Avalanche take the ice  
