<DOCNO> APW19990503.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:25:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Tops $19 a Barrel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude futures rose Monday above $19 a barrel for the first time  
since 1997 on the New York Mercantile Exchange as traders bet world 
oil producers remain committed to slashing output despite sharply 
higher prices. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, wheat futures sank, as did palladium.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude briefly topped $19 before investors took profits, but  
analysts said the gains could continue in coming days if an 
upcoming report from the Organization of Petroleum Exporting 
Countries shows its members are adhering to promised cutbacks. 
</P>
<P>
	OPEC and other oil producers pledged to cut about 2.7 percent of  
daily supply from the market beginning in April in a bid to boost 
prices. Oil had been hovering at 12-year lows amid overproduction 
and weak world demand. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest in a series of promised cutbacks has caused prices to  
jump more than 50 percent in a few weeks as oil producers signal 
they are serious by reducing exports to key countries, including 
the United States and Japan. Those cutbacks have been reflected in 
weekly inventory data. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say the key to a sustain price rise, however, will be  
how long oil producers keep crude off the market. Previous 
agreements have produced few results in terms of price increases 
because of widespread cheating that left targets far off the mark. 
</P>
<P>
	Light, sweet crude for June delivery rose 19 cents to $18.85 a  
barrel, after earlier in the session topping $19 a barrel. June 
heating oil rose .27 cent to 45.73 cents a gallon; June unleaded 
gasoline rose .37 cent to 55.56 cents a gallon; June natural gas 
rose .58 cent to $2.311 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat futures were pressured on the Chicago Board of Trade by  
expectations a crop tour of winter wheat growing regions this week 
will find above-average yields that could lead to increased 
estimates for the early summer harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	While prices were lifted recently amid fears heavy rains in the  
Plains states could lead to disease, forecasts for drier, 
beneficial weather have caused investors to take that risk premium 
out of the market. 
</P>
<P>
	A bumper crop would come at a time when there still is plenty of  
last year's crop in storage amid a period of relatively weak export 
demand. 
</P>
<P>
	July wheat fell 4 cents to $2.64 a bushel.  
</P>
<P>
	Palladium fell sharply, below $300 an ounce, on the New York  
Mercantile Exchange amid expectations a supply shortage will ease 
rapidly with new shipments from Russia. 
</P>
<P>
	While Russia has yet to confirm large-scale shipments are  
underway after a five-month absence, traders of the industrial-use 
metal pointed to last week's large sale as confirmation of the 
fact. Russia controls nearly 80 percent of the world's palladium 
supply, a metal used in electronic and automobile emission-control 
devices. 
</P>
<P>
	June palladium tumbled $11.70 to $296.30 an ounce.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
