<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:29:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 2 IOC Ethics Cases To Get Review </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- The last two cases involving IOC  
members in the Salt Lake scandal will be reviewed by the 
committee's leadership Tuesday with the help of new evidence. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Olympic Committee's new ethics commission,  
meeting for the first time Monday, sent the cases of Australia's 
Phil Coles and South Korea's Kim Un-yong to the ruling executive 
board. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim is an executive board member and the highest-ranking  
official implicated in the scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	``A decision tomorrow (Tuesday) one way or the other will be  
taken in both cases,'' said executive board member Kevan Gosper, 
one of three IOC delegates on the new eight-member ethics panel. 
``If there's any further investigation to be done, that will be 
triggered tomorrow.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC vice president Keba Mbaye, the head of the new ethics panel,  
said new evidence had been received on both Kim and Coles, who have 
received the highest level of warnings from IOC investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the new data in Kim's case involved verification of a  
signature and other information. Mbaye declined to give details on 
Coles' case. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics commission decided that the board already had the  
cases under control and ``it would be counterproductive'' to 
reexamine them, Gosper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles has been cited for accepting travel and accommodation  
perks from Salt Lake City. He is under renewed scrutiny since his 
ex-wife claimed that representatives of Athens' unsuccessful bid 
for the 1996 Olympics gave the couple jewelry worth $6,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Gosper said he didn't know if Coles would need to appear again  
before Olympic investigators, and that he might abstain from a vote 
on his countryman. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim, the highest-ranking official implicated in the Salt Lake  
affair, could face expulsion if it is proved that he knew that the 
Salt Lake committee paid for his son's salary at a 
telecommunications company. 
</P>
<P>
	The ethics panel of top international personalities, including  
former U.S. Senate Majority Leader Howard Baker and former U.N. 
chief Javier Perez de Cuellar, was established in March as part of 
reforms in the wake of the Salt Lake scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten IOC members were expelled or resigned for receiving improper  
inducements during the campaign for the 2002 Winter Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Mbaye, said minor allegations involving some 30 members had  
arisen as a result of letters sent by the IOC to cities involved in 
Olympic bids going back several years. 
</P>
<P>
	The names -- half of which had already been dealt with in the  
Salt Lake investigation -- arose in letters from 26 Olympic 
candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	Gosper said the latest cases would be examined by the ethics  
commission. But in a conference call, Baker said the new panel 
``did not take jurisdiction of these matters. They were left with 
the executive council (board).'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mbaye refused to reveal the names, but said that the alleged  
infractions were minor. 
</P>
<P>
	Summaries of the cases later posted on the IOC's Web site did  
not contain members' names, and it appeared most of the cases 
already had been reported. Others were seemingly mundane actions, 
such as introducing the children of two members to ``academic 
institutions,'' and another member bringing two guests to a dinner 
with bid-city officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't read too much into it,'' Gosper said.  
</P>
<P>
	The ethics panel is meant to draw up ethical rules, study the  
Olympic bidding and selection process, ensure accountability and 
enforce compliance with a new code of conduct. 
</P>
<P>
	French Sen. Robert Badinter was put in charge of finalizing the  
new code. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker said the panel is going about the drafting ``carefully and  
slowly in a way calculated to make a real difference.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When it's finished, it will be a good document,'' he added.  
But many questions remained at Monday's session on what it would 
contain. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the challenges we have is to try to make it short  
enough so people read it,'' Baker said. ``There's a lot to learn 
and I'm trying to come up to speed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said the commission's priority was ``getting the machinery in  
place'' and hoped a draft of the new ethics code ``not only for 
members and officers of the IOC but those that do business with the 
IOC'' would be finished within 30 days. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker declined to say what ideas for the code were discussed.  
But he said the commission's goal was similar to that of the ethics 
panel headed by another former Senate majority leader, George 
Mitchell, which called for more openness and accountability in IOC 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the commission is off to a good start,'' Baker said.  
``I think it is a good initiative by the IOC. I think it is almost 
certain to succeed in its mission, and its mission in the final 
analysis is to make sure that a code of ethical conduct, clearly, 
succinctly sets out what is expected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other members are former Swiss President Kurt Furgler;  
former Canadian Olympic athlete Charmaine Crooks; and IOC executive 
member Chiharu Igaya of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC president Juan Antonio Samaranch hopes their moral clout  
will help repair the IOC credibility following the biggest scandal 
in its 105-year history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 14:55:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Up Vs. Euro, Yen </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rose against the yen and the euro  
Monday as the Dow industrials ran past 11,000 and another raft of 
positive economic news enhanced the United States' position as the 
strongest economy worldwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``The dollar loved it because of no inflation, no near-term  
(Federal Reserve) action, a booming stock market,'' said Jeremy 
Fand, foreign exchange strategist at BankBoston in Boston. ``All in 
all, good news for the dollar.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In late New York trading, the dollar was quoted at 120.31  
Japanese yen, up from 119.40 yen late Friday. The euro fell against 
the dollar, trading at $1.0567, down from $1.0582. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders bought dollars because they liked what they saw in the  
U.S. data released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest and dividend income rose in March, along with rental  
incomes and business owners' incomes. Spending last year on 
existing residential properties rose 0.8 percent. Commercial 
construction fell, but not enough to wipe out last month's 
increase. Government construction spending rose. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's data followed even stronger reports from Friday, which  
showed the U.S. economy growing at a robust 4.5 percent annual rate 
for the first three months of 1999 with inflation nearly 
non-existent. The lack of meaningful inflation made traders think 
the Federal Reserve will not take any immediate action to steer the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average rose all day, but made an extra  
push at the end of trading to rise 225 points to close at 
11,014.69, a new record. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our economy still rolls along,'' said Ricardo Gomes, head of  
foreign exchange at Republic National Bank. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar's rise against the yen was aided by the lack of  
announcements of new initiatives regarding Japan's recession during 
a Washington news conference with President Clinton and Japanese 
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi. Japanese markets were closed for a 
national holiday, keeping currency trading volume low. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar was quoted at 1.5236 Swiss francs, down from 1.5243,  
and 1.4470 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4587 late Friday. The 
British pound was quoted at $1.6093, up from $1.6090; British 
markets were also closed. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro no  
longer are traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed 
rate. Based on the euro rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8508 German 
marks, up from 1.8484; 6.2073 French francs, up from 6.1996; and 
1,831.50 Italian lire, up from 1,828.15. 


</P>
</TEXT>
