<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine School Crosses Removed in Hassle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The carpenter who built 15 large crosses  
for the victims of the Columbine High School has taken them all 
away because of controversy over two of the memorials naming the 
gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	Greg Zanis drove 14 hours from his home at Aurora, Ill., last  
week to erect an 8-foot cross for each of the 13 shooting victims 
and the two gunmen. 
</P>
<P>
	However, many people were angry that two of the crosses  
represented the killers. And on Friday, Brian Rohrbough, whose son, 
Daniel, was among those killed on April 20, took down the crosses 
for gunmen Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Zanis received so many nasty telephone calls about the 15  
crosses that he drove back to Littleton -- leaving Saturday 
afternoon and driving all night -- and removed them all early 
Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He thought the people were upset about them,'' his daughter,  
Maria, said from Aurora. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was so disturbed by the reaction he got,'' said Edie  
Hylton, manager of community service for Foothills Parks and 
Recreation District. ``He was trying to do something good.'' Zanis 
himself had no immediate comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The hundreds of people who arrived Sunday expecting to see the  
crosses were mystified. 
</P>
<P>
	``You build a memorial for someone, then you take it down? That  
doesn't make sense to me,'' said Wayne Haubenschild. 
</P>
<P>
	His 16-year-old son, Chris, who helped erect the crosses, said  
he wished they were still planted in the park. 
</P>
<P>
	``People look at that (the crosses), and they know that violence  
is really bad,'' Chris Zanis said. ``It helps them to let (their 
grief) out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rohrbough also was unhappy at Zanis' action.  
</P>
<P>
	``He should have left the 13 other crosses standing,'' Rohrbough  
said Sunday. ``Instead of doing the right thing to honor the 
victims of those two murders, he comes back and tears down whole 
thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Sunday afternoon, an unidentified man erected one large,  
wooden cross near the spot where Zanis' memorials had stood. 
</P>
<P>
	``People don't realize what the cross means to the Christians  
who came to the park to remember and mourn,'' Chris Odom, 32, said 
as he looked at the new cross. ``It's a symbol of forgiveness and 
healing.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
