<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cubans Cheer National Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAVANA (AP) -- Cubans rushed home early from work and crowded  
around television sets to cheer their hometown baseball heroes 
during their historic rematch with the Baltimore Orioles at Camden 
Yards. 
</P>
<P>
	The childhood home of Cuban baseball's biggest stars, Javier  
Mendez, was packed with relatives and neighbors watching the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am so proud of my son because he fought hard to be on the  
Cuban team,'' said his father, Javier Mendez Cuadrado, 58. ``Over 
there, we have him defending the Cuban flag.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The father said he hoped the game would help bring the American  
and Cuban people closer together. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sports has nothing to do with politics,'' he said. ``We have  
nothing against the American people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is so moving seeing him up there,'' added the player's  
mother, Mirna, who looked overwhelmed as she watched her son on the 
television set. ``For this he worked so hard, to play for his 
country.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also crowded into the living room of the Mendez family's modest  
home was the player's 82-year-old paternal grandmother, who 
traveled 373 miles to be with her family as she watched her 
grandson play. 
</P>
<P>
	The streets were virtually deserted throughout the neighborhood  
just outside the Havana city limits in the community of Santa Fe. 
Just one uniformed police officer walked the streets outside. 
</P>
<P>
	The street cop was among the very few Cubans not glued to the  
television. 
</P>
<P>
	``Who isn't watching the game in Cuba tonight?'' asked Jose  
Antonio Arenas, a worker at a newspaper stand surrounded by 
neighbors struggling to see the game on his small set. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wouldn't miss this game for anything,'' Leonor Limonta said  
as she walked down the stairs of her apartment building to catch 
the game on a television inside a nearby pastry shop. 
</P>
<P>
	Baker Alejandro Zabater let the shop patrons take over the set  
and change it from the highly popular Colombian soap opera, ``Aroma 
de Mujer (Scent of a Woman),'' to the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Partner, I'll do it,'' said a young man who gave his name only  
as Alexander. ``We've got to see this game against the Yuma,'' he 
added, using a colloquial term used to describe Americans. ``We're 
going to win!'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the very few not watching Monday night was Ariel Perez,  
who drives a bicycle taxi in Central Havana. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure, I'd like to see the game,'' he said. ``But I have to  
work. My economic situation is not good.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
