<HEADLINE> Change in Colo. Victims' Crosses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BIG ROCK, Ill. (AP) -- A man who erected 15 large wooden crosses  
in Colorado to memorialize those who died at Columbine High School 
says he will change the display after the two crosses for the 
gunmen were torn down. 
</P>
<P>
	``I couldn't believe people were angry and defiled the  
crosses,'' Greg Zanis said after the two crosses for the killers, 
Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, were torn down. Harris and 
Klebold committed suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got involved in this whole process to help with healing,''  
Zanis said Monday. ``When I found out the crosses were not healing, 
I was saddened by it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He says families in Colorado had asked him to make the trip to  
memorialize the Columbine shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	Zanis established Crosses for Losses in tribute to his  
father-in-law, who was fatally shot in 1996. Since then he has 
built more than 200 crosses and raised them around the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday afternoon, as the 48-year-old general contractor put six  
crosses together for a trip to New Mexico, where children had been 
killed in a bus accident, Zanis announced he will stop again in 
Colorado. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he has been asked to return by several people in  
Littleton, including the families of three victims. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to put 13 (crosses) on one hill, and two on another  
hill,'' he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
