<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Buena Vista President Vogel Resigns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *With AM-Disney-Slump    	
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- David Vogel, who oversaw the production of  
family films such as ``George of the Jungle,'' stepped down Monday 
as president of the Walt Disney Co.'s Buena Vista Motion Pictures 
Group, saying he had lost the autonomy to run the studio as he 
liked. 
</P>
<P>
	Vogel was replaced by Buena Vista executive vice president Todd  
Garner and former DreamWorks SKG executive Nina Jacobson, who will 
act as co-presidents. 
</P>
<P>
	Vogel, named president of Buena Vista last year, said his  
ability to run the studio had eroded since the appointment in 
January of Peter Schneider as president of The Walt Disney Studios, 
whose role included oversight of Buena Vista. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm leaving because of the reorganization that was announced  
early this year, that changed my autonomy in terms of Disney live 
action,'' Vogel said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	``... I wouldn't say it was so much a personality conflict as it  
was a change of management structure,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	During nine years as a Disney executive, Vogel oversaw the  
production of popular family fare that also included the ``Mighty 
Ducks'' films, ``101 Dalmatians'' and ``Cool Runnings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Disney executives did not respond to a request for comment on  
Vogel's statement. In a news release, Disney Studios chairman Joe 
Roth said Vogel is one of the top production executives in the 
industry ``and we're sorry to see him go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garner, a nine-year Disney veteran, has developed such films as  
``The Waterboy,'' ``Father of the Bride'' and ``Con Air.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jacobson joined Walt Disney Pictures last year and has worked on  
two films, ``Mission to Mars'' and ``The Sixth Sense,'' both of 
which have yet to be released. At DreamWorks, she developed scripts 
and oversaw production for several films, including ``What Lies 
Beneath.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
