<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Texas Cities Choose Mayors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- In by far the lightest voter turnout in 30 years,  
Dallas Mayor Ron Kirk has easily won re-election to a second 
four-year term. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk captured almost three-fourths of the 38,000 votes cast, a  
turnout of about 5 percent, in beating Margaret Donnelly, an 
immigration lawyer seeing office for the first time, and Billy Jack 
Ludwig, an investor making his sixth mayoral bid since 1976. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Donnelly got about 20 percent of the vote and Ludwig less  
than 5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1995, Kirk became Dallas' first black mayor, and as a result  
of Saturday's voting, minorities will make up a majority of the 
15-member Dallas City Council for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a ratification of what we accomplished the last  
four years. The people feel good about the direction of the city,'' 
Kirk said. 
</P>
<P>
	Kirk, a lawyer and former Texas secretary of state, promised to  
focus his second term on fixing Dallas streets, keeping the city 
safe and promoting economic development in south Dallas, the 
poorest part of town. 
</P>
<P>
	Four other major Texas cities -- San Antonio, El Paso, Abilene  
and Brownsville -- also had mayoral elections Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	In San Antonio, Mayor Howard Peak took 85 percent of the votes  
in a five-way race, with a 7.5 percent turnout. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a great victory, not just for me, but for the  
bonds,'' said Peak as voters also approved a $140.2 million package 
to improve streets, drainage, flood control, parks and recreation, 
libraries and public safety. 
</P>
<P>
	El Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez pulled in 56 percent in beating  
three other candidates. 
</P>
<P>
	The only incumbent to fall was Henry Gonzalez in Brownsville,  
who was defeated by Blanca Sanchez Vela, wife of a federal judge. 
With all ballots counted, Ms. Vela received 4,700 votes, or 56 
percent to Gonzalez's 44 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In Abilene, Grady Barr, former president of the Abilene Chamber  
of Commerce, was elected mayor with 63 percent of the vote, 
defeating A.R. ``Fal'' Falcioni. The incumbent, Gary McCaleb, did 
not seek re-election. 
</P>
</TEXT>
