<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Colo. Officials Warn of Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JACKSON, Miss. (AP) -- Colorado officials told the nation's  
attorneys general to prepare for the kind of school violence that 
recently turned one of their affluent suburbs into a battleground. 
</P>
<P>
	``Six weeks ago I would have said that this is the last place in  
America that school violence like this could happen,'' said Dave 
Thomas, district attorney of Jefferson County, Colo., where the 
Columbine High shootings occurred. ``But I am here to tell you that 
it can happen everywhere.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas told participants at the two-day National Association of  
Attorneys General summit on youth and school violence that 
Littleton, Colo., is a white-collar, middle class area where 
students aren't faced with the limits of poverty and neglect that 
are often associated with violence. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has everything you would think that you would need to  
prevent school violence,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	However, none of that stopped Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan  
Klebold, 17, from going into Columbine High School on April 20 and 
killing 12 students and one teacher before shooting themselves. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado Attorney General Ken Salazar said addressing violence  
committed by minors on and off school campuses must become a top 
priority in all states. 
</P>
<P>
	And better relations among politicians can result in better  
programs to detect youth and school violence, said Troy Eid, chief 
legal counsel to Colorado Gov. Bill Owens. 
</P>
<P>
	``You do not build trust in a time of urgency, do it now while  
you can,'' Eid said. ``Because if times get tough you're going to 
need one another.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ari Zavaras, Colorado's public safety director, urged the  
attorneys general to get their law enforcement agencies, community 
leaders and policy makers together for possible violence in their 
states. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do any of you think this will be the last time this happens?''  
he asked. ``Because I'm sure don't.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
