<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smith-De Bruin Appeals Drug Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- Triple Olympic gold medallist  
Michelle Smith-De Bruin appealed to an international panel Monday 
to overturn her four-year drug ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Lennon, Smith-De Bruin's lawyer, told the International  
Court of Arbitration for Sport that the swimmer had been denied ``a 
reasonable judgment'' and that FINA, swimming's world governing 
body, had failed to prove she had tampered with a urine sample. 
</P>
<P>
	Lennon said the decision last August by a FINA doping panel  
``was patently unsound.'' FINA held Smith-De Bruin responsible for 
tampering with the out-of-competition urine test taken at her home 
in Kilkenny, Ireland. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't have to prove my innocence here,'' Smith-De Bruin told  
the tribunal when asked whether she had tampered with the sample. 
</P>
<P>
	The panel heard the accounts of Smith-De Bruin and Albert Guy,  
who with his wife, Kay, supervised the collection of the sample. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither could say how the sample could have been contaminated,  
but Guy said he noticed ``a sweetish, somewhat sickly odor'' when 
it was decanted into containers for processing. 
</P>
<P>
	FINA said the sample was contaminated with large amounts of  
alcohol, probably whiskey. 
</P>
<P>
	Guy said he watched the decanting in Smith-De Bruin's kitchen  
and that he didn't comment on the odor because he couldn't tell 
where it was coming from. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith-De Bruin said there was a brief period when she took her  
eyes off the sample as she went to get a drink of water. 
</P>
<P>
	FINA lawyer Jean-Pierre Morand said it was clear that someone  
had tampered with the samples before they came under the control of 
FINA. 
</P>
<P>
	``For us this case is a case of tampering,'' Morand told the  
three-arbitrator panel. ``Something happened with those samples, 
and I don't think it can be disputed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ban includes the Sydney 2000 Olympics and the 2001 World  
Championships, and effectively ends the 28-year-old Irish swimmer's 
career. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am fighting for my reputation and for my right to go to  
Sydney,'' Smith-De Bruin said after the ban was handed down. 
</P>
<P>
	Smith had a mediocre record before capturing three gold medals  
and a bronze at the Atlanta Games, three years after Erik de Bruin 
became her coach. 
</P>
<P>
	Her marriage to de Bruin, the Dutch discus and shot put champion  
banned for four years after testing positive to excessive 
testosterone, stirred speculation that her own meteoric rise had 
been aided by drugs. But she said she had been tested more often 
than any of her rivals and each time the result was negative. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
