<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cause of Ark. Boat Accident Sought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- Investigators said Monday they will  
take underwater pictures of the boat that dragged 13 tourists to 
their deaths in seconds in hopes of learning how the accident 
happened. 
</P>
<P>
	The World War II-vintage tourist boat had been in the repair  
shop just two days before it sank in Lake Hamilton on Saturday, 
drowning 13 of its 21 passengers. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators want to know if repair work done to the boat's  
drive-shaft was the cause of the accident, or if two other seals in 
the boat's hull were responsible. They say a videotape of the wreck 
on the lake bottom will help. 
</P>
<P>
	``The interest is to document the condition of the vessel before  
they attach devices to lift it to the surface so we make sure we 
don't see salvage-imposed damage when it gets to the surface,'' 
said Capt. Glenn Anderson, chief of the Coast Guard's 
investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators concentrated on the possible failure of three  
separate seals on the vessel -- 4-inch drain plugs on the boat's 
thin, metal bottom; rubber boots on the wheel casings; and a 1-inch 
sealed drive-shaft opening. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said the amphibious boat -- called a ``duck'' because  
it can travel on both land and water -- sank in a matter of seconds 
as passengers scrambled for life preservers, which were not 
required to be worn on the vessel. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said water pouring through a 4-inch hole would have  
caused the boat to sink as swiftly as it did. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Powers said that, when he first noticed water pooling in  
the stern of the boat, he stood up and started throwing life vests 
at other passengers. He last saw his wife, Danna, 32, as she 
struggled to fit a life vest over the head of their 8-year-old 
daughter, Madeline, he said. The girl survived; his wife died. 
</P>
<P>
	``I tossed them the jacket and said `Get out of here now,'''  
said Powers, 34, of Little Rock. ``It was that quick. We were under 
water.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some victims -- especially those near the center of the vessel --  
may have been prevented from swimming free by an overhead canopy. 
Most of the victims were found still inside the sunken boat. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said his formal report to the Coast Guard would include  
recommendations for changing the rules about wearing life 
preservers and installing canopies that can more easily be 
punctured if a boat sinks. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators for the National Transportation Safety Board  
obtained copies Monday of maintenance records from the shop where 
the fleet of White and Yellow Duck Tour boats operated by Land and 
Lake Tours Inc., are serviced. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials said they had not had time to review the records. An  
attorney for mechanics Bill Woodall and Mike Oliver said a leaky 
accordion-shaped rubber boot on the boat's main drive shaft was 
replaced Friday. He said Oliver did the work and called it routine. 
</P>
<P>
	``They feel bad about it,'' attorney Morse U. Gist Jr. said.  
``What they've told me is that they've gone over and over in their 
minds anything that they could have done that was not done 
correctly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And the NTSB began its own under-oath interviews Monday, with  
the owner of the company that operated the boat, the mechanics and 
drivers. 
</P>
<P>
	Q. Byrum Hurst, lawyer for Land and Lake Tours, said employees  
were cooperating fully with the NTSB. He also said the company was 
conducting its own internal investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Anderson said tour boats operating in the Hot Springs area,  
including the boat that sank, had received a clean bill from 
inspections done in February. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no laundry list of wrong things,'' he said. ``That  
was a clean bill.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Contractors were to arrive Tuesday to videotape the vessel,  
which sits under 50 feet of murky water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
