<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:25:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Voting Begins in Nepalese Elections </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KATMANDU, Nepal (AP) -- Wearing caps and capes in party colors,  
Nepalese waited in long lines today to elect a new parliament while 
security forces stood guard against more attacks by Maoist 
guerrillas. 
</P>
<P>
	Police told voters to leave guns at home and walk to polling  
stations for Nepal's third election in eight years. Cars, buses and 
other vehicles were banned from the streets as a security 
precaution after two weekend attacks left two policemen and three 
rebels dead and five officials seriously wounded. 
</P>
<P>
	The insurgents have asked people to boycott the elections.  
</P>
<P>
	Two party activists were shot today during an attack on Madhav  
Kumar Nepal, general secretary of the United Marxist-Leninist 
Communist Party of Nepal in Saruhata village, 120 miles south of 
Katmandu, said politburo member Pradeep Nepal. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the gun-mounted military jeeps patrolling Katmandu, the  
capital took on a party atmosphere among the hundreds who waited 
more than an hour to vote. Communist supporters donned white caps 
with red stars blazing in the sun. National Democratic Party 
activists wrapped themselves with blue and green party flags. 
</P>
<P>
	The carnival mood was a sharp contrast to the poorly attended  
campaign rallies. Many voters expect Nepal's 30 parties to split 
the 205-seat parliament and produce another hung legislature or 
weak government. 
</P>
<P>
	Rampant corruption, stagnant development and the Maoist  
insurgency are the key national issues. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest polls showed the centrist Nepali Congress slightly  
ahead of its main rival, the United Marxist-Leninist Communist 
Party of Nepal, which has suffered a major split since the last 
elections. The two parties are partners in the present caretaker 
administration. 
</P>
<P>
	``Most political parties have split in the past year and the  
votes are going to be divided,'' said Meena Tuladhar, a housewife. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly 45,000 policemen were guarding polling stations today in  
34 districts. Hundreds of soldiers were on standby. 
</P>
<P>
	A second round of voting for the other 41 districts was  
scheduled for May 17 to give security forces the chance to guard 
those polling stations. 
</P>
<P>
	Results will be announced May 18.  
</P>
<P>
	The rebels are demanding an end to Nepal's constitutional  
monarchy and reform of the centuries-old feudal structure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 06:25:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
