<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Okla. Twister Stuns Residents </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOORE, Okla. (AP) -- As far as the eye could see there was  
debris. Just debris. Not one house stood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Oh my God! Oh my God!'' one woman yelled. Others just  
wandered, stunned. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's gone,'' LeeAnn Richardson said as she looked toward where  
her home once stood along Regency Street in this Oklahoma City 
suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were just standing in there and looking at the weather on  
television,'' Ms. Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	They ran to their storm cellar when clouds rolled in and rain  
started pouring down. Sixteen people and four pets were in the 
storm cellar. All survived without injury. 
</P>
<P>
	``We opened up and everything was gone,'' Ms. Richardson said.  
</P>
<P>
	Phillip and Jennifer Schantz stood in the front yard where their  
home used to be. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just bought this house,'' Mrs. Schantz said as she clung to  
her young daughter and wept. They weren't home when the storm hit 
about 7:30 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Rows and rows of houses were destroyed. Trucks were overturned.  
Firefighters from nearby Norman battled a house that was ablaze. 
</P>
<P>
	Power lines and piles of carpet were everywhere.  
</P>
<P>
	Catherine Meyers sat on the tailgate of a pickup truck that was  
being used by a Red Cross volunteer. Injured people waited for 
ambulances. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Meyers hid under a mattress when the storm blew over her  
home. Afterward, she bled from the head and her right arm. 
</P>
<P>
	``My mattress didn't help me,'' she said. ``I got hit four or  
five times on the head by something. I've lost a lot of blood.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Her husband, Melvin, injured his right knee and left wrist. He  
bled from the head. He said he hid under a different mattress that 
was sucked up out of the house when the roof blew off. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first burst it took it out of there. Part of the ceiling  
fell in on me and shaded me,'' Meyers said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were in our storm cellars. We were watching TV and I knew  
to get into the storm cellar. I could feel it going over -- the 
pressure in your ears,'' Rhonda Hall said as she stood in the 
driveway of her home. 
</P>
<P>
	Her roof and the north wall were missing. She said her husband  
and two pets were in the storm cellar. No one was hurt. 
</P>
<P>
	Loretta and Theresa Jones said they survived the storm by hiding  
in their closet in their home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We heard it coming and -- Whoa, Whoa, Jesus -- we called on his  
name and I felt his arms come around us and saved us from that 
tornado. And I thank God for that,'' Theresa Jones said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
