<HEADLINE> Dow Jones Ends Above 11,000 Points / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average sped past  
11,000 Monday, shattering the record for the fastest rise between 
1,000-point milestones. 
</P>
<P>
	The index of 30 blue chip stocks rose 225.65 to close at  
11,014.69. It took just 24 trading days for the Dow to move from 
10,000 to 11,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Even by the compressed standards of the modern stock market, the  
latest milestone arrived with remarkable speed. The previous record 
for 1,000-point gains -- from 6,000 to 7,000 -- was 89 trading days 
from October 1996 to February 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's close was also Dow's fourth record high in the last  
five trading sessions. 
</P>
<P>
	Two more reports of an ebullient economy -- showing consumer  
spending up and manufacturing continuing to grow -- pushed the 
stocks of big corporate names higher. That aided the Dow and the 
Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 stock index, which also recorded a healthy 
gain of 19.45 to 1,354.63. But investors continued to dump Internet 
shares, pushing the Nasdaq composite index down 7.27 to 2,535.58. 
</P>
<P>
	On a percentage basis, Monday's Dow speed record is not  
comparable to the previous mark. The move from 6,000 to 7,000 was a 
16 percent rise, while the move from 10,000 to 11,000 was only 10 
percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the Dow's rise above 11,000 ``is truly remarkable; it's  
breathtaking,'' said Hugh Johnson, market strategist at First 
Albany Corp. ``I didn't suspect that I would be talking about Dow 
11,000 this year, let alone at the beginning of May.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ralph Acampora, director of technical research at Prudential  
Securities, said the market was much stronger now than it was five 
weeks ago. When the Dow passed 10,000, investors were excited, but 
also wary because the advance was made on just a few stocks in the 
technology, telecommunications and pharmaceutical sectors, and a 
few other industries. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past five weeks, the market's roster of leaders has  
broadened to include manufacturing and basic-materials companies 
that had been out of favor for years. 
</P>
<P>
	That means the market -- and the economy -- are much stronger than  
they were a short month ago, Acampora said. ``It's like driving a 
brand new car out of the showroom, and this thing doesn't have a 
nick on it. That's a real move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing and industrial shares rose Monday after investors  
got two fresh reminders that the economy is strong, but not 
inflationary. The National Association of Purchasing Management's 
index of manufacturing activity declined 1.5 percentage points, to 
52.8 percent, in April. That indicated that the manufacturing 
sector is still expanding, but at a slower rate than before. 
Analysts had expected the index to rise 2.2 percent. The slower 
rate quelled fears of inflation among some traders. 
</P>
<P>
	And the Commerce Department reported that Americans' personal  
income rose 0.4 percent in March, but their spending kept pace, 
leaving the nation's savings rate at a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	After the purchasing managers' report, bond prices erased early  
losses. The yield on the 30-year Treasury bond, which moves in the 
opposite direction from price, closed at 5.65 percent, down from 
5.66 percent late Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Influenced by the rise in bond prices, financial stocks  
recovered from a weak opening to end higher. Dow component J.P. 
Morgan added 2 5/8 to 137 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was also led higher by such industrial stalwarts as  
Minnesota Mining &AMP; Manufacturing, up 4 7/8 to 93 7/8; United 
Technologies, up 3 1/2 to 148 3/8; and Goodyear Tire and Rubber, up 3 5/8 to 
60 3/4. 
</P>
<P>
	Oil stocks, which have benefited lately from strong oil prices,  
were also big winners. Exxon gained 3 to 86 1/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Internet and some technology stocks took a drubbing  
as investors continued last week's strategy of taking profits. 
America Online slid 9 5/8 to 133 1.7 in leading volume on the New York 
Stock Exchange. Microsoft shed 1 5/8 to 79 11/16 in leading Nasdaq 
volume. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a strong 2-to-1 margin  
on the New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated NYSE volume came to 
985.58 million shares, down from Friday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 9.88 to 644.18, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 9.70 to 786.67. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.47 to 433.28. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign stock markets, the Tokyo exchange was closed for the  
first day of a 3-day holiday and will resume trading on Thursday. 
The London market was closed for the May Day holiday. In Paris, the 
CAC index rose 0.85 percent, while the DAX in Frankfurt added 0.4 
percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
