<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 126 but Nasdaq Falls 26 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Blue-chip stocks were mostly higher in late  
afternoon, as strong consumer and manufacturing data boosted 
economically sensitive names, but technology stocks were lower as 
investors continued to unload Internet stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 126.28 at 10,915.32, a record high. On Friday the Dow ended 
89.34 lower at 10,789.04, after coming within 39 points of 11,000 
and setting three record highs last week. The Dow closed at a 
record 10,878.38 last Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 5.87 at 1,341.05, but the Nasdaq composite index was 
down 26.04 at 2,516.81. 
</P>
<P>
	Manufacturing shares took off this morning, pushing the Dow  
higher, after a report from the National Association of Purchasing 
Management showed that its index of manufacturing activity declined 
1.5 percentage points, to 52.8 percent, in April. The survey 
indicated the manufacturing sector is expanding, but at a slower 
rate. Analysts had expected the index to rise 2.2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The NAPM report followed an earlier report from the Commerce  
Department that showed Americans' personal income rose 0.4 percent 
in March, but their spending kept pace, leaving the nation's 
savings rate at a record low. 
</P>
<P>
	After the purchasing managers' report, bond prices erased early  
losses. The 30-year Treasury bond was yielding 5.66 percent. The 
strength in the bond market helped push manufacturing stocks 
higher, said William Meehan, chief market analyst for Cantor 
Fitzgerald. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds ``got a nice bounce off the (manufacturing) report, which  
came in a little bit weaker than expected,'' Meehan said. The 
recovery in bond prices in turn helped stocks, he added. ``You'd 
have a difficult time moving cyclicals, or anything else, if you 
continued to see the bond market going lower.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was led higher by industrial shares Minnesota Mining &AMP;  
Manufacturing, up 3 3/4 at 92 3/4; United Technologies, up 2 3/4 at 147 5/8, 
and Goodyear, up 2 3/4 at 59 15/16. Oil stocks, which have benefitted 
lately from strong oil prices, were higher again today. Dow 
component Exxon was up 2 3/4 at 85 13/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial stocks were mixed. American Express was up 11/16 at  
131 3/8, but Citigroup was off 7/8 at 74. Richard Cripps, chief market 
strategist for Legg Mason in Baltimore, said that was a sign that 
the stock advances may not hold. 
</P>
<P>
	``The financials are one of those groups that we probably should  
watch here because they are an indicator of what the bond market is 
likely to do,'' Cripps said. ``I'd say their mixed showing is not a 
strong indicator that this market can continue to go higher. It 
could be an indication that the Dow is overstating'' the market's 
strength. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks were lower as investors continued last week's  
strategy of taking profits in them. AOL was down 7 5/8 at 135 1/8 in 
leading volume on the New York Stock Exchange, and Microsoft was 
down 2 9/16 at 78 3/4 in leading volume in Nasdaq trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues led decliners by 7 to 4 on the New York Stock  
Exchange, where volume came to 619.34 million shares, down from 
Friday's pace. 

</P>
</TEXT>
