<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A television reporter said in an interview  
published Monday that he was told what questions to ask when he 
interviewed the country's security chief. 
</P>
<P>
	The interview with national security adviser Vladimiro  
Montesinos last week on the television news program ``Revista 
Dominical'' had been advertised as the ``interview of the 
century.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Alamo Perez, the reporter who conducted the interview, was  
quoted as saying by El Comercio, Peru's leading newspaper, that 
doing ``the interview meant not touching certain issues.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The revelation came a day after The New York-based Committee to  
Protect Journalists labeled Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori one 
of the 10 world leaders who most violate press freedom. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the first time in Fujimori's nine years in power that the  
secretive Montesinos had given an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAO PAULO, Brazil (AP) -- The government of a southern state and  
General Motors Corp. announced Monday that they had reached an 
agreement allowing the U.S. automaker to complete its new assembly 
plant there. 
</P>
<P>
	The agreement came after a month of negotiations following the  
decision by officials in the state of Rio Grande do Sul to stop 
disbursement of several million dollars in loans and other 
incentives earmarked for the world's largest automaker. 
</P>
<P>
	The state government's press office said further details of the  
agreement would be announced later this week by Gov. Oilivio Dutra 
and the president of GM's Brazilian subsidiary, Frederick 
Henderson. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Ford Motor Co. scuttled its plans to build its $1  
billion factory in Rio Grande do Sul. Construction of the Ford 
plant, which was expected to begin making 120,000 cars a year in 
2001, was in its initial stages. Ford said it would build its plant 
elsewhere in Brazil, but gave no indication where. 

</P>
</TEXT>
