<HEADLINE> Boston Waits for Next Opponent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- The Boston Bruins spent Monday waiting to face the  
great unknown. 
</P>
<P>
	Who would they play next in the NHL playoffs? And what would it  
be like to reach the second round where few of them have been? 
</P>
<P>
	``This is new for a lot of guys,'' forward Rob DiMaio said.  
``Now the attention is going to get greater. The mental mistakes 
can't be made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	DiMaio was in the minority among the 19 Bruins who suited up for  
Sunday night's 2-0 victory over the Carolina Hurricanes that 
clinched the Eastern Conference quarterfinal series four games to 
two. 
</P>
<P>
	He was one of seven players in that group who reached the second  
round before. The other 12 aren't sure what's in store. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of experience was handed around (in Sunday's) game,  
because a lot of guys haven't been beyond the first round before 
and now guys are believing,'' goalie Byron Dafoe, one of the 
second-round newcomers, said a few minutes after the victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bruins' next opponent hinges on the outcome of Tuesday  
night's seventh game between New Jersey and Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	If New Jersey wins, Boston will open the best-of-7 second round  
at Toronto. If Pittsburgh wins, Boston starts at home against 
Buffalo. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's Toronto, they're the top offensive team in the league,  
so, obviously, they can bring it and they have pretty good 
goaltending,'' DiMaio said. ``If it's Buffalo, their goaltender 
(Dominik Hasek) can beat you on his own.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least the Bruins, who thrived on defense, have shown a  
balanced scoring attack in the playoffs. Eleven players contributed 
to the 16 goals they scored against the Hurricanes. 
</P>
<P>
	Young forwards like Anson Carter, 24, and Joe Thornton, 19, made  
key contributions. Carter scored the winning goal in a 4-3, 
double-overtime win in Game 5. And he and Thornton, the top pick in 
the 1997 draft, scored in Game 6. 
</P>
<P>
	``Carter and Thornton stepped it up. Their future is unlimited  
as to how good they could be,'' said captain Ray Bourque, in his 
19th playoffs in his 20-year career that began about three months 
after Thornton was born. 
</P>
<P>
	During the regular season, the Bruins were 3-1-1 against the  
Maple Leafs, outscoring them 15-11. Toronto scored just one goal in 
three of the five games. 
</P>
<P>
	Against the Sabres, the Bruins were 1-4 and were dominated by  
Hasek as they scored a total of just seven goals while allowing 14. 
</P>
<P>
	But Boston finished with a flourish, going 17-6-4 in its last 27  
regular-season games before beating Carolina in a very close series 
in which two games were decided in overtime and only one was won by 
more than two goals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We thought our veteran leadership and experience in the locker  
room would be an edge for us in the series,'' Carolina's Keith 
Primeau said Sunday. ``Dafoe made saves time and time again. It 
really hurt us. Dafoe's goaltending was the difference in the 
series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last season, Boston was eliminated in the first round by  
Washington, 4-2. This time, the Bruins succeeded in pressure-filled 
games despite their playoff inexperience. 
</P>
<P>
	``This series was huge in terms of this team growing,'' Bourque  
said. ``This year having a good series and falling short wasn't 
going to be good enough.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With no dominant team in the Eastern Conference, Boston might  
have as good a chance as any to advance to the Stanley Cup finals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all have a taste of the first round,'' said Boston's Tim  
Taylor, a member of the Detroit team that lost in the 1995 
championship series. ``We're excited for a day and bask in our 
glory, but come Tuesday we have to start getting ready for 
Thursday.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
