<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FAA Wants Better Flight Recorders </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Pressured by investigators seeking more clues  
about airplane accidents, the government today called for faster 
installation of better flight recorders on Boeing 737 commercial 
jets. 
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Administration proposed requiring airlines  
to install flight data recorders, known as black boxes, that can 
track more flight functions, especially related to the rudder. The 
FAA proposal comes after the National Transportation Safety Board 
ruled that a jam in rudder-control valve caused the 1994 crash of 
USAir Flight 427 near Pittsburgh, killing all 132 people on board. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the years, flight recorders have provided a blueprint for  
deficiencies in the system that needed to be fixed,'' FAA 
Administrator Jane Garvey said at the NTSB's international 
symposium on flight data recorders that began Monday in Arlington, 
Va. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the FAA also will propose increasing the 30-minute  
recording now required on cockpit voice recorders to two hours and 
installing a 10-minute backup power supply by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	The NTSB has been asking the FAA for years to require longer  
tapes to record pilots' conversations and better flight data 
recorders, two devices that play a critical role in helping 
investigators determine the cause of accidents. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, federal regulators issued a rule ordering all U.S.  
transport airplanes -- not just 737s -- to be equipped with flight 
data recorders that could track a minimum of 17 functions. The FAA 
said the changes had to be made by August 2001. 
</P>
<P>
	Garvey said the agency now will propose additional requirements  
for newer 737s. The FAA wants to require these 737s to have flight 
data recorders that can keep information on four to 11 other flight 
functions -- beyond those covered by the 1997 ruling. And they would 
have to be installed by August 2000 -- a year sooner than those 
covered in the earlier ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	There are 3,100 Boeing 737s in the worldwide fleet.  
</P>
<P>
	Robert Frenzel, head of safety and operations for the Air  
Transport Association, which represents major U.S. airlines, said 
the association is somewhat frustrated by the changing mandates 
from the FAA. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our members have already been upgrading the parameters on the  
flight data recorders based on the previous order,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Southwest Airlines, a Dallas-based carrier, already has upgraded  
flight data recorders on 264 of the 288 737s in its fleet. 
Spokeswoman Linda Rutherford said the new recorders track 18 to 88 
parameters, depending on the plane. The proposed rule is not likely 
to require the airline to do additional retrofitting, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's our understanding that the upgrades we've done will  
either meet or exceed what the FAA is now asking,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	When the NTSB announced in March that the probable cause of the  
Sept. 8, 1994, crash of USAir Flight 427 near Pittsburgh was 
related to the rudder, the board again pressed the FAA to require 
better airline flight recorders. The board criticized the FAA for 
not mandating them until 2001. Investigators said they were 
hampered by the plane's flight data recorder that provided only 11 
pieces of information to help them determine a cause for the crash. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
