<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Umpire Hospitalized as Precaution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- Umpire Kerwin Danley was hospitalized  
overnight Monday after becoming light-headed while working home 
plate. 
</P>
<P>
	Danley left after the second inning of the Cincinnati Reds' 4-3  
victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks, walking off the field 
without assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	When a medical exam at Cinergy Field found that his blood  
pressure was high, Danley was taken to Good Samaritan Hospital for 
further tests. 
</P>
<P>
	Umpire Ed Montague, who took over behind the plate, said Danley  
has not felt well for the last few days. The umpiring crew worked a 
3-hour, 48-minute game in Montreal on Sunday and had to get up at 6 
a.m. Monday to catch a flight to Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hasn't been feeling well lately, so they want to make sure  
he's all right,'' Montague said. ``When we were in Montreal, he 
said he hadn't been feeling well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rest of the game was played with three umpires.  
</P>
<P>
	Danley, 37, worked his first National League game in 1992 and  
became an NL regular last season. 
</P>
<P>
	After Danley made it through the first inning on a 78-degree  
evening, Montague went into the umpires' dressing room to put on 
his chest protector and shin guards so he could replace him after 
the next half-inning. 
</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks catcher Damian Miller said Danley gave no  
indication to him that anything was wrong. Miller got the start 
because Kelly Stinnett became ill shortly before the game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was one of those nights, I guess,'' Miller said. ``He  
didn't say anything to me about feeling bad.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
