<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Mayor Arrested in Corruption Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A mayor and two former police officers were among  
those arrested today in a corruption case alleging they charged a 
``street tax'' to bars, restaurants and adult bookstores. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials called it the most significant case in years  
involving Chicago-area organized crime. 
</P>
<P>
	``It targets the corruption of police and public officials who  
the mob allegedly bribed,'' U.S. Attorney Scott Lassar said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indicted were Anthony T. Centracchio, an alleged mob boss; Stone  
Park Mayor Robert D. Natale; former Stone Park police Lt. Thomas R. 
Tucker and former Franklin Park officer Robert Urbinati. The men 
have pleaded not guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	A Chicago crime commission has said Centracchio is the head of  
the mob on the city's West Side and in DuPage County. 
</P>
<P>
	The Thursday federal indictment accuses the four of a conspiracy  
to put illegal gambling devices such as video poker in numerous 
west suburban bars, restaurants and fraternal clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	The indictment also says the participants imposed a ``street  
tax'' -- or charge for protection on establishments as far north as 
Wisconsin. 
</P>
</TEXT>
