<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Decide on Appeals Rules </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court said today it will use a  
California case to decide whether criminal defense lawyers have a 
duty to file appeals after their clients plead guilty. 
</P>
<P>
	The justices voted to review the case of a California man  
sentenced to 15 years to life in prison after pleading guilty in 
1993 to second-degree murder. The court documents submitted in 
Lucio Flores Ortega's case gave no details of the crime. The 
charges had been filed in Fresno County. 
</P>
<P>
	Ortega, who spoke no English, did not appeal his plea-bargained  
conviction until it was too late under state law. When he did 
appeal, California appellate courts and a federal trial judge 
turned him down. 
</P>
<P>
	But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals threw out Ortega's  
conviction last November, ruling that his public-defender lawyer 
had violated Ortega's Sixth Amendment right to adequate legal 
representation by failing to file an appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Ortega contended that in 1993 he had requested such an appeal  
within the 60-day deadline, but that the lawyer never followed 
through. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeals court ordered California authorities to release  
Ortega unless a state court re-enters a conviction and allows an 
appeal within 60 days. 
</P>
<P>
	In the appeal acted on today, state prosecutors argued that  
defense lawyers commit no constitutional error when they do not 
file appeals in behalf of clients who pleaded guilty, were informed 
of right to appeal and made no such request. 
</P>
<P>
	The appeal said other federal appeals courts have issued rulings  
in conflict with the 9th Circuit Court's ruling. 
</P>
<P>
	The case is Roe vs. Ortega, 98-1441.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0265 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 19:13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Fatal Tornado Hits Oklahoma  
</P>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- A tornado that witnesses said was at least  
a half-mile wide tore through the central part of the state 
tonight, wiping out neighborhoods and causing an unknown number of 
fatalities. Oklahoma City police dispatcher John Zondol said there 
were a few fatalities and at least 400 houses had been destroyed. 
Forecasters said the tornado would register as an F-5, the 
strongest classifications for twisters. Television reports showed 
hundreds of homes destroyed east of Oklahoma City. Heavy damage 
also was reported in Moore, east of Oklahoma City. 

</P>
<P>
	Jackson: Don't Demonize Milosevic  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Rev. Jesse Jackson returned from  
Yugoslavia today and urged President Clinton to call Slobodan 
Milosevic and release two Yugoslav prisoners of war as a goodwill 
gesture that can lead to peace. A senior administration official 
said there are no plans to meet Jackson's two requests. Upon 
returning to Washington, Jackson met with Clinton to give him the 
letter Jackson received from Milosevic in Belgrade. Jackson, 
speaking to reporters after meeting the president, did not reveal 
the letter's contents. But Jackson said Clinton did not reject his 
appeal outright, so he remains hopeful he president will respond. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton: Pause in Bombing Possible  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A U.S. official who sat in on a meeting today  
with Viktor Chernomyrdin said the Russian envoy's report on his 
talks with Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic in Belgrade last 
Friday revealed nothing that merits serious consideration. 
Chernomyrdin met with President Clinton today to urge a diplomatic 
solution to the Kosovo standoff. Clinton said ``we could have a 
bombing pause'' in Yugoslavia if Milosevic accepts NATO's demands 
for the withdrawal of his troops, the return of refugees and the 
deployment of an international security force. Chernomyrdin said 
after the meeting with Clinton that ``we got closer to a diplomatic 
solution.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Man Arrested In Colo. Shooting Case  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- The attorney for the man arrested on  
suspicion of supplying the Columbine High School gunmen with a 
semiautomatic handgun said his client knew nothing of the impending 
massacre. Mark Manes ``was horrified when it happened,'' said 
attorney Robert Ransome. Manes, 22, of Littleton, was booked for 
investigation of providing a handgun to a minor, a charges that 
carries a maximum six years in prison. He was released on bond. 
Manes, who once attended Columbine, was the first person since the 
April 20 shootings to be arrested on charges of helping Eric 
Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, arm themselves. 

</P>
<P>
	Aetna Selling Plan For Uninsured  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Aetna Inc. is launching a no-frills health  
insurance policy geared to help the 25 million working Americans 
who are uninsured. The program, called Affordable HealthChoices, 
will be sold to employers who can't afford to offer a policy to 
their workers or have had to drop the insurance benefit because of 
higher premiums. Aetna's new policy will cost as little as $46 per 
person, or $156 per family, per month. The employer can elect to 
pay all or part of the premium. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Ends Above 11,000  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average sped past  
11,000 today, shattering the record for the fastest rise between 
1,000-point milestones. The index rose 225.65 to close at 
11,014.69. It took just 24 trading days for the Dow to move from 
10,000 to 11,000. Japan's financial markets were closed Tuesday for 
Between Day, a national holiday. 

</P>
<P>
	Baltimore Embraces Cuba  
</P>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- The Baltimore Orioles did virtually everything  
possible to make the Cuban national baseball team feel at home for 
their exhibition game tonight. Latin music was played over the 
public address system, black beans and rice were served at Boog's 
Bar-B-Q Pit and a Cuban festival was staged behind the bullpen 
area. Outside the stadium, hundreds of protesters staged a peaceful 
demonstration against the two-game series, which began March 28 in 
Cuba. 

</P>
<P>
	Giants' Kent Hits for Cycle  
</P>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jeff Kent hit for the cycle in his first four  
at-bats against Pittsburgh tonight, becoming the first San 
Francisco Giants player to do so since Robby Thompson on April 22, 
1991. Kent is the 19th player in Giants' history to hit a single, 
double, triple and homer in the same game -- something Giants star 
Barry Bonds has never done. Kent singled in the first inning before 
hitting a three-run homer in the third for his first RBIs since 
April 20. He tripled to center field in the fifth and doubled down 
the left-field line in the seventh. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by SUZANNE ROWLAND  
</P>
</TEXT>
