<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 14:03:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Netanyahu: Proud To Be Riffraff </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) -- Eagerly grasping a campaign issue handed  
him by his opponents, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu surveyed 
cheering supporters Monday in a Tel Aviv slum and declared: ``I am 
proud to be riffraff.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu was responding to an actress and backer of his rival,  
Ehud Barak, who used the slur in a rally to describe Netanyahu 
voters, many of them Sephardic Jews of Middle Eastern origin. 
</P>
<P>
	The remark has ignited Israel's ethnic powder keg less than two  
weeks before May 17 elections and was expected to help Netanyahu 
revive his sluggish campaign and catch up to Barak in the polls. 
Barak's Labor Party is still closely identified with Israel's 
predominantly European-born elites. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu quickly seized actress Tiki Dayan's remarks and turned  
them into the centerpiece of his campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor leaders ``understand, of course, that this is going to  
hurt them because it reveals that they all think this way,'' 
Netanyahu told Israel army radio. 
</P>
<P>
	His Likud Party ran a TV campaign ad replaying excerpts from  
Dayan's speech, followed by footage of a smiling Barak and an 
announcer saying: ``Barak clapped, laughed and didn't say anything. 
Such a man cannot be prime minister.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Labor responded by screening some unedited footage showing that  
Barak was laughing at something else entirely. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu made an unscheduled campaign stop Monday in the  
outdoor market of the poor Hatikvah quarter, a Likud stronghold of 
Sephardic Jews, to reinforce the message. Surrounded by cheering 
vendors and shoppers, Netanyahu declared he was proud to be 
``asafsouf'' (pronounced as-af-SOOF') -- the Hebrew word for 
riffraff. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was an ugly comment,'' vendor Ezra Mizrahi, 48, said of  
Dayan's statement as he measured coffee beans into a grinder. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do you think there's no discrimination any more?'' he asked,  
his large eyes narrowing in anger as he told how his daughter was 
refused entry into a prestigious high school because of her 
Sephardic last name. 
</P>
<P>
	Sephardic Jews find it hard to forgive the Labor Party for  
mistreating waves of North African immigrants in the early years of 
the state. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Barak took the unusual step of asking for forgiveness  
from the Sephardic community for his party's wrongs. Now Labor 
campaign managers worry that one word from an actress may have 
scuttled all their efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	It was all the more maddening to the Labor activists because it  
has happened before. 
</P>
<P>
	Menachem Begin's Likud government was in serious trouble in 1981  
until an actor took a microphone at a rally and called Likud 
backers ``chach-chachim,'' Hebrew slang for roughnecks. Begin 
latched on to the ethnic issue and rode it to victory. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu narrowly won the 1996 election by putting together a  
coalition of what he said were Israel's outsiders -- Sephardic Jews, 
ultra-Orthodox Jews and Russian immigrants. Although of European 
descent himself, he presented himself as the underdog who would 
seize power from Israel's elites. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1999 campaign, he has tried to revive that coalition, but  
has run into some trouble. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak, who is also of European origin, has made inroads among  
Sephardic Jews and disappointed Likud supporters, and there is 
growing acrimony between two former Netanyahu allies, the Russian 
immigrants' party, Israel B'Aliya, and the ultra-Orthodox Shas 
Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Labor activists are trying to control the damage caused by  
Dayan's comments. They point out that she is Sephardic herself and 
has apologized. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the shopkeepers in the Hatikvah quarter agreed with  
Labor that her slip-up is being blown out of proportion. 
</P>
<P>
	But the neighborhood remains Likud territory. The people say  
they have always voted Likud. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a strong leader, we can trust him,'' said Ofer Yaacov,  
36, cutting up a chicken in his butcher shop. Barak's accusation 
that Netanyahu constantly lies doesn't bother him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone lies, that's what works today,'' he explained. ``You  
can trust him to lie to everyone.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0267 </DOCNO>
