<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:25:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Tape Figures in Marine Pilot Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A back-seat crewman on the Marine jet  
that sliced an Italian gondola cable -- killing 20 people -- 
testified today he was asked by the pilot and navigator what to do 
with a videotape shot during the flight. 
</P>
<P>
	``I said I'd get rid of it,'' Capt. Chandler Seagraves said at  
the court-martial of Capt. Richard Ashby. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagraves, who testified under immunity, was the main witness  
against Ashby, who is charged with obstruction of justice and 
conspiracy for helping his navigator get rid of the personal tape. 
</P>
<P>
	The government rested its case Monday. If convicted, Ashby, 32,  
could be sentenced to 10 years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagraves said he was approached by Ashby and navigator Capt.  
Joseph Schweitzer, 31, a few days after the mishap. Schweitzer told 
him they had taken a tape out of the crippled jet and asked what 
Seagraves thought should be done with it. 
</P>
<P>
	After Seagraves told them to dispose of it, he said Schweitzer  
told him several days later that the tape was gone. 
</P>
<P>
	Schweitzer has pleaded guilty to obstruction and conspiracy and  
was sentenced by a jury to dismissal from the Marines after 
admitting he threw the videotape into a bonfire. 
</P>
<P>
	Seagraves also testified that the four crew members met  
individually with Italian officials the day after the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	``I knew they obviously were looking into what was going on, but  
at that time, that was the least of my concerns,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors were trying to establish that Ashby knew there was a  
criminal investigation underway when he helped destroy the video. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby has admitting taking the tape from the jet, but maintains  
he didn't intend to obstruct justice because he didn't know there 
was a criminal investigation at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	Another military jury acquitted Ashby in March of 20 counts of  
involuntary manslaughter stemming from the Feb. 3, 1998 accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0269 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 16:25:22 </DATE_TIME>
