<DOCNO> APW19990503.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 10:15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Case From Starr Probe Tried </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALEXANDRIA, Va. (AP) -- A judge said today that Kathleen Willey's  
allegation of an unwanted sexual advance by President Clinton won't 
be allowed to dominate the trial of a former friend charged with 
lying about Mrs. Willey to investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	A jury and two alternates -- eight women and six men -- were  
seated in less than an hour this morning in the trial of Julie 
Hiatt Steele, whose sworn testimony in Independent Counsel Kenneth 
Starr's probe contradicted part of the story told by her one-time 
friend, Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has denied making a sexual advance to Mrs. Willey.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are not going to try Mrs. Willey,'' U.S. District Judge  
Claude Hilton warned a defense attorney while the jurors were out 
of the courtroom. ``We are not going to get into the truthfulness 
of Mrs. Willey's story.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton was responding to a complaint from Ms. Steele's lawyer,  
Nancy Luque, that she had been unable to reach witnesses who she 
believes have information undermining Mrs. Willey's credibility. 
Luque said one of those witnesses was expected to say Mrs. Willey 
herself had given false information to Starr's investigators. 
</P>
<P>
	The case against Ms. Steele, a relatively minor player in  
Starr's probe, is the only criminal trial resulting from the 
investigation that centered on the president's relationship with 
Monica Lewinsky and led to a Senate impeachment trial. 
</P>
<P>
	In addressing potential jurors, the judge noted that Ms.  
Steele's case was ``part of the investigation of ... the president 
of the United States'' and would include some mention of 
independent counsel Starr and Mrs. Willey, who told her story on 
``60 Minutes.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Starr recently suffered a stinging courtroom setback in his case  
against Susan McDougal, a figure in the Whitewater phase of his 
investigation, who planned to be on hand for the trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton has made clear he will not allow Ms. Steele's lawyers to  
put Starr's tactics on trial, as happened when Ms. Steele testified 
in support of Mrs. McDougal, a former Whitewater investment partner 
of Clinton and his wife, Hillary. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Steele's lawyer, Luque, argued before Hilton that Starr's  
prosecutors made a series of misrepresentations, designating Ms. 
Steele as a mere witness in the investigation when they actually 
regarded her as a major focus of the probe. Ms. Steele was tricked 
into making statements for which she was later indicted, her legal 
team contends. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nancy Luque told me that if she sees an opening to put Starr  
on trial, she'll call Starr as her first witness and Susan McDougal 
right behind him,'' said Geragos. 
</P>
<P>
	The defense has subpoenaed testimony and notes from Newsweek  
magazine reporter Michael Isikoff, who first wrote about Mrs. 
Willey's allegation. The defense team also issued a subpoena to CBS 
for outtakes from a ``60 Minutes'' interview with Mrs. Willey. 
</P>
<P>
	Hilton has yet to decide whether to allow that evidence into the  
case. CBS and Newsweek are seeking to quash the subpoenas. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Willey says she confided Clinton's alleged sexual advance  
to Ms. Steele, a fellow resident of the Richmond area, the day it 
occurred in 1993. Ms. Steele initially supported Mrs. Willey's 
version of events to Newsweek, then recanted, telling her revised 
account to the FBI and two grand juries. 
</P>
<P>
	She now says the first time she heard the allegation was when  
Mrs. Willey called her in 1997 and asked her to back up her story 
to Isikoff. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office has not said whether Mrs. Willey will testify,  
but Ms. Steele's lawyers are assuming that she will and are 
marshaling evidence about Mrs. Willey's background that they hope 
to use to destroy her credibility. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's office denies that and says the information from such  
witnesses has nothing to do with Mrs. Willey's accusation against 
Clinton. It says it has witnesses besides Mrs. Willey who will 
testify that Ms. Steele knew of the alleged sexual advance well 
before 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors acquitted Mrs. McDougal of a charge she obstructed  
Starr's investigation and deadlocked on two counts of criminal 
contempt for refusing to testify before a grand jury. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0281 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:34:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  'Nightingales' Nominated for Tony </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Arthur Miller, the nation's most distinguished  
living playwright, and two other titans of the American theater -- 
the late Tennessee Williams and Eugene O'Neill -- dominated 
Broadway's Tony nominations Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Their plays collected a total of 17 nominations. Williams' ``Not  
About Nightingales,'' a prison drama written more than 60 years 
ago, was nominated as best play. O'Neill died in 1953 and Williams 
in 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the first time these three men have had plays on  
Broadway at the same time,'' said Jed Bernstein, president of the 
League of American Theaters and Producers, which co-produces the 
Tony Awards. 
</P>
<P>
	The ambitious ``Parade,'' a musical that sharply divided critics  
and audiences and closed in February after a short run, received 
nine nominations, more than any other show. The musical was based 
on the true story of a 1913 murder in Georgia and the subsequent 
lynching of a Jewish man. 
</P>
<P>
	Potent productions of Miller's ``Death of a Salesman'' and  
O'Neill's ``The Iceman Cometh'' will square off for best 
revival-play, the Tony's most hotly contested category. Also up for 
the award: critically acclaimed reworkings of Sophocles ``Electra'' 
and Shakespeare's ``Twelfth Night.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Salesman'' and ``Not About Nightingales'' received six  
nominations each and ``Iceman'' took five nominations. Written in 
1938, ``Nightingales'' was not produced until it was done last year 
in England, then at Houston's Alley Theater before coming to 
Broadway. 
</P>
<P>
	``Salesman,'' ``Iceman'' and ``Nightingales'' will also face off  
in the toughest acting race, pitting Brian Dennehy, who plays Willy 
Loman in the Miller play, against Kevin Spacey of ``Iceman'' and 
Corin Redgrave, a corrupt prison warden in the Williams melodrama. 
The fourth nominee is Brian O'Byrne, playing a combative brother in 
Martin McDonagh's ``The Lonesome West.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McDonagh's black comedy also was nominated for best play along  
with Warren Leight's jazz-memory play ``Side Man.'' ``Closer,'' 
Patrick Marber's acerbic look at sex and love in the '90s, 
completes the category, although nominators snubbed all four of its 
actors, including Natasha Richardson, a winner last year for 
``Cabaret.'' 
</P>
<P>
	David Hare was the year's biggest loser. He had three new plays  
on Broadway this season, yet none was nominated. Nor was Nicole 
Kidman, star of Hare's most publicized effort, ``The Blue Room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet Hare's ``Amy's View'' is a solid box-office success, thanks  
to its star and Tony nominee for best actress, Judi Dench. She 
already has won an Oscar this year for ``Shakespeare in Love.'' 
Dench's competition on Broadway: Stockard Channing for ``The Lion 
in Winter''; Marian Seldes in ``Ring Round the Moon'' and Zoe 
Wanamaker who starred in ``Electra.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The nominations buoyed bankrupt Livent Inc., which produced not  
only ``Parade'' but another best-musical nominee, ``Fosse,'' a 
celebration of the choreography of Bob Fosse. Both shows were 
initiated by the company's former head, Garth Drabinsky, who was 
dismissed because of financial irregularities. 
</P>
<P>
	``The nominations are particularly rewarding because it has been  
such a difficult year for the company legally and financially,'' 
said Todd Haimes, Livent's artistic director. 
</P>
<P>
	Also nominated for best musical were ``The Civil War,'' Frank  
Wildhorn's pop pageant, and ``It Ain't Nothin' But the Blues,'' a 
history of the blues and the influence it has on other forms of 
music. 
</P>
<P>
	Bernadette Peters was the favorite in the musical-actress  
category for her perky portrayal of Annie Oakley in ``Annie Get 
Your Gun.'' Also nominated was Peters' co-star, Tom Wopat. The 
Irving Berlin musical received a musical-revival nomination along 
with ``Peter Pan,'' ``You're a Good Man Charlie Brown'' and 
``Little Me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wopat's challengers: Martin Short of ``Little Me''; Brent Carver  
of ``Parade,'' and Adam Cooper, who danced the lead swan in ``Swan 
Lake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The winners will be announced June 6 in a televised ceremony.  
They will be chosen by more than 800 theater professionals and 
journalists. 
</P>
<P>
	Arthur Miller, at 83, is assured of one Tony Award. Miller,  
actress Uta Hagen and Isabelle Stevenson, chairman of the American 
Theater Wing, will be given special Tonys for lifetime achievement. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990503.0282 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:34:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
