<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Federal Trial Opens Against Amway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOUSTON (AP) -- A federal trial got under way Monday in a lawsuit  
accusing Amway distributors of reviving false rumors linking rival 
Procter &AMP; Gamble with satanic cults. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit is one of many that consumer products giant Procter  
&AMP; Gamble brought after rumors began circulating in 1981 that the 
company's logo -- a bearded man on the moon and stars -- was a symbol 
of Satanism. 
</P>
<P>
	The company alleges Amway distributors, including several from  
the Houston area, revived the rumors in 1995, using a voice mail 
system to tell thousands of customers that part of Procter &AMP; 
Gamble's profits were directed to satanic cults. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a malicious lie that erodes the trust of customers and  
has cost us millions of dollars in sales,'' said Elaine Plummer, a 
spokeswoman for Procter &AMP; Gamble, which makes such products as 
Ivory soap, Tide detergent and Crest toothpaste. 
</P>
<P>
	Amway Corp., based in Ada, Mich., denies the allegations.  
</P>
<P>
	``This rumor was started in churches ... and Amway didn't have a  
thing to do with it,'' defense attorney Charles Babcock said. ``A 
few Amway independent distributors talked about the rumor -- not in 
a mean-spirited way but in an informational way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In March, a Utah federal judge dismissed a similar lawsuit  
against Amway, ruling the rumors were not defamatory and that 
Procter &AMP; Gamble hadn't made a case for specific damages. 
</P>
<P>
	The Houston trial is expected to last two weeks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
