<DOCNO> APW19990503.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-03 15:25:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Exams Delay Holdsclaw's DC Arrival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Chamique Holdsclaw isn't quite ready to join  
the Washington Mystics. Final exams come first. 
</P>
<P>
	Mystics coach Nancy Darsch on Monday confirmed the widely  
expected move -- her team will use the top pick of Tuesday's WNBA 
draft to select the two-time player of the year from Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft is especially deep, featuring college players as well  
as ones from the defunct ABL. And, clearly, Holdsclaw is the best 
one out there. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw, who wears No. 23, has had to play down claims she is  
the ``female Michael Jordan.'' The 6-foot-2 forward is projected to 
be the league's dominant player for years to come. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think eventually she will be,'' Darsch said. ``If it happens  
this summer, then I will be thankful for it. She is an extremely 
talented young lady.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The draft was postponed one week because a labor dispute between  
the players and league. Last week, the Mystics had planned to 
welcome Holdsclaw with a rally at Union Station the day after they 
selected her. 
</P>
<P>
	They were going to do the same thing this time until they  
learned Holdsclaw's final set of exams is Thursday, and she plans 
to spend all day Wednesday studying. 
</P>
<P>
	So the rally has been postponed until Friday, when she will have  
completed requirements for a political science degree to go with 
the three national championships she helped win for the Volunteers. 
</P>
<P>
	``To have an opportunity to graduate on time, and take your  
finals and get that behind you before you join your new team, that 
says a lot,'' Darsch said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw is arriving at the right time -- for herself, the  
league and the Mystics. Women's sports are enjoying a surge in 
popularity, and her marketability could earn her millions in 
endorsements in her first year alone. 
</P>
<P>
	The WNBA will benefit from a player familiar to fans, and the  
Mystics need all the talent they can get. 
</P>
<P>
	They went 3-27 last year -- thought to be the worst season record  
in pro basketball history -- yet were a big draw at the MCI Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The draft is so rich with talent that a player of first-round  
quality could be available in the third round. 
</P>
<P>
	``The good teams are going to get better; the bad teams are  
going to get better,'' Mystics general manager Wes Unseld said. 
``The thing that concerns me most is just being able to catch up. 
Even the expansion teams have an opportunity to improve very 
quickly.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
